export const entryContentById: Record<string, string> = {
  "journal-entry-may-14": "### Preparation\r\n\r\nI want to begin with the worst sentence in the book.\r\n\r\nNot the most famous one. Not the one with blood or wolves or children of the night or any of Dracula's better branding. I mean this one: Mina is a woman, and there is naught in common. They are devils of the pit.<annotation data-note=\"This sentence governs far more of the novel than it first appears to. It creates the binary through which the text sorts acceptable and unacceptable femininity.\" data-label=\"mina note\"></annotation>\r\n\r\nThat sentence had been bothering me before class because it is both absurd and terrifyingly efficient. It does not merely describe women in the novel. It arranges them. Mina on one side. Female vampires on the other. Truth, sweetness, nobility, helpfulness, modest intelligence, proper use. Then, across the line, voluptuousness, appetite, hellfire, wantonness, excess. Once the sentence is in place, the novel barely has to do any work at all. Every female character gets dragged toward one pole or the other, and every male action starts to look like an attempt to preserve the distinction.\r\n\r\nThat interested me because it also seemed to explain why the novel feels so panicked whenever women get too close to desire. Lucy cannot merely flirt. She must become a danger. Mina cannot merely be smart. She must be useful. The vampire women in the castle cannot simply be erotic. They must become demonic. This is how the machine runs. You do not need a full theory of women if you have a binary and enough confidence.\r\n\r\nI was also thinking about Mina's \"man's brain,\"<annotation data-note=\"Mina's intelligence is praised in a form that also limits it. She can be brilliant, but only if that brilliance stays compatible with service, feeling, and male authority.\" data-label=\"mans brain note\"></annotation> which is one of those backhanded compliments men in old novels give when they are trying to admire a woman without allowing her to remain fully woman. Mina is praised for intelligence, but only by being momentarily translated out of femininity. Then the novel gives her back her \"woman's heart,\" by which it really means the part of her that can be made vulnerable, sentimental, sacrificial, useful, endangered, protected, and occasionally excluded from information for her own good. Which is a very crowded little phrase.\r\n\r\nAnd then there was the question of Dracula himself. What if the male vampire is actually the novel's safer monster. What if Dracula is useful because he lets the text displace onto a male figure all the desire, fear, contamination, and appetite it does not want to see too directly in women or in men themselves. I came into class thinking that might be true. I left class thinking the book almost depends on it.\r\n\r\n### In Class\r\n\r\nClass started by putting that Mina sentence right at the center, which felt correct. The novel does not really hide its operating system. It just expects you to read fast enough not to stop and stare at it.\r\n\r\nThe key point was simple. Women in the novel are constructed through a binary opposition. Mina is the norm. The vampire women are the abnormal. Mina is true, sweet, noble, helpful, selfless, almost aggressively lacking in ego. The other women are carnal, demonic, excessive, dangerous, bodily in the wrong way, visible in the wrong way, desirous in the wrong way. Once that opposition is established, everything else in the plot becomes easier to justify. Saving Mina makes sense. Killing Lucy makes sense. Excluding women from knowledge makes sense. Men become men by defending the boundary.\r\n\r\nThat was one of the most useful class points for me, that masculinity in the novel is not standing there by itself like some independent substance. It has to be produced through women being women in the approved sense. Men need women to be sweet, true, noble, helpful, and not too egotistical. Van Helsing practically says so in the language he uses for Mina. She is valuable because she is constructed as ideal femininity with a little borrowed masculinity added for clerical purposes. She can type. She can collate. She can organize. She can think, but thankfully in a way that helps men think better. She is not allowed to become a fully autonomous center of action or knowledge without the whole arrangement starting to wobble.\r\n\r\nThat was where the \"man's brain and woman's heart\" line became especially useful. It is meant as praise, of course. It is also a reduction. Mina's intellect can be admired as long as it is masculinized and then immediately subordinated to a feminized emotional function. She is a wonderful helper. A glorious assistant. The best office manager in Gothic fiction. But once the hunt for Dracula becomes serious, the men decide she must be removed from full participation. All the knowledge, all the help, and then suddenly no, not that help, not that knowledge, not from her. She is transferred from the category of knower into the category of person-to-be-protected. Or more exactly, person-to-be-managed.\r\n\r\nThat exclusion mattered more once class put it beside Mina's actual labor in the novel. She has transcribed, organized, and collated almost everything. She has given the men the archive through which they can even imagine acting coherently. Then they turn around and tell her she must not know too much because the strain would be too much for a woman. This is one of those moments where you want to stand up in the text and begin arguing with furniture. She has already done the work. The men are just now discovering that they would prefer the worker not to become the thinker.\r\n\r\nClass also went back to Lucy, which was necessary, because Lucy is where the novel makes its example. She expresses the mildest imaginable wish for multiple lovers and gets turned into a lesson in female excess. That lesson is then medicalized, eroticized, demonized, and finally staked. We talked about the way the text prepares the reader to consent to what happens to her, and that still seems crucial to me. Lucy has to be seen as no longer Lucy. Her sweetness must visibly become cruelty. Her pure eyes must become hellfire eyes. Her body must become too much body. Once that transformation is in place, the men can act with what Seward calls \"savage delight,\" which remains one of the most revealing phrases in the novel.\r\n\r\nThat phrase came back in a stronger way this time, because class tied it more directly to masculinity. The men do not merely protect women. They bond through shared desire for women, shared fear of women, and shared violence toward women who have crossed the line from acceptable to unacceptable femininity. Arthur's staking of Lucy is one example, but the others participate too, emotionally, imaginatively, even erotically. They want to do it with him and through him. The group coheres around her destruction. That is ugly to say. The novel is ugly enough to require saying it.\r\n\r\nI thought the class was especially strong when it pushed on the idea that Dracula is, in some sense, the novel's safer monster. The female vampire makes visible what the text most fears: female desire, sensuality, appetite, initiative, pleasure without proper authorization. That is too dangerous to leave onstage for long. So Dracula becomes the more manageable figure, because he can carry desire while keeping women technically redeemable. He externalizes the threat. He allows the men, and perhaps the reader, to say the danger comes from him, not from the structures that make women's desire appear demonic in the first place.\r\n\r\nThen class made the turn into late nineteenth-century science, which was one of the best parts because it kept the novel from floating off into pure symbolism. The discussion of the book on \"the woman vampire,\"<annotation data-note=\"The term belongs to more than fiction. Late nineteenth-century medical discourse already pathologized excessive female sexuality in ways Dracula can draw on very easily.\" data-label=\"woman vampire note\"></annotation> the medical discourse around excessive female sexuality, and the pathologizing of women's desire made it clear that Stoker's imagination is not eccentric here. It is depressingly well stocked by contemporary science. The woman who wants too much, the woman who drains men, the woman whose sensuality makes her husband weak, the woman whose body is understood as open, unstable, excessive, dangerous, all of that already exists in supposedly respectable medical writing. Dracula is not inventing this. It is reorganizing and sensationalizing it.\r\n\r\nThat was where the comparison to The Yellow Wallpaper helped. Male scientific authority does not need to scream to dominate. It just needs credentials, institutional standing, and the confidence to tell a woman that her experience is not knowledge. So when Mina is sidelined, or Lucy's body becomes something to be read and managed by men, the novel is not leaving modernity behind. It is fully inside it. Hypnosis, sexology, criminology, medicine, all of those sciences are already helping structure the categories by which the novel thinks. The vampire story is modern in exactly that bad way.\r\n\r\nThe part on Dracula as \"criminal type\" and \"child-brain\" was useful too, though more chilling than surprising. The men need Dracula to become legible as a type in order to defeat him. Once you can classify him, you can predict him. That is the fantasy, anyway. Criminal anthropology, child development, degeneracy theory, all the late nineteenth-century taxonomic machinery gets dragged in to explain the vampire. But the more the class talked about it, the more it seemed that the novel is using those sciences as much to manage fear as to produce knowledge. If Dracula can be named, then the threat is containable. If the female vampire can be named, even better. The problem is the thing the text keeps circling without wanting to say: what if the real threat is not a type out there but a desire or fear already operating within the people doing the classifying.\r\n\r\n### Reflections\r\n\r\nWhat stays with me most is how hard the novel works to keep women from becoming complicated.\r\n\r\nThat sounds almost too simple, but I think it is right. Mina must become idealized so that she can be protected. Lucy must become demonized so that she can be destroyed. The vampire women must become devils so that nobody has to wonder too long what is actually being desired in their presence. The categories are not subtle. What is subtle is the amount of labor required to keep them functioning.\r\n\r\nMina is the clearest case. The novel wants her abilities. It needs them. Then it wants to deny what those abilities would mean if taken seriously. She becomes a machine for transcription, synthesis, and moral encouragement. She is allowed intelligence as long as it circulates under the sign of service. That is why I cannot quite take the praise of her at face value. \"One of God's women\" sounds exalted. It also sounds like a sentence you say when you need someone to remain very useful and very bounded. She is fashioned for a purpose. Fine. The question is whose purpose.\r\n\r\nLucy, on the other hand, is punished for being too available to life. That is what I think the novel cannot forgive. She is flirtatious, open, desired, slightly unserious about monogamy, capable of pleasure, susceptible to altered states, and not disciplined enough to transform all of that immediately into help for some man's project. So she becomes the novel's object lesson. But even then the text cannot quite stop itself from making her too attractive, too vivid, too charged. Which is why the men need so much language to turn her from woman into thing. They do not simply kill Lucy. They spend pages teaching themselves how to say she is killable.\r\n\r\nAnd that, maybe, is the ugliest thing in the book. Violence requires rhetoric. The stake through the heart does not happen in a vacuum. It is prepared by purity language, devil language, monster language, restoration language. Lucy must first be made into a category. Then the act can look like duty. I think that is what class helped me see most clearly this time. The novel is not merely full of violence. It is full of the production of justifying language around violence.\r\n\r\nI also think the homosocial part matters more than the novel wants to admit. These men are bound together through women, yes, but also through each other's relation to women. They desire, fear, protect, narrate, and destroy in company. Arthur does not stake Lucy alone in any meaningful sense. The others watch, endorse, and in some ways participate. Van Helsing jokes about polyandry because the men have already been bound together through Lucy's body and blood. The novel keeps trying to keep all this straight, clean, and medical. It does not quite manage it. Good.\r\n\r\nSo I suppose the question I am left with is whether Dracula is really the central monster at all. He is certainly convenient. He gives the novel a focal point for fear. He brings the East westward, carries plague, animates female sensuality, all the usual excellent vampire services. But the deeper horror may be the ordinary social order that needs him in order to keep itself from seeing what it is doing. The book can say: he made Lucy this way. He stained Mina. He corrupts women. He threatens men. Much harder to say: the society in the book already had a whole apparatus ready for classifying women, disciplining desire, and turning fear into sanctioned violence.\r\n\r\nThat answer is less satisfying than \"kill the vampire and save the woman.\" Which is probably why the novel prefers the other one.",
  "journal-entry-may-12": "### Preparation\r\n\r\nI want to begin with Lucy wanting blood.\r\n\r\nThat sentence sounds ridiculous until you remember that in this novel ridiculous things are usually just important things wearing a worse outfit. When Van Helsing says, \"Young miss is bad, very bad. She wants blood,\" the line seems medical at first. Lucy is weak. She has lost blood. She needs blood. Fine. Straightforward enough. The trouble is that about fifty pages later wanting blood means something very different, and suddenly the same desire that once marked her as fragile marks her as monstrous.<annotation data-note=\"The novel keeps trying to speak of blood transfusion as treatment while also loading it with erotic and symbolic force. It never fully stabilizes into either register.\" data-label=\"blood note\"></annotation> That shift had been bothering me before class, because it made clear that the novel is not only interested in blood as substance. It is interested in blood as desire, as intimacy, as class essence, as sexuality, as inheritance, as whatever Victorian men become nervous around and therefore rename.\r\n\r\nI was also thinking about Lucy and Mina as a pair, because the novel has been arranging them a little too efficiently for comfort. Mina learns shorthand, studies for usefulness, helps Jonathan, transcribes, organizes, serves, in the flattering sense and the more troubling one. Lucy likes being wanted. Lucy likes being alive. Lucy says the quiet part out loud and wonders why a woman should not marry three men if three men want her.<annotation data-note=\"Lucy jokingly wonders why a woman cannot marry multiple men. The text later turns that playful wish into a darker structure through the multiple transfusions and Van Helsing's awful joke.\" data-label=\"polyandry note\"></annotation> It is the sort of sentence that makes a modern reader like her more and the novel trust her less. Which already tells you something.\r\n\r\nAnd then there was the abattoir painting and the women drinking blood, which class had brought in. That image stayed with me because it made the question of blood suddenly material in a way Dracula often tries to mystify. Here are women being told to drink blood for health. Here are doctors recommending it. Here are working-class men covered in the labor and violence that make such nourishment possible. Here, in other words, is the whole system before the vampire enters and makes it melodramatic. That mattered to me because it suggested that the novel's blood obsession is not only symbolic or erotic. It sits inside real nineteenth-century medical fantasies about women's bodies, weakness, menstruation, replenishment, nervous disorders, all of it. Which is to say, the Gothic is once again doing very little that respectable science was not already doing in a cleaner font.\r\n\r\nSo I came into class with three questions. First, why does blood move so easily between medicine and sexuality in this novel. Second, why does Lucy's desire become the thing that must be killed. Third, what exactly makes Mina \"good\" besides being useful to men in a way the text finds soothing.\r\n\r\n### In Class\r\n\r\nClass began with the painting, which turned out to be the right ugly doorway into the problem.\r\n\r\nThe main question there was coercion. The women are present at the slaughterhouse, yes, but what does presence mean. Are they choosing freely. Are they following medical advice. Are they being escorted into a scene whose violence they are supposed to accept because it is good for them. That discussion helped because it immediately widened the frame beyond Dracula and into the institutional authority of medicine itself. Women are told what their bodies need by men whose knowledge arrives backed by science, credentials, and the social confidence that comes from occupying the right role. That mattered because it gave the whole blood question a much less romantic setting. Before Lucy becomes a vampire, women are already being asked to ingest blood under male supervision in the name of health. That is a horrifying sentence. It is also, apparently, medicine.\r\n\r\nFrom there class moved into the language of women and blood more directly. The point was not only that nineteenth-century medicine links women to blood, but that it does so through a whole structure of assumptions about menstruation, weakness, nervous susceptibility, hysteria, and open bodily economies. Men are closed systems. Women are porous. Men expend. Women lose. Men think. Women drift toward symptoms. I am compressing rudely, but not unfairly. That was useful because it clarified how Dracula can take the ordinary medical preoccupation with women's blood and make it Gothic without really having to invent much. Stoker just adds a vampire and some weather.\r\n\r\nLucy then came back into focus. Van Helsing's remark that she is \"very bad\" because she wants blood sounds diagnostic, but the whole class was really about how unstable that diagnosis is. At first the wanting is passive. She needs blood because it has been taken from her. So the men rally, nobly, theatrically, and with more erotic energy than they seem to realize. Arthur first, because aristocratic blood is, apparently, best blood. Then Seward. Then the Texas man. Then Van Helsing's older blood. Every man gets his turn. Which is already awkward enough before the novel itself starts making jokes about it.\r\n\r\nArthur's response after the first transfusion was one of the strongest moments of class. He feels that Lucy is \"really his wife in the sight of God\" because his blood is now within her. The text could not be less subtle if it tried, though I suspect it is trying very hard. Blood here becomes a form of marriage, possession, union, erotic transmission, class continuity, spiritual sealing, all under the cover of medical necessity. That is why Van Helsing's polyandry joke later is so awful and also so revealing. Lucy had already proposed, lightly, that a woman ought to be able to marry multiple men. The novel first treats that as charming impropriety, then enacts it symbolically through transfusion, and finally punishes her for it. The joke lands because the book has been constructing Lucy as multiply entered long before she becomes the \"bloofer lady.\" It is horrible. It is also structurally neat in the worst way.\r\n\r\nThe contrast with Mina sharpened everything. Van Helsing talks about Mina as one of God's women,<annotation data-note=\"Mina's intelligence is praised because it is useful, organized, and directed toward male projects. The novel rewards female competence once it stays within serviceable bounds.\" data-label=\"good woman note\"></annotation> and the compliment sounds noble for about five seconds before you notice what it really means. She is good because she helps. She studies what Jonathan studies. She types. She organizes. She makes \"good lessons\" for future children. She is intelligent, yes, but her intelligence is fully acceptable because it has been directed toward service. That was the key class point. The novel has room for competent women as long as that competence stabilizes male projects and does not generate too much desire of its own. Mina gets to be brilliant because she is useful. Lucy gets to be lovely until loveliness starts wanting things.\r\n\r\nI thought the class was especially sharp on Lucy's sleepwalking experience too. Mina's description of Lucy's trance, the black figure, the bitter sweetness, the drifting soul, the sinking away, reads like something halfway between violation and ecstasy. The novel later insists on one reading. The language itself resists staying that obedient. Lucy's experience carries too much sensation, too much openness, too much pleasure and terror intermingled, for the later moral sorting to feel stable. Which is why the text needs to work so hard once she changes. It has to make her visibly other. Her eyes must become unclean. Her lips voluptuous in a bad way. Her sweetness must turn to cruel appetite. The book needs her readable as monster because otherwise the men are just killing a woman whose desires got too alive for their comfort.\r\n\r\nThat scene with the transformed Lucy was probably the center of the class. Once the men encounter her in the tomb with the child, the language becomes almost embarrassingly heavy-handed. She is voluptuous, wanton, demonic, smiling in a way that horrifies them, and Arthur moves from love to hate with astonishing speed. That speed mattered. The class kept returning to it, and rightly. What changes so fast is not simply Lucy. The men's permission structure changes. Once the woman can be seen as impure, everything becomes possible. Violence now looks like restoration. Murder becomes rescue. Desecration becomes purity. That is the darkest trick the novel pulls, and it pulls it openly.\r\n\r\nI was glad class slowed down over Seward's line that had Lucy needed killing, he could have done it with \"savage delight.\"<annotation data-note=\"Seward's phrase matters because it reveals how quickly protective violence can become pleasurable once Lucy has been reclassified as impure or monstrous.\" data-label=\"savage delight note\"></annotation> It is one of those sentences that sounds like it should destroy the moral arrangement of the whole scene. It does not, because the novel keeps hurrying us forward. Class refused to hurry. Good. Savage delight is not a neutral little phrase. It is the whole point, almost. The men tell themselves they are defending innocence, but the energy with which they move toward violence reveals something much less innocent. Lucy's destruction allows desires the novel cannot otherwise admit, rage, mastery, penetration, group solidarity, the thrill of sanctioned violence, all to gather under the sign of purification.\r\n\r\nThen hypnosis came in, which was a good reminder that the novel is not just full of old superstition but of new sciences that are every bit as strange. Charcot, hysteria, the staged female body, the doctor interpreting while the woman writhes or collapses or speaks symptoms she does not control, this all helped make Van Helsing's authority feel much less stable to me. He is not simply the man of knowledge against chaos. He is one more man inside a modern regime that turns women's experience into spectacle, evidence, case, and diagnosis. Dracula is creepy. So are the scientific structures ranged against him. The novel knows this sometimes and then forgets it quickly.\r\n\r\n### Reflections\r\n\r\nWhat stays with me most is that the novel's category of \"good woman\" is much narrower than its admirers usually admit.\r\n\r\nMina is good because she is clever in the right direction. She learns the technologies of modernity, shorthand, typing, organization, collation, but does so in order to support male effort. Her intelligence does not threaten the arrangement. It lubricates it. Lucy, by contrast, is harder to place because she enjoys being wanted and says so, because she lets desire become visible without immediately translating it into duty, because even her passivity, sleepwalking, openness, receptivity, carries too much charge. She does not become monstrous because she is morally worse than Mina. She becomes monstrous because the novel needs a woman onto whom its anxiety about female desire can be projected at full scale.\r\n\r\nAnd blood is the perfect medium for that anxiety because it never stays in one register. It is bodily and symbolic, scientific and erotic, sacred and filthy, life-giving and contaminating. The men in the novel keep trying to manage those meanings by professionalizing them. This is medicine. This is treatment. This is duty. This is science. Yet the text itself keeps sabotaging that effort. Arthur feels married through transfusion. Seward feels pride and tenderness in watching his blood enter the woman he loves. Van Helsing jokes about polyandry at a funeral. These are not accidents. The novel cannot keep blood clean because blood is exactly the thing that reveals the failure of cleanliness as a fantasy.\r\n\r\nI also think the class was right to make coercion a larger issue than just Dracula's bite. The women in the slaughterhouse painting, the women under medical advice, the women under male supervision, the hypnotized woman in the clinic, Lucy in the tomb, all of these scenes involve women's bodies being interpreted, directed, handled, narrated, or corrected by male authority. Dracula is one version of that authority, the obscene one. Van Helsing and company are another, the legitimate one. The novel clearly wants me to prefer the second. Fine. I do. But preference is not innocence. The men who save Lucy do so by deciding what Lucy now is, and once they have decided, the rest follows with frightening ease.\r\n\r\nThis is part of why I cannot quite hate Van Helsing. He is too funny, too resourceful, too convenient, too Dutchly omniscient. But I also do not trust him. He moves across medicine, folklore, hypnosis, Catholic objects, science, pseudoscience, practical rescue, mystical authority, and male emotional management with absurd confidence. He is a one-man interdisciplinary center for killing the wrong kind of woman. That is both narratively efficient and morally suspicious.\r\n\r\nSo I think the question I am left with is not whether Lucy becomes a monster. Of course the novel says she does. The more interesting question is what cultural work that transformation performs. What gets clarified, secured, purified, or redistributed once she becomes killable. The answer, I think, is: male solidarity, sexual panic, the distinction between proper and improper femininity, the usefulness of Mina, the expendability of Lucy, and the possibility of imagining violence as moral hygiene.\r\n\r\nThat is not a comforting answer. Good. Comfort has not been behaving especially well in this book.",
  "journal-entry-may-7": "### Preparation\r\n\r\nI want to begin with Budapest, because apparently once you move east of it the food gets spicy, the trains get unreliable, the peasants get superstitious, and modern English self-confidence starts sweating through its collar.\r\n\r\nThat is Jonathan Harker's version, anyway.\r\n\r\nBefore class, what stayed with me most was how quickly Harker turns geography into judgment. He does not simply travel east. He travels backward. That is how he wants to understand it.<annotation data-note=\"Harker does not describe a neutral geography. He turns spatial difference into civilizational difference and then into temporal difference, as though traveling east also means traveling backward into an older world.\" data-label=\"east west note\"></annotation> The East becomes a place where time itself has thickened, where old customs persist, where people still wear crucifixes as though objects might actually do something, where clocks are less decisive, where wolves are somehow too wolfy, and where dinner, fatally, contains seasoning. It is a very English way of being frightened by a menu.\r\n\r\nI was also thinking about the crucifix, because Harker's relation to it seemed more interesting than the usual \"rational man meets superstition\" version. He calls it superstitious, yes, but what exactly is being named there?<annotation data-note=\"His discomfort with the crucifix is specifically Protestant. The issue is not religion in general but a material sacred object treated as effective rather than merely symbolic.\" data-label=\"crucifix note\"></annotation> The peasant woman gives him the crucifix because she thinks it has efficacy, not because it is a pretty symbol or a tasteful bit of devotional jewelry. Harker comes from a Protestant world where sacred objects are supposed to have been drained of that kind of dangerous material potency. So the issue is not merely religion in general. It is one form of Christianity finding another embarrassingly too physical, too enchanted, too attached to objects. That matters because the whole novel is about things crossing boundaries they are not supposed to cross, blood, nations, bodies, genders, desires, East and West, all of it. The crucifix is just the first annoying little object that refuses to stay symbolic.\r\n\r\nAnd then, of course, the women. You always know things are going badly in these books when a man starts describing women in terms that sound like he found them in a perfume ad written by a theologian. Voluptuous lips, white teeth, wicked longing, deadly fear.<annotation data-note=\"A danger word in this novel. It marks the point where male fear of women becomes visible as fear of one's own desire. Whenever the word appears, trouble is already in the room.\" data-label=\"voluptuous note\"></annotation> I knew before class that the three women in Dracula's castle would matter, but what interested me was not simply that they are seductive. It was that Harker seems far more comfortable narrating them as demonic excess than admitting how much he wants them. This is a recurring male strategy in the Gothic, and also, unfortunately, outside the Gothic.\r\n\r\nSo I came into class mostly wondering about three things. First, how does Harker's \"East\" get constructed as a fantasy rather than a place. Second, what exactly makes these women terrifying to him. Third, why does the novel seem so invested in dividing women into Mina on one side and devils of the pit on the other, as though that could possibly hold.\r\n\r\n### In Class\r\n\r\nClass began with introductions and conclusions, which I appreciated more than I initially expected, partly because it is useful to be told that an introduction should not begin at the dawn of time, and partly because \"Merriam-Webster defines...\" really should be illegal by now. The practical advice was good: begin with the world, move toward the question, arrive at the claim; then reverse the motion in the conclusion, moving back out from the claim into the larger world it opens. That felt almost suspiciously elegant, which is perhaps why it works. I also liked the point that an argument is not \"this paper will discuss...\" but the answer to the question you have actually posed. It sounds obvious. It is also exactly the sort of thing students, meaning all of us at one point or another, manage to avoid hearing until someone says it with enough force.\r\n\r\nThen Dracula.\r\n\r\nThe first important thing class did was make the East into a problem of construction rather than a map fact. Harker capitalizes East and West, which is already a warning sign, since capital letters in travel writing are usually how empires smuggle fantasy into geography. He experiences himself as leaving the modern West and entering an older, stranger world. But that difference is not self-evident. It is produced through his observations, or more precisely through the way he interprets his observations: food, clocks, clothing, religion, peasant customs, wolves, darkness, all of it gets folded into a single fantasy of belatedness. East becomes what the West thinks it has already overcome. That is why the trains matter. A late train becomes cultural evidence. A cross becomes a symptom of civilizational lag. Paprika becomes destiny.\r\n\r\nClass was especially good on the religious point. When Harker calls the crucifix \"superstitious,\" he is not just declaring himself secular or rational. He is making a Protestant judgment on a more materially invested religious world. The difference here is not belief versus nonbelief. It is one set of sacramental assumptions encountering another. Does a sacred object actually do anything. Does holy water matter. Does the host mean flesh or only signify it. These are not tiny questions in Christian history, and Stoker knows that. The novel enters through them. Dracula is scary partly because he appears in a world where the things modern Englishmen have been trained to treat as obsolete embarrassments suddenly work. That is a nasty little reversal. It also explains why Harker keeps wanting to dismiss local knowledge and then immediately needing it. The \"superstitious\" people keep surviving longer than the modern man with his notebook.\r\n\r\nI also liked the point that Harker is not simply traveling east in space. He feels as though he is traveling into an earlier time. That is what tourism, colonial writing, and a lot of bad anthropology tend to do. They turn difference in space into difference in historical development. Those people are not merely elsewhere. They are earlier. That move allows the metropolitan observer to feel not only different but superior. Which is useful if you run an empire and less useful if you are about to become dinner.\r\n\r\nThen we got to Dracula himself, who is immediately more interesting than Harker, which is rude but true. The relationship between them begins in hierarchy, not intimacy. Dracula treats Harker as a clerk, a functionary, a servant of other men's property and papers. Harker arrives thinking he is conducting business in a foreign castle. Dracula immediately understands the deeper arrangement: one aristocrat dealing with the employee of another world. That mismatch matters because it exposes how vulnerable Harker is before anything overtly supernatural has happened. He is socially overmatched before he is metaphysically threatened.\r\n\r\nAnd then the line about Harker not daring to confess his thoughts even to his own soul. Class was right to stay on that. \"I doubt; I fear; I think strange things, which I dare not confess to my own soul.\" The sentence effectively creates two Jonathans, the one thinking and the one policing thought, with \"the soul\" functioning like a little internal moral customs office trying to stop prohibited feelings at the border. That felt important because the novel keeps staging desire as something that must first be denied internally before it can be blamed externally. Harker is already repressing himself before the women even arrive. They just make the whole operation harder to maintain.\r\n\r\nThe women in Dracula's room were probably the center of the class for me, because they make the book's gender logic so indecently obvious. Harker imagines the old room as once occupied by fair ladies writing blush-filled love letters, which is already funny in a sad way, because he is basically fantasizing a museum diorama of femininity right before actual women show up and ruin it by wanting something. Then the three women arrive, two dark, one fair, all teeth and lips and voluptuousness, and Harker gives us that amazing confession: he feels a \"wicked, burning desire\" that they should kiss him. He then immediately apologizes to Mina in advance, which is one of the most Victorian and least convincing gestures in world literature. Sir, you are not sorry. You are narrating. Those are different activities.\r\n\r\nThe crucial point from class was that the women force a binary into place for the rest of the novel. Mina is a woman. These are \"devils of the pit.\" That distinction, once made, structures everything that happens later to Lucy. Women in the novel do not get to be complex moral beings for very long. They tend to be sorted into proper womanhood or predatory monstrosity, virtue or appetite, assistance or danger. Lucy's tragedy, in that sense, is that she is too alive for the first category and too vulnerable to avoid the second. Harker's experience with the three women gives the novel its panic-template.\r\n\r\nLucy got even more interesting once class put her beside Mina directly. Mina works, studies shorthand, learns for usefulness, wants to help Jonathan professionally, a very efficient proto-clerical wife, almost an honorary office machine with feelings. Lucy, by contrast, is looser, more playful, more openly desirous. She gets three proposals and dares to write that she wishes women could marry three men or as many as want them. That line is light and funny and also, from the novel's point of view, probably treason. Lucy enjoys attention too visibly. She thinks desire in plural. She does not stay within the neat managed channel Mina seems willing to accept. It is not difficult to guess which one the text will punish.\r\n\r\nThe sleepwalking passage mattered a lot too. Mina's account of Lucy's strange experience, the long black figure, the sea-like sensation, the drifting soul, the bitter and sweet feeling, reads almost like ecstatic description before the novel teaches us to read it as violation. Class did a good job keeping that tension open. If you encountered that passage outside Dracula, it could register as possession, yes, but also as erotic transport, trance, mystical experience, psychedelic unselfing, the whole unstable zone where sensation outruns the moral vocabulary assigned to it. Lucy's problem, in a sense, is that she experiences too much without the proper interpretive guardrails in place. The novel does not like that. The novel likes women whose inner lives can be translated quickly into serviceable categories.\r\n\r\nThen Van Helsing appeared, which is always narratively convenient because he is essentially a Dutch humanities department, a medical faculty, a folklore archive, and a weird uncle with a bag of garlic all rolled into one. His solution to Lucy's blood loss, transfusion, turned out to be far more charged than the book initially pretends. Arthur's blood is prized because of his strength, youth, aristocratic value, the whole blue-blood metaphysics of class. Blood here is not merely medical substance. It is essence, inheritance, sex, family, social worth, all under cover of scientific procedure.<annotation data-note=\"Dracula treats blood as bodily substance, medical necessity, class essence, and erotic medium all at once. That is why the transfusions are so overcharged even when the men pretend they are only being practical.\" data-label=\"blood note\"></annotation> So when Lucy begins filling up with the blood of multiple men, the novel is already playing with a kind of sanctioned polyandry before it starts making jokes about it. Which is why Van Helsing laughing about polyandry later is so horrible and so revealing. They have already been doing it in the only acceptable way: medically, heroically, and with men supervising the exchange.\r\n\r\n### Reflections\r\n\r\nWhat keeps staying with me is that Dracula seems to organize fear by first organizing desire.\r\n\r\nThat is, the book does not simply say here is the monster, now be afraid. It first gives us a whole set of desires and uncertainties the men in the text can barely admit, then hands them an object onto which those disturbances can be projected. The East becomes dangerous because it seems older, looser, more enchanted, less disciplined by the categories Harker trusts. The women become dangerous because they want with insufficient shame. Lucy becomes dangerous because she is too open to multiple forms of attachment. Blood becomes dangerous because it reveals how intimate men already are under the sign of rescuing her. Dracula, in that sense, does not invent the crisis. He animates one that is already there.\r\n\r\nI also think the text is very worried about mediation. Harker writes in shorthand. Mina transcribes. Letters cross distances. Diaries accumulate. Sacred objects matter or do not. Blood travels from body to body. People keep trying to secure experience by recording it, exchanging it, categorizing it. That is one reason the novel feels so modern in spite of all the castles and wolves. Everyone is documenting, transferring, processing, filing, trying to get ahead of whatever is entering the system. It is a vampire novel run like an office in a panic. Which, honestly, is a good premise.\r\n\r\nThe Mina-Lucy contrast still bothers me, though, because it is too useful for the novel and therefore too suspicious for me. Mina is intelligence disciplined into usefulness. Lucy is charm loosened into danger. That is not entirely fair to either of them, but it is very much how the book wants the moral field arranged. Lucy's wishes, multiple suitors, strange sleep, ecstatic bodily experience, make her vulnerable not only to Dracula but to the novel's need to turn female desire into a cautionary tale. Mina's competence, by contrast, stays protected as long as it remains in service to male survival and interpretation. This is a rotten arrangement. The novel knows it enough to make it interesting, though not enough to escape it.\r\n\r\nAnd I think the blood is where all of this gets most embarrassing for the men involved. They want transfusion to mean rescue, duty, masculine sacrifice, pure medical necessity. Fair enough. It is also intensely intimate, bodily, mingling, and impossible to keep wholly separate from the sexual logic the novel claims to manage. Blood keeps ruining distinctions the men would like to preserve. Medicine and desire. Class and substance. Purity and mixture. Friendship and bodily penetration. No wonder Van Helsing keeps talking so much. If I were in that novel, I too would become suspiciously verbose whenever the topic got close to what everyone was actually doing.\r\n\r\nSo I think what I am left with after this class is the sense that Dracula is much less stable than its later iconography lets it seem. You think you are entering a book about a clearly marked villain with fangs and a cape and maybe some nice cheekbones. Instead, you enter a book about anxious men, badly managed categories, religious objects that keep becoming real at inconvenient moments, women who are either too proper or too much alive, and a whole civilization terrified that what it has called outside may already be circulating within.",
  "journal-entry-may-5": "### Preparation\r\n\r\nI want to begin with the cry.\r\n\r\nNot the law, not the island, not even Moreau doing his usual god-complex routine in a lab coat. The cry. Before class, what stayed with me most was Prendick's distinction between the crying of the puma and the crying he later identifies as human. He wants the distinction badly. You can feel that. It matters to him that one sound belong to \"animal pain\" and the other to \"human torment,\" as though the whole ethical order of the world depends on keeping those categories from bleeding into each other. But the novel itself seemed less convinced. Or, maybe, less polite.\r\n\r\nWhat bothered me was the idea that suffering only becomes unbearable once it finds a voice. Prendick more or less says so. If the pain had remained dumb, he could have stood it better. That is one of those sentences that sounds revealing in ways the speaker probably does not intend. It suggests that people are often perfectly capable of tolerating cruelty as long as the cruelty does not address them. Pain can exist nearby. What becomes intolerable is the demand it makes when it enters perception as something speakable, or at least audible. That felt larger than Moreau's island very quickly.\r\n\r\nI was also already thinking about geography, because class clearly wanted us to. The novel has two islands, not one. There is England and there is Moreau's island in the Pacific.<annotation data-note=\"The island works as a colonial space because pain is inflicted at the periphery while knowledge and authority remain oriented toward the metropolitan center. England is never absent from the experiment.\" data-label=\"colonial allegory note\"></annotation> That mattered to me because once you say it that way, the whole book begins to shift. A disgraced English scientist flees to a distant island, performs violent experiments on living creatures, and produces a broken social order justified by \"law.\" That is not just weird science. That is colonial weird science, which is worse because it is recognizable. The island stops being only a Gothic or speculative space and starts looking like an exaggerated version of what empires actually do: export pain, import knowledge, and then act surprised when the results do not remain docile.\r\n\r\nAnd then there was the phrase \"the House of Pain,\"<annotation data-note=\"More than a location. It is the novel's governing principle for Moreau's science: living beings are remade through inflicted suffering, and that suffering is treated as both obstacle and instrument.\" data-label=\"house of pain note\"></annotation> which is so dramatic that it should almost be embarrassing, except the book earns it. The Beast People recite the law in order to keep themselves human, or human-ish, or at least non-beastly according to Moreau's categories, and the law is built almost entirely out of prohibitions. Not to go on all fours. Not to suck up drink. Not to chase men. It sounds half ridiculous, half terrifying, and exactly like the sort of legal order a man would invent if he thought personhood could be produced through enough disciplined renunciation. Which, to be fair, is not only Moreau's problem.\r\n\r\nSo before class my main questions were these: what does the novel think pain does to language, what does colonialism have to do with Moreau's experiment, and why does \"becoming human\" here sound so much like learning a set of punishments by heart.\r\n\r\n### In Class\r\n\r\nClass began with the geography, and I was glad it did, because the island gets stranger the moment it stops being alone.\r\n\r\nThe first important point was that there are really two islands, England and the Pacific island, and the relation between them matters. Moreau is not simply some isolated madman who has invented cruelty from scratch. He is an English scientist who has moved imperial violence offshore. Once class framed it as a colonial allegory, the novel became much easier to see and much harder to excuse. A metropolitan intellectual gets disgraced at home, relocates to the colonial periphery, and there conducts experiments on bodies whose pain will never have to interrupt the social life of the people who benefit from the knowledge. That seems less like fantasy and more like a summary with tropical weather.\r\n\r\nThe cry came next. We looked closely at Prendick's reaction to the puma's suffering, especially the claim that if the pain had been \"dumb\" he could have endured it more easily. Class kept worrying that sentence in exactly the right way. What makes suffering ethically difficult here is not only the suffering itself but the way it becomes voiced. A cry produces obligation, or at least disturbance. It gets through the little protective stories one tells oneself about necessity, science, progress, and all the other professional words people use when they are trying not to listen too hard. That was one of the strongest ideas from class: pain unmakes the sufferer's world, yes, but it also threatens the observer's world if the observer actually hears it.\r\n\r\nFrom there, the move to torture and language felt inevitable. Pain attacks speech. It reduces the body toward screams, groans, silence, the breakdown of articulate selfhood. That was where the Douglass comparison mattered. Violence is not only physical injury. It is an attack on a person's ability to inhabit language and make meaning through it. Moreau's whole project depends on that kind of violence. He wants to cut, reshape, train, and discipline living beings into new forms. The \"House of Pain\" is therefore not just a place where bodies are altered. It is a place where subjectivity is assaulted at its own basis. That sounds abstract. The novel makes it ugly enough to keep it from becoming merely abstract.\r\n\r\nThen we got to Moreau's defense of himself, which is one of those speeches that make you admire a novel for giving such a terrible person such coherent logic. His big idea is plasticity, the infinite plasticity of living forms,<annotation data-note=\"Moreau's key term. It names the supposedly limitless mutability of living forms. The novel keeps asking whether what he calls 'plasticity' is really only life viewed from the angle of domination.\" data-label=\"plasticity note\"></annotation> and the thing that prevents transformation, according to him, is pain. Pain interrupts the remaking of the body. Pain drags the creature back toward animal resistance, toward instinct, toward unshaped life. So from his point of view, cruelty is not incidental to his science. It is the obstacle he is trying to overcome and the means by which he tries to overcome it. This is a very clean argument if you are a sadistic colonial scientist and a very bad one if you are anyone else.\r\n\r\nI liked the question class kept raising there: what if pain is not the obstacle to the full realization of life but the sign of a being's refusal to be remade for someone else's purposes. That felt like the ethical center of the discussion. Moreau treats pain as a technical inconvenience, or as a primitive weakness to be burned out. The class kept pulling it back toward the fact that aversion to pain may be one of the clearest signs that a living being is not raw material. That seems obvious once you say it. It also seems like the sort of obvious thing empires, labs, and states spend a lot of time teaching themselves not to say.\r\n\r\nThe law of the Beast People became much more interesting after that. \"Sayers of the Law\" is such a good chapter title, because it makes clear that these creatures do not author the law. They recite it. They are not legislators. They are repeaters. And the law itself is all \"nots,\" a sequence of prohibitions that define humanity negatively: what one must no longer do, how one must no longer move, eat, drink, pursue, or crouch.<annotation data-note=\"The Beast People's law is almost entirely prohibitive. That matters because it defines 'the human' as a disciplined refusal of animal behavior rather than as a positive form of flourishing.\" data-label=\"law note\"></annotation> This helped clarify something I had only half seen while reading: Moreau's version of \"the human\" is not a positive condition. It is a disciplinarian ideal created through suppression. Humanity here is not flourishing. It is managed abstention with a bad whip behind it.\r\n\r\nThat led to the colonial question again. Class was especially good on the possibility that the Beast People's recitation of law might look, from Moreau's angle, like mere mimicry, but mimicry is never simple. Colonized people can adopt forms, institutions, laws, languages, habits, and then use them in ways imperial power did not fully predict. The text itself is not generous enough to let that possibility flourish for long, but it opens it just enough to matter. When the Beast People say after Moreau's death that they love the Law and will keep it though there is no Master and no House of Pain, they seem, briefly, to imagine a version of order not grounded in immediate violence. The novel then more or less crushes that possibility, but class was right to pause there. One can feel an alternative world flicker and then get shut down.\r\n\r\nPrendick's response to that shutdown was also revealing. He does not merely fear the reversion of the Beast People. He becomes preoccupied with extermination, with the need to destroy them before they reproduce, before ambiguity spreads, before the line between human and animal gets any worse than it already is. That felt horrible in exactly the way it should. Class pushed this toward colonial language pretty directly: the fear of mixed forms, of proliferating difference, of beings who are neither one thing nor another in a way power can comfortably classify. The novel wants that fear on the page. It also, I think, wants us to notice how fear quickly becomes exterminatory when categories fail.\r\n\r\nThe bit about the female Beast People was especially telling. What disgusts Prendick most is not only general reversion but a certain kind of sexual or social impropriety, \"public outrages upon the institution of monogamy,\" which is such a wonderfully pompous phrase for what is basically him being scandalized that beings he does not recognize as properly human are refusing the script of respectable social order. That fit perfectly with the broader point class was making. The \"human\" here is inseparable from a whole package of norms: posture, diet, speech, sexuality, domestic arrangement, decency, all the usual suspects. The horror is not just animality. It is social noncompliance.\r\n\r\nAnd then we ended, or nearly ended, with the biggest question of all: what makes the human distinct at all. The class pushed on this through Prendick's own inability to keep the categories separate, through philosophy, through animal suffering, through the very weak distinction between \"the black-faced man\" and \"the black\" earlier in the novel. Prendick racializes what he sees almost immediately, which means his supposedly scientific or observational language is never innocent. He does not discover difference neutrally. He imposes systems of legibility that come preloaded with hierarchy. That felt like one of the most important undercurrents of the whole discussion. The human/animal split in the book is never just about species. It gets entangled with race, empire, class, and discipline almost as soon as anyone begins describing bodies.\r\n\r\n### Reflections\r\n\r\nWhat I keep returning to is how much of this novel depends on denying relation.\r\n\r\nMoreau can only do what he does if the bodies on which he works are not fully available to him as others in any meaningful sense. They have to be material, specimens, plastic forms, cases, things on which knowledge is produced. Pain must be reduced to obstacle. Crying must be treated as noise. Law must become command without reciprocity. That seems to me the whole moral structure of the island. It is not just that Moreau is cruel. It is that his entire system depends on translating relation into experiment.\r\n\r\nThat is why the cry matters so much. A cry is hard to keep in the category of \"material.\" It addresses. It gets through. It makes the fiction of detached observation wobble. The novel clearly knows this. It keeps showing us Prendick trying to preserve distinctions, animal cry versus human groan, creature versus man, civilized science versus barbarity, and every one of those distinctions grows unstable the longer the story goes on. By the end, the island has ruined his ability to see London cleanly. Everyone threatens to become beast-like. The contamination travels back to the metropolis, which is probably the most colonial thing about the novel: the fear that what was exported and inflicted elsewhere will return altered and unmanageable.\r\n\r\nI also think the class was right to emphasize that the Beast People are not simply \"subhuman\" in the way Prendick keeps trying to think them. They are too human for that, which is exactly the problem. They speak, organize, suffer, imitate, remember, revert, improvise, fear, gather, obey, disobey. The categories fail because the creatures fail to remain cleanly within the abstract slots created for them. Moreau wants animals refined into humans. Prendick wants humans secured against animals. The novel gives us beings who keep crossing the line in both directions. Good. The line was probably doing bad work anyway.\r\n\r\nThe whole discussion of pain and knowledge also stayed with me in a way that is more uncomfortable than literary classes usually are. Because Moreau's island is not only fantasy. It raises the question of where pain is inflicted and where the benefits of that inflicted pain are enjoyed. That is a scientific question, a political question, an imperial question, a medical question, and probably a question every modern society gets very good at avoiding by distributing those two locations far apart. The island makes the arrangement theatrical. Real life usually makes it administrative. That is sometimes worse.\r\n\r\nAnd I think that is why the colonial allegory matters so much here. The island is not just a weird place where a weird man does weird things to animals. It is a model of how empire imagines itself justified in reshaping life elsewhere for the sake of knowledge, order, civilization, or whatever noble noun is currently available. The Beast People do not have to be straightforward stand-ins for colonized humans for the allegory to work. In fact, it works better when we resist that simplification. What matters is the structure: distant bodies, metropolitan knowledge, racialized perception, coercive law, anxiety about reversion, panic about mixture, and finally the dream that violence can produce a higher form of life. It is a rotten dream. The novel knows it is rotten. That does not make it less compelling.\r\n\r\nSo I think the question I am left with is not \"are humans animals too,\" though yes, obviously, and the novel enjoys making that obvious feel scandalous. The better question is what kinds of social and intellectual work get done by insisting that we are not. Moreau needs that distinction. Prendick needs it. Colonialism needs it. Race science needs it. The law maybe needs it too, at least in the form practiced on this island. Once the distinction weakens, all sorts of claims become harder to sustain, some of them terrible, some of them useful. The novel is not generous enough to make that weakening feel hopeful. It does make it feel unavoidable.",
  "journal-entry-april-28": "### Preparation\r\n\r\nI want to begin with the phrase \"a certain impatient gaiety of disposition,\"<annotation data-note=\"This line matters because Jekyll does not initially describe his desires as evil in themselves. Their darkness comes from the social world in which they conflict with public masculine respectability.\" data-label=\"gaiety note\"></annotation> because it is doing suspiciously large amounts of work for such a fussy little sentence.\r\n\r\nBefore class, that line kept sticking in my head, partly because Jekyll uses it as if it should explain everything while still remaining vague enough to protect him from actual explanation. It sounds, at first, almost harmless. Cheerful. Restless. Maybe a little too fond of pleasure. Fine. That is barely even a sin in a decent novel. But in Jekyll and Hyde, the whole point is that harmless phrasing is never harmless. The sentence exists inside a social world where desire, pleasure, masculinity, reputation, medicine, class decorum, and secrecy are all piled on top of one another like overfurnished Victorian drapery. So \"gaiety\" starts sounding less like a mood and more like a pressure point.\r\n\r\nWhat interested me going in was the fact that Jekyll does not describe his pleasures as dark in themselves. He more or less says the opposite. What makes them dark is the relation they bear to his aspiration to public respectability. In other words, the problem is not that he wants pleasure. The problem is that the world in which he wants it has already arranged pleasure as something that must either be disciplined, hidden, or renamed. That felt important. It also felt nastier than the easy reading where Hyde just equals evil, Jekyll just equals good, and the whole thing becomes a cautionary tale about having too much fun after nine o'clock.\r\n\r\nI was also thinking about Utterson, because the novel begins by making him seem like the safe one, the sober one, the lawyerly one, the man who keeps his wine under control and his feelings in a locked cabinet somewhere near his liver. But then the story gives him that strange dream, or not quite a dream, where he imagines Jekyll in bed, the curtains pulled apart, Hyde standing over him, power given to him, Jekyll forced to rise and do his bidding. That is an extraordinarily weird thing for a respectable lawyer to imagine about his friend. There is no polite way around that. So I came into class wanting to know what exactly the novel thought it was doing with all that tension. Because it is either doing too much, or exactly enough.\r\n\r\nAnd then Hyde himself. I kept returning to the way people respond to him. They hate him, recoil from him, feel loathing and disgust and fear, but cannot say why. There is no nameable malformation. No clear visible offense. He produces effects without offering the neat visual cause everyone wants. That seemed crucial. The book keeps staging a crisis of interpretation. Hyde is intolerable because he cannot be fully read, and because the people who encounter him get forced back onto their own disturbed reactions, which they would really prefer not to inspect too closely. Fair enough. I too would prefer not to inspect some of my reactions too closely. Still.\r\n\r\nSo I came into class with three questions. First, what exactly is Jekyll trying to reconcile and why does he refuse reconciliation as a solution. Second, what is the relation between the novel's early homoerotic pressure and its later language of medicine and drug use. Third, why does Hyde feel less like a person than like an affliction everyone else keeps accidentally revealing in themselves.\r\n\r\n### In Class\r\n\r\nClass made the novel much queerer and much sadder, which I think is correct.\r\n\r\nWe started with Hyde's effects. This mattered because the book is incredibly careful about how people feel in Hyde's presence. Enfield tells the \"odd story\" of Hyde running down the girl, yes, but the real oddity lies in the response. The people who gather around him do not merely get angry. They feel a kind of disproportionate hatred. Utterson feels something similar later. So does Lanyon. Hyde causes \"odd subjective disturbance,\" disgust, loathing, fear, a sense of deformity without a visible deformity. That phrase, or versions of it, kept returning in class because it shows that Hyde does not arrive as a cleanly legible object. He arrives as an interpretive failure that rebounds onto the subject trying to read him. The problem is not only Hyde. The problem is what Hyde does to whoever sees him.\r\n\r\nThat led naturally back to the question of blackmail and \"Queer Street,\" which the text pretends to handle in euphemism while making the euphemism stranger by repetition. One of the strongest points from class was that blackmail here should not be read only as a plot device or even only as the threat surrounding some specific act. It belongs structurally to the world the novel describes.<annotation data-note=\"In the novel, blackmail is not only a discrete event. It belongs to a homosocial world that tightly regulates male relations while depending on them, making exposure a constant threat.\" data-label=\"blackmail note\"></annotation> These are bourgeois men, bachelors, professionals, tightly bound to one another in intensely homosocial ways, while also living in a society that polices the possibilities within those bonds. That creates a permanent condition of exposure. Blackmail becomes not just an event but a social logic. No man in that world can ever be entirely secure against accusation, because the whole order depends on drawing and redrawing the line between acceptable male intimacy and condemnable desire. That is a genuinely ugly arrangement, and the novel feels soaked in it from the first pages.\r\n\r\nThe dream sequence made more sense once class framed it that way. Utterson's imagination is described as \"enslaved,\" which is already a strange word for one's own imagination, and the scene it produces is grotesquely intimate. Jekyll in bed, smiling in sleep, the curtains plucked apart, Hyde standing there, power given to him, Jekyll forced to rise and do his bidding. The novel gives us that without direct evidence, which means the image belongs to Utterson's own pressured imagination. He is not simply deducing. He is fantasizing in a way that reveals the kinds of relations the novel cannot state more openly. That was one of the most convincing class ideas, to stop treating this as random Gothic excess and start reading it as displaced knowledge.\r\n\r\nThen we got to Jekyll's own statement, which was where the whole thing opened further. The key line, obviously, was that \"a certain impatient gaiety of disposition\" made it difficult for him to reconcile his pleasures with his \"imperious desire to carry my head high.\" The important point here was that the pleasures themselves are not initially described as dark. The darkness comes from the social frame. His aspirations, his professional seriousness, his medical identity, his public dignity, all of that converts pleasure into shame. In another world, maybe you reconcile these things and get on with your life like a reasonably adjusted person. Jekyll refuses that possibility. He does not want compromise. He wants total access to both. Public virtue without stain, private pleasure without cost. This is where the novel starts feeling less like a moral fable and more like a catastrophic failure of integration.\r\n\r\nClass made a useful comparison to Victor Frankenstein here. Victor also refuses reconciliation. He rejects domestic affection in the name of noble scientific labor and produces death in the process. Jekyll does something adjacent. He rejects the difficult work of living with divided motives, divided wants, divided forms of selfhood, and instead seeks a technological solution. That move matters. He does not want to negotiate among conflicting desires. He wants chemistry to do the moral work for him. Which is both very modern and very stupid.\r\n\r\nThe passage where Jekyll describes man as \"not truly one, but truly two\" got even more interesting once class kept going. He says two because his current knowledge does not go further, but he guesses man might be \"a mere polity of multifarious, incongruous and independent denizens.\"<annotation data-note=\"Jekyll's language of the self as a 'polity of multifarious, incongruous and independent denizens' suggests that the self is far more crowded than the neat Jekyll/Hyde split allows. Hyde is a simplification, not a solution.\" data-label=\"polity note\"></annotation> That phrase is ridiculous and excellent. A polity. A little government. A city of badly coordinated selves. That, to me, was one of the best moments of class because it pulled the novel away from the simple dualism everyone remembers and toward something messier. Jekyll wants two because two is manageable. Two gives you good and evil, doctor and monster, day and night, public and private. But the language of \"polity\" suggests he already knows the self is more crowded than that. Hyde is just the crudest simplification of a much more complicated internal world.\r\n\r\nThen the drug question came in, and once it did, it became impossible to ignore. What links Jekyll and Hyde materially is the potion. A chemical. A dose. A substance taken in a lab, alone, in secret, to produce transformation. This shifts the novel, as class pointed out, away from pure erotic tension and toward the language of addiction, or at least toward a world where addiction is becoming thinkable as a category. That was especially interesting because it did not cancel the homoerotic reading. It displaced it. The novel moves from the unsayable relation between men toward a story about solitary substance use, medicalized desire, the will overcome by some external or internal compulsion. The shift does not solve the earlier tension. It gives it another form.\r\n\r\nThat was where the historical material on sexology and the will became especially helpful. The late nineteenth century invents new kinds of people, the homosexual, the addict, the criminal, the deviant child, all as supposedly scientific types. What these figures share is a crisis of will. Either one cannot help oneself, or one's will has been seized, corrupted, diverted, degraded, overpowered by instinct, desire, substance, perversity, whatever term the discipline prefers that week. Class connected this to Ulrichs and the attempt to medicalize same-sex desire as something involuntary rather than criminal. That move is politically double-edged. It can rescue people from law by placing them under medicine. Not exactly liberation, but you take your historical openings where you can get them.\r\n\r\nLanyon mattered in this frame too. He reacts to Hyde through medical language, \"malady,\" \"deform,\" \"abnormal,\" all the terms by which disgust tries to become diagnosis.<annotation data-note=\"Lanyon's medical language tries to turn disturbed reaction into diagnosis. Hyde becomes 'abnormal' or 'deformed,' which lets the observer treat his own disgust as objective knowledge.\" data-label=\"medicine note\"></annotation> That move felt very nineteenth century in the worst way. Something disturbs you. Instead of staying with the disturbance, you relocate it into the essence of the other. Hyde becomes the malformed one. The diseased one. The revolting one. Your own disturbed response gets translated into objective description. This was one of the class's most useful recurring insights: people in the novel keep trying to flee their own reactions by projecting them into Hyde as visible truth.\r\n\r\n### Reflections\r\n\r\nWhat stays with me most is that the novel seems less interested in evil than in the social production of shame.\r\n\r\nThat is probably too broad as a final claim, but I think it is close to right. Jekyll has desires. Fine. Everyone does. He wants pleasure, gaiety, freedom from constant self-discipline, maybe sexual latitude, maybe other kinds of appetite the text keeps hazy on purpose. The key thing is that he experiences these not simply as competing desires but as incompatible with the kind of publicly legible masculine goodness he wants to inhabit. That is what converts desire into secret, secret into split, split into experiment, and experiment into catastrophe. The disaster is not only that Hyde is bad. The disaster is that Jekyll never permits himself a language in which desire could exist without immediately falling under degradation.\r\n\r\nThis is why the opening matters so much. The novel starts among men who share food, wine, law, medicine, old friendship, letters, trust, discretion, all the surfaces of bourgeois masculine order. That world feels calm. It is actually brittle. Everyone is guarding something. Everyone is interpreting everyone else just enough to avoid interpretation becoming explicit. The social order requires concealment, and concealment, naturally, produces fantasy, anxiety, suspicion, blackmail, dream-life, medical jargon, and late-night pacing. Which is to say, a great novel.\r\n\r\nI also think Hyde works less as \"the true self\" than people sometimes claim. That reading is too easy. Hyde is not the authentic essence finally set free. He is a reduction, a distilled and weaponized form of one set of impulses detached from the social, moral, and relational world that usually complicates them. He is what happens when Jekyll treats the self like a problem of chemical separation instead of lived contradiction. In that sense, Hyde is not more real than Jekyll. He is more abstract. The potion does not uncover essence. It enforces a fantasy of purification. That fantasy turns out to be lethal.\r\n\r\nAnd the will. I keep coming back to that. The novel's whole drama seems to depend on the desire to believe that if we could just locate the true mechanism, chemical, psychological, moral, social, we could explain why people do what they do and perhaps free them from responsibility, or condemn them with better terminology, depending on the mood of the century. Jekyll wants to escape the burden of mixed motives. Medicine wants to classify disturbance. Sexology wants to explain desire. The law wants to punish. The novel keeps making all of those ambitions look thinner than the thing they are trying to seize. The self is not a neat fortress. It is overcrowded. Jekyll knows that for one amazing paragraph and then spends the rest of the book trying to deny it.\r\n\r\nSo I do not think the question I am left with is whether Hyde is evil. Of course he is destructive. He hurts people. He kills. That part is not subtle. The more interesting question is what kind of society produces a man who thinks his only options are exemplary public goodness or chemically segregated vice. That is a much darker question than \"why do bad people do bad things.\" It also feels much less Victorian than advertised.",
  "journal-entry-april-21": "### Preparation\r\n\r\nI want to begin with the very odd fact that this class opened with thesis statements and ended with ghosts.\r\n\r\nThat sounds like a joke, though it is really just the syllabus doing what the syllabus does when Dr. Cantrell is in charge of it. We started with argumentation, claims, reasons, evidence, objections, all the clean little parts that make an academic essay hold together.<annotation data-note=\"Useful here because class was not only giving paper-writing advice. It was also implicitly giving a way to think through how a difficult novel makes and resists meaning. Claims need reasons; reasons need evidence; endings need suspicion.\" data-label=\"claim note\"></annotation> Then we drifted, or were dragged, back into Wuthering Heights, which is one of the least cooperative texts imaginable if your secret hope is that literature might behave like a respectable five-paragraph argument. This was useful. It also felt slightly cruel in the right way. First: here is how to build an argument. Second: here is a novel that keeps making argument impossible to finish tidily.\r\n\r\nBefore class, the part of the novel that stayed with me most was Heathcliff's claim that the whole world has become writing about Cathy. Memoranda, inscriptions, reminders, texts everywhere.<annotation data-note=\"Heathcliff's language of memoranda matters because it turns the whole world into writing about Cathy. Writing preserves evidence of existence. It also confirms absence. You get the trace, never the person.\" data-label=\"memoranda note\"></annotation> I liked that language because it felt both true and hopeless. Writing proves that something happened. It also proves that what happened is no longer present except as writing. You have the record, not the thing. You have her words, her name, the paths they walked, the objects that carry her trace, but never her again. That seems to be the torture. The whole world has become legible and therefore unbearable. Reading does not restore the lost object. It keeps the loss available. Which is a pretty nasty thing for a text to understand so well.\r\n\r\nI was also already suspicious of the \"happy ending.\" Or maybe suspicious is too weak. Mildly offended by it, perhaps. Hareton and young Cathy are sweet enough, and after several hundred pages of emotional weather, one does feel the cheap bodily temptation of relief. Ah good, some literacy, some mutual affection, maybe nobody gets psychologically vivisected for six pages. Lovely. Except every time the novel edges toward comfort, it starts making that comfort look politically expensive. A quiet marriage at the end sounds nice until you remember whose property is being stabilized, whose class power is being restored, and which dangerous dark outsider had to die for the atmosphere to improve. That is the sort of \"happy ending\" that always makes me want to check who cleaned the room afterward.\r\n\r\nSo going in, I had two questions. First, what does it mean to make a real claim, the kind that actually risks something, instead of just saying \"this paper will discuss...\" like a hostage note from a textbook. Second, what does it mean that Wuthering Heights itself seems committed to an experience that keeps outrunning the languages available to settle it, mourning, realism, heaven, tranquility, all of them.\r\n\r\n### In Class\r\n\r\nClass began with argumentation in the brutally useful way that good teaching sometimes does: not as inspiration, but as structure.\r\n\r\nClaim. Reason. Evidence. Objection. Qualification. Warrant. It sounded almost mechanical at first, though not in a bad way. More like being reminded that if you want to persuade someone, you cannot simply arrive in their office waving three feelings and a paragraph of fog. The point that stuck with me most was that a claim has to claim something. \"This paper will discuss the role of OPEC...\" is not a thesis. It is a sentence that has not yet developed self-respect. A thesis has to be contestable, specific, and explicit enough that a reader can tell what is actually at stake. That mattered because it made the whole idea of writing less mystical. You do not wait for a perfect revelation. You discover what your question has pushed you toward, then you make a statement sturdy enough to organize the work that follows.\r\n\r\nThe part about reasons and evidence helped too, especially because it clarified a distinction that is obvious the second someone says it and embarrassingly easy to blur before then. Reasons support claims. Evidence supports reasons. You do not ask what reasons support your evidence. That way lies chaos, podcasts, and probably certain cable news panels. The point was not only logical but practical: what kind of evidence do you have, how reliable is it, how representative, how precise, how authoritative, how clear. There was something comforting about hearing good writing described in terms that concrete, especially in a humanities class where people sometimes act like if you define the gears too clearly you have somehow betrayed the soul. Apparently not. The soul can survive an outline.\r\n\r\nI also liked the section on quotation, partly because it made quotation sound less like decorative obedience and more like pressure between languages. A summary gives the gist. A paraphrase reveals your relation to the material. A quotation earns its place when the wording itself matters, its tone, its rhythm, its conceptual weight, its stupidity, if you are criticizing it, its power, if you are not. That seemed important beyond the immediate research advice. It describes what class has been doing all semester. We keep taking language seriously enough to notice that different words do different things, even when they appear to be saying the \"same\" thing. That may be the main transferable skill of the course, apart from the ability to become unreasonable about dashes.\r\n\r\nThen class swung back into Wuthering Heights, and the atmosphere improved immediately by becoming much less stable.\r\n\r\nThe first major thread was Heathcliff's grief and its relation to writing. The phrase that the world appears as memoranda, documents, reminders, records of Cathy's existence and therefore of her loss, became the center of the discussion. What mattered there was the distinction between event and text. Writing gives form to what happened. It also confirms that what happened is absent. You have the sign. The thing itself is gone. The grammatical point about \"I have lost\" was especially good: present possession fused to past absence. You \"have\" loss. That sounds almost stupidly simple until you realize it is a miniature theory of mourning. Heathcliff cannot escape because every object becomes legible as after. The whole world is annotated by damage.\r\n\r\nThe Dickinson poem came in beautifully here. \"You cannot solder an abyss with air.\" That line did exactly what a good quotation is supposed to do: it did not merely illustrate the point. It sharpened it. Loss opens a gap. You can try to fill it with the thing lost, impossible. You can try to fill it with some substitute, equally impossible. You can get Lady Rowena, or the second black cat, or whatever replacement fantasy literature is currently offering, and the gap does not close. It just becomes more furnished. That was one of the class moments where the criticism felt less like explanation than like another poem arriving to make the first text harder and truer at the same time.\r\n\r\nFrom there we moved to Linton, which I appreciated because it is very easy to skip over him with a sort of impatient disgust. He is weak, manipulative, sickly, pathetic, cruel by delegation, the kind of person who makes you feel bad for rolling your eyes and then makes you roll them anyway. Class resisted the easy version of that. Linton is awful, yes, but awfulness is not all that is going on. Heathcliff scripts him, coerces him, weaponizes his weakness, and thereby makes him an especially miserable instance of what the novel does to people caught inside class violence. He does not become sympathetic exactly. That would be too generous and probably inaccurate. But he becomes more intelligible, which is different and, for criticism, more useful.\r\n\r\nThe part that really held the room, though, was the ending. Or rather the fact that the ending keeps pretending to settle things while generating new trouble.\r\n\r\nHareton and young Cathy learn to read together. This looks, on the surface, redemptive: mutual affection, education, softening, social repair, all the nice words. Class kept refusing to let those words sit comfortably. What kind of reading civilizes Hareton. What kind of world gets restored when those two inherit the Grange and the Heights. What happens when degradation and elevation are both understood as things done by humans to humans. That last point hit especially hard. If degradation is arbitrary social violence, elevation is not automatically innocent. Civilizing someone can be another form of domination, especially in a novel so suspicious of \"heaven,\" refinement, and class ascent. So the tenderness of the ending remains real. So does its cost. The novel does not let the reader have one without the other.\r\n\r\nThen Lockwood, of course, comes back to close the novel in the precise wrong way.\r\n\r\nHe stands over the graves, under the \"benign sky,\" listening to the soft wind, looking at the churchyard, and wonders how anyone could imagine unquiet slumbers for the sleepers below. Having read the book, this is almost an offensively stupid thing to say. Which is why it is perfect. Lockwood has learned just enough to remain wrong with greater elegance. He wants tranquility. He wants the local ghost talk to be superstition. He wants the novel to sleep. But the whole thing we have just read insists on unrest, the persistence of desire, the irreducibility of Cathy and Heathcliff to any pious closure, and the failure of available languages, grief, realism, heaven, propriety, to contain what happened between them. Lockwood closes the book exactly as the wrong reader would. He gifts us peace where the novel has spent hundreds of pages refusing it.\r\n\r\nThat, I think, was the most useful final move from class: the argument that realism is not the faithful reporting of social types. Realism, in the richer sense, is what breaks through the culture's dominant ways of talking.<annotation data-note=\"The final class point was especially good: realism does not have to mean faithful reporting of social types. It can mean a breakthrough beyond the usual categories a culture uses to explain itself. In that sense, the ghost is more real than Lockwood's tranquility.\" data-label=\"realism note\"></annotation> Heathcliff is not \"real\" because he can be assigned a tidy category, Irish, Romani, dark, rustic, whatever. The book is real because something in it exceeds every category its own characters keep trying to impose. The ghost is real in that sense. Not because a specter with little Victorian ankles is literally strolling the moors, though maybe it is, but because Cathy's desire, and Heathcliff's, and the disturbance they produce, keep breaking into every story told about them. That is a much more interesting realism than \"homely northern farmer\" ever was.\r\n\r\n### Reflections\r\n\r\nWhat I keep coming back to is that the class's two halves were less separate than they looked.\r\n\r\nAt first it seemed we had a writing lecture and then a novel. But the more I think about it, the more Wuthering Heights itself behaves like a problem of argumentation, only an argument forever refusing to stay tidy. It makes claims. It gives reasons. It provides evidence. It produces objections almost immediately. It forces qualifications. It wrecks the warrant. Cathy says heaven is not her home. The novel spends the rest of itself making that claim harder and harder to dismiss. Lockwood offers a counter-reading, tranquility, benign sky, sleepers at rest, and the text more or less laughs at him. So one thing I took from class is that the machinery of argument is not opposed to literary difficulty. It is what lets you stay with the difficulty without reducing it to vibes and admiration.\r\n\r\nI also think the ending matters more because it does not fully resolve. Yes, there is relief. Hareton and Cathy are easier to watch than literally anyone else in the book. Literacy, kindness, less psychic mutilation, wonderful. But relief is not the same as vindication. Heathcliff dies. The outsider energy that has spent the novel attacking landed gentility is gone. Property consolidates. The hereditary order steadies itself. We are invited to breathe easier. The invitation itself should make us suspicious. If I find myself feeling soothed, this novel has trained me well enough to ask: soothed for whom.\r\n\r\nThe writing discussion stayed with me here too, especially the point about specificity. A weak claim says the novel ends happily. A better claim starts asking what kind of happiness, for whom, under what terms, against what background of violence, and at what cost to the furious energies the book has generated all along. A still better claim, maybe, asks why the ending feels both moving and compromised at once. That seems truer to the experience of reading it. The book does not want me to become simple in its presence. That is one of the reasons it is worth rereading, whereas a cleaner novel you can finish once, nod at, and leave politely on a shelf like a guest who never embarrassed you.\r\n\r\nAnd then there is Lockwood. I almost feel bad for how useful he is as a model of bad reading. Almost. He sees peace where the villagers see haunting. He sees types where the novel gives singularity. He sees surfaces where the book keeps insisting on pressure, remainder, disturbance. Yet he is the one left standing at the end, reading gravestones, initiating more readings, more films, more classes, more journals like this one. That is a little unfair and maybe profound. The wrong reader can still become the occasion for future reading. In some cursed way, Lockwood is the patron saint of literature classes.\r\n\r\nSo the thing I am left with, maybe the main thing, is that some texts do not reward closure because closure is exactly what they know how to distrust. The \"unquiet slumbers\" line is silly only if we forget that the whole novel has been trying to teach us another way of reading, one that does not confuse social stillness with truth. Cathy and Heathcliff do not stay put. The story does not stay put. The language keeps opening, rewriting, scratching in margins, returning as ghost. If that is not a good argument for rereading, I do not know what is.",
  "journal-entry-april-16": "### Preparation\r\n\r\nI want to begin with Cathy saying heaven is not her home,<annotation data-note=\"In Wuthering Heights, heaven often names the social world of cultivation, class refinement, and proper domesticity. Cathy's dream and later breakdown turn that value system upside down by making heaven the place she cannot live in.\" data-label=\"heaven note\"></annotation> because that is one of those sentences that should make the whole book tilt.\r\n\r\nUsually heaven arrives in novels already pre-approved. You are not supposed to argue with it. Heaven is good, hell is bad, good people ascend, passionate weirdos burn, everyone learns a moral lesson, end of story. Emily Bronte, apparently, looked at that whole arrangement and decided it needed to be bullied a little. So Cathy dreams of heaven, gets thrown out, lands back on the moors, and wakes \"sobbing for joy.\" Which is an extraordinary way to feel about not getting into paradise. It also makes perfect sense almost immediately, because the heaven available in this book is full of Lintons.\r\n\r\nThat is unfair to the Lintons. It is also fair enough.\r\n\r\nBefore class, what kept bothering me was the sheer nastiness of the inversion. If heaven is the polished, cultivated, civilized world of Thrushcross Grange, then Cathy's ascent into it is not a reward but a mutilation. She gets improved into a lady. She gets refined, clothed, softened, and placed. From the outside, that looks like social advancement. From the inside, it starts to look like spiritual suffocation. So the question I brought into class was not simply why Cathy prefers Heathcliff to Edgar, which is too tidy and too romantic and, frankly, a little boring. The better question was what kind of world requires her to call the place of her supposed elevation a prison.\r\n\r\nI was also still thinking about Lockwood, because he remains useful precisely by being so wrong about almost everything. He keeps approaching Yorkshire as though he has discovered a realer version of life, the way people from cities sometimes visit \"rustic\" places and start narrating like they are the first person ever to encounter weather. He likes the region as image, type, authenticity, all those flattering metropolitan fantasies that allow one to admire rural people without ever really having to take them as fully social beings. The class material on photography and tourism made that much clearer for me. A cottage becomes a picture of cottage life. A broom by a doorway becomes atmosphere. The actual labor and actual people fade behind the image that stands in for them. Lockwood feels, in that sense, less like a man and more like an early guidebook with legs.<annotation data-note=\"Lockwood treats Yorkshire less as a society than as a scenic object and a storehouse of authentic types. Tourism here means a way of seeing that turns space into image and difference into backwardness.\" data-label=\"tourist gaze note\"></annotation>\r\n\r\nAnd I was still thinking about the names in Cathy's room. Catherine Earnshaw. Catherine Linton. Catherine Heathcliff. They swarm the page. At first that looks like childish scribbling or romantic rehearsal. The more I looked, the less innocent it seemed. It felt like someone trying on futures and refusing each one just as quickly. Or perhaps someone discovering that names do not settle identity so much as expose how unstable it already is. I do not think the novel wants us to choose the \"right\" Catherine. I think it wants us to sit in the proliferation and feel a little dizzy.\r\n\r\n### In Class\r\n\r\nClass opened, unexpectedly but usefully, with punctuation and sources, which sounds unpromising until you realize Dr. Cantrell can make punctuation sound like a question of time, force, and temperament rather than just a set of tiny traffic laws. The point that stayed with me was that punctuation is both logical and artistic. It arranges relations between clauses, yes, but it also creates rhythm, pause, interruption, flow. Which turned out to be a good accidental introduction to Bronte, whose sentences often feel like they are trying to decide whether to proceed rationally or run at the wall again. There was also the research advice about reading the frame first, introduction, conclusion, index, bibliography, which is the sort of practical counsel that sounds obvious right up until the moment you are drowning in sources and need someone to tell you that no, you do not actually have to marry every book you meet.\r\n\r\nThen we came back to Wuthering Heights, which was where the real psychic weather was.\r\n\r\nLockwood showed up first, sadly for him. The key move here was his assumption that rural people \"live more in earnest,\" that they are somehow more authentic because they are farther from metropolitan complication. Nelly replies, sensibly, that they are much the same as anyone else once you know them. Lockwood cannot accept that. He protects his ignorance the way he always does, by turning Nelly into an exception. Since she speaks too well and does not bear the visible marks of provincialism he expects, she cannot challenge the type. She has to prove the rule by failing to fit it. That is one of his most durable habits: whatever interrupts the category must be reclassified as anomaly instead of forcing revision of the category itself.\r\n\r\nThe discussion of tourism sharpened that enormously. A photograph does not only record. It captures in the stronger sense. It takes an object or scene and produces an image that can circulate apart from the thing itself, inviting fantasy to do the rest. The little broom by the open door is no longer just a broom. It becomes cottage life for people who do not live in cottages. Yorkshire, in this way, becomes available to metropolitan visitors as a kind of earlier England, a trip through space that flatters itself as a trip backward in time. That was one of the class ideas I liked most, because it explains why Lockwood can look at the Heights and immediately start seeing \"homely northern farmers\" and other literary species instead of people. He is not learning the place. He is visiting a ready-made imaginary.\r\n\r\nThen Heathcliff, of course, because the type breaks the minute he appears. Lockwood wants a northern farmer and gets a dark-skinned man who dresses like a gentleman, speaks in ways he cannot place, and refuses to stabilize as merely rural. So race arrives. \"Gypsy,\" darkness, foreignness, the whole attempt to explain him by making his appearance the truth that invalidates his manners. Class was very good here too. Heathcliff does not need to resolve into one neat identity for the analysis to matter. Irish, Romani, Black, Moorish, Liverpool-linked, slave-trade-adjacent, all of these possibilities circulate because the text racializes indeterminacy itself. He is not simply poor. He is made unplaceable in ways that let class degradation and racial suspicion reinforce one another. That seems more important than pinning down one final answer and congratulating ourselves for solving Heathcliff like a crossword.\r\n\r\nThe dog point was also excellent and, annoyingly, persuasive. The Heights dogs are violent, yes, but the Grange dogs bite too. Which means civilization does not get to exile violence to the rough house on the hill and keep refinement pure. The Grange is guarded by violence. It is cultivated through exclusion. The nice house with nice surfaces still needs dogs trained to attack outsiders. There is something almost too neat about that symbolically, except it is not just symbolic. Estates really do work like that. The beautiful house is lovely partly because its violence has been redistributed and disguised.\r\n\r\nThen Lockwood and women, which is where his whole worldview becomes much smaller and much funnier in a bad way. The seacoast anecdote gave us the pattern in miniature. He sees a \"real goddess,\" loves her perfectly as long as she does not notice him, and the second she looks back he shrinks \"like a snail.\" That simile does more damage to him than any critic ever could. He likes women best when they remain one-way visual experiences. Once the gaze returns, the fantasy collapses. He can behold. He does not want to be beheld. That carried directly into his description of young Cathy, whose face he admires but whose eyes displease him because they express scorn. Again, female subjectivity ruins the scene. How rude of it.\r\n\r\nThe class then turned, beautifully, to the names and the dream.\r\n\r\nCatherine Earnshaw. Catherine Linton. Catherine Heathcliff. The proliferation of names in the margins of the old books is one of those moments where the novel seems to open up several different versions of itself at once. On one level, yes, Cathy is imagining futures. On another, she is multiplying herself beyond any one social destiny. The names move through the male lines of the novel, but her repetition of them does not feel docile. It feels experimental, almost defiant. She is trying on forms of social existence, but she is also revealing how unstable they are. The \"real\" Catherine becomes harder to locate the more names appear, which prepares for Lockwood's confusion and, later, for the ghostliness of Cathy as something that exceeds ordinary categories of personhood.\r\n\r\nThen the dream itself, which is really the center of the whole class for me. Cathy dreams that heaven is not her home, the angels throw her back onto the moors, and she wakes crying for joy. Nelly, being Nelly, tries almost immediately to calm, translate, and domesticate the dream. But the dream resists that treatment. It makes heaven look like exile. And once class put that beside Heathcliff and Cathy peering into Thrushcross Grange as children, the logic became brutal. The Grange looks heavenly from outside: chandeliers, carpets, polished surfaces, the glow of wealth and order. Then you look closer and the children inside are shrieking over a dog like tiny upholstered lunatics. Cathy and Heathcliff laugh because they can already see that heaven is ridiculous when you get too near it.\r\n\r\nThat, I think, is why Cathy's later movement into ladyhood feels like a fall rather than an ascent. The novel starts inverting the usual topography. She is elevated socially. She is degraded spiritually. She gains refinement. She loses the self that mattered. When she cries later that she wishes she were \"a girl again, half savage and hardy, and free,\" it becomes very difficult to read her earlier transformation as improvement. She has not climbed into fulfillment. She has been translated into someone else's vocabulary.\r\n\r\nThe heaven and hell language became even stranger once class brought in Paradise Lost by way of Frankenstein. In Shelley, the creature uses Milton to name his exclusion, Adam denied, Satan produced. In Bronte, the inversion goes further. The problem is not exactly expulsion from heaven. It is entrapment within it. Cathy's hell is the social heaven of classed femininity. Her joy lies in the outside, in weather, moor, disorder, and in Heathcliff, who is not simply a love object here but something like the condition of a self she cannot preserve inside polite society. When she says he is \"more myself than I am,\" that is more radical than most love language because it does not sound like complementarity at all. It sounds like a damaged form of indivisibility.\r\n\r\n### Reflections\r\n\r\nWhat keeps staying with me is that the novel does not merely reverse heaven and hell for shock value. It asks what kinds of life get named by those words in the first place.\r\n\r\n\"Heaven\" in this book starts looking like social success, proper marriage, gentility, inheritance, smooth surfaces, well-behaved bodies, good rooms, civilized taste. None of those things are false exactly. They are real social goods for the people who possess them. What Bronte seems to understand, and to dislike, is that those goods demand forms of deadness from certain people, especially women. Cathy can become Mrs. Linton. She cannot do that and remain the wild creature of the moors in the same way. The social role is not just additive. It is transformative in the punishing sense. She is not decorated. She is rewritten.\r\n\r\nThat is why Nelly matters so much as narrator. She wants order. She wants moral legibility. She wants Cathy's death to settle into recognizable religious comfort. She sees an angel, an infinite calm, a spirit at home with God. Cathy, meanwhile, has been saying for pages that heaven is the wrong frame. So one of the most interesting tensions in the novel is not only between Cathy and Edgar or Cathy and Heathcliff, but between Cathy's own language of desire and Nelly's language of consolation. Nelly keeps trying to move Catherine back into a system of meaning that Catherine herself has already rejected. That is not villainy. It is something more ordinary and maybe more damaging: interpretive domestication.\r\n\r\nI also think the novel is doing something very nasty, and very smart, with childhood. Usually childhood in nineteenth-century fiction gets sentimentalized into innocence or vulnerability or moral truth. Here childhood starts to look like the site of a form of attachment and freedom that the adult social world cannot accommodate. Cathy's longing to be \"a girl again\" is not nostalgia in the simple sense. She is not missing dolls and nursery comforts. She is missing the possibility of being half savage, bodily, unladylike, outside the social heaven that now claims her. That is a much harsher thing to mourn.\r\n\r\nAnd Lockwood, dear God, Lockwood. What I like about him structurally is that he keeps failing in the correct way. He fails so consistently that the novel can use him as a demonstration of what it means to read badly. He treats regions as images, people as types, women as spectacles, houses as symbols he can decode from the threshold, and every time the novel hands him something more unruly. He goes looking for a northern farmer's life and finds Heathcliff. He wants a pretty young woman and finds scorn. He lies in a bed expecting shelter and gets names, margins, ghosts, and Catherine bleeding through the frame. In another novel he would learn. Here he mostly just continues being Lockwood, which is somehow funnier and more useful.\r\n\r\nSo I think what I am left with is a different way of hearing Cathy's dream. Not as melodrama, not as adolescent excess, not as some decorative Gothic flourish, but as the novel's clearest statement so far that the values called civilized, elevated, heavenly, are not neutral. They have a cost. They distribute life unevenly. They ask for submission and call it peace. Cathy's refusal of heaven is not a tantrum. It is knowledge. Messy, destructive, impossible knowledge, maybe. Still knowledge.",
  "journal-entry-april-14": "### Preparation\r\n\r\nI want to begin with Lockwood, which is unfortunate for all of us, including Lockwood.\r\n\r\nHe is one of those narrators who keeps making the same mistake with such confidence that you almost have to admire the stamina. By this point in the novel, he has already misread Heathcliff, misread Cathy, misread the house, misread the dogs, and misread the basic fact that other people are not little scenic features arranged for his interpretive pleasure. Still, he persists. There is something almost Seinfeldian about it. Not in the sense that he is funny on purpose, but in the sense that every new social interaction somehow reveals a fresh and unnecessary layer of self-delusion. He walks into Yorkshire like a man who thinks he has discovered authenticity the way tourists think they have discovered \"hidden gems,\" which usually means a place where real people still have to live while being looked at.<annotation data-note=\"Tourism here does not mean simple travel. It means a way of seeing a region as image, type, and fantasy, often translating spatial difference into temporal backwardness, as though going north were somehow going into the past.\" data-label=\"tourism note\"></annotation>\r\n\r\nWhat struck me before class was the way he talks about rural people as if they become more interesting under conditions of isolation, like spiders in dungeons becoming more fascinating than spiders in normal rooms. That analogy is so revealing that it almost does the work for us. He does not see country people as people. He sees them as intensified objects of observation. Their value comes from the frame in which he encounters them. They are interesting because he is bored. That seems to be the beginning of a lot of bad reading.\r\n\r\nI was also thinking about photography, because once you start talking about tourism and realism and \"types,\" it becomes difficult not to. The little cottage with the broom propped just so, the northern farmer in his chair, the mug of ale, the whole thing feels like a calotype before the camera even arrives. A scene captured, arranged, detached from its life, and then circulated as image. That was what interested me most: realism here does not mean reality in some innocent sense. It means a way of seeing people as instances of categories.<annotation data-note=\"Lockwood's 'homely northern farmer' is not an observed person but a category he already knows how to deploy. That is one way realism works: it makes people legible by referring them to social types. The novel keeps breaking that process.\" data-label=\"realism note\"></annotation> A homely northern farmer. A provincial woman. A gypsy-like man. A dark child speaking gibberish. The category arrives first and then the object gets pushed into it. If the object resists, so much the worse for the object.\r\n\r\nAnd then Cathy. By which I mean both Catherines, which is already the problem. The names in the bed-closet had stayed with me, mostly because they feel like a child's game and a metaphysical crisis at the same time. Catherine Earnshaw. Catherine Linton. Catherine Heathcliff. Different sizes, different forms, different futures, none of them stable. Before class I kept coming back to the possibility that the writing is not only imaginative rehearsal but a kind of refusal. Each new name loosens the hold of the last one. She is trying them on, yes, but she is also escaping each as she writes the next. There is a lot of freedom in that. There is also a lot of panic.\r\n\r\nSo I came into class with three questions. First, how does Lockwood's tourist gaze distort everything it touches. Second, what makes Nelly's narration different from Joseph's and Zillah's. Third, why does heaven keep sounding so bad in this novel.<annotation data-note=\"In this novel, heaven is rarely a straightforward good. It often names social order, refinement, domestic enclosure, and class elevation. Cathy's dream turns the whole value system upside down by making heaven the place she cannot live in.\" data-label=\"heaven note\"></annotation>\r\n\r\n### In Class\r\n\r\nClass began with the question of servants again, which felt right, because the novel keeps asking who gets to appear as a subject and who gets to appear as a function.\r\n\r\nZillah got us there quickly. She does things. She takes Lockwood upstairs. She misdirects him into Catherine's room. She serves the plot beautifully, which is exactly the problem. When class asked what we know about her, the answer was basically her usefulness. That is not an accident. Servants in novels often arrive as verbs wearing aprons. They carry, open, fetch, warn, vanish. Their names are less important than the mechanism they enable. Joseph gets slightly more because he is linguistically obnoxious enough to force his way into memory, but even there the novel uses him partly as a performance of dialect, a kind of resistant noise in the text.\r\n\r\nNelly, though, is harder to reduce. Class was good on this. She is still a servant. She tells the story because Lockwood commands it in the soft, genteel way that still counts as command. He wants animation. He wants a regular gossip. He wants to be entertained out of his own vacancy. But Nelly is not simply delivering scenic local color. She has read. She speaks in a way that surprises Lockwood because he expects provincialism to come marked on the body and in the voice. Since it does not, he protects his assumptions by calling her an exception. That move felt very modern, unfortunately. The category must survive. The actual person gets renamed to preserve the category.\r\n\r\nThe tourism piece clarified that further. Dr. Cantrell's discussion of calotypes and early photography made Lockwood's way of seeing much easier to understand. Tourism does not simply look at a place. It translates it into an image fit for circulation. A broom by a cottage door ceases to be a broom someone uses and becomes a sign of cottage life for metropolitan fantasy. A region becomes a past time made visible in space. You do not travel north. You travel backward. Yorkshire becomes a place where London can encounter its own imagined earlier self, rougher, more earnest, more \"real,\" which is the sort of thing cities love to say about places they are exploiting visually while misunderstanding socially. The Blue Ridge Parkway example made this painfully clear. An overlook teaches you what to see and, more importantly, what not to see. The mountains appear; mountain labor disappears. I kept thinking that Lockwood is basically an overlook with gloves.\r\n\r\nThat also helped with realism. I liked the point that realism here functions through categories. The \"homely northern farmer\" is not a person Lockwood has met. It is a social type he has already been trained to recognize. So when he walks into Wuthering Heights and starts describing what belongs to such a type, he is not learning from the place. He is imposing legibility on it. That is why Heathcliff becomes so important. Heathcliff appears as a singular contrast, and Lockwood immediately reaches for race to explain the disruption. Dark-skinned. Gypsy. Gentleman in dress but not in essence. He has to be coded as exception because otherwise the type collapses. Heathcliff makes the category wobble and Lockwood responds by tightening his grip on every bad classification available to him.\r\n\r\nThe class discussion of Heathcliff was especially useful because it resisted solving him. Irish, Romani, Black, linked to Liverpool, linked to the slave trade, linked to migration, linked to racialization without being neatly pinned to one modern identity. That seemed exactly right. The text does not want him legible in that clean way. His indeterminacy is part of his social function in the novel. It lets everyone around him project different forms of alterity onto him while still treating him as degradable labor. Race and class work together here so thoroughly that trying to peel them apart too neatly feels like a mistake.\r\n\r\nThe dogs helped too, which still sounds ridiculous until you remember that they always help in this class. Lockwood wants the Heights dogs to mean savagery and the Grange dogs to mean civilization, but the Grange dogs bite as well. The \"civilized\" world is defended by trained violence. That was one of the most useful class points because it ruins the easy symbolic split. Savagery is not housed at the Heights while refinement lives safely at the Grange. The Grange is also violent, only its violence is better upholstered.\r\n\r\nThen we got to Lockwood and women, and things became more embarrassing for him than they already were. The seacoast \"goddess\" story was almost too perfect. As long as the woman does not notice him, she can remain a goddess. The moment she looks back, he retracts into himself \"like a snail,\" which is one of those similes that no one survives with dignity. The point is not that he is shy in some charming, Studio Ghibli rain-scene way. The point is that female subjectivity spoils the fantasy. He wants to behold. He does not want to be beheld. Once the woman looks back, she stops being a beautiful object and becomes someone. Disaster.\r\n\r\nThat reading carried directly into his encounter with young Cathy. He can describe her face, her form, her youth, her beauty. The problem again is the eyes. Her look contains scorn and a kind of controlled hostility, and those are disagreeable to him because they indicate that she is not passively available to his reading. This really does seem to be a Lockwood pattern. He likes women most securely when they remain one-sided visual experiences. A woman who answers the gaze becomes difficult. A woman who thinks becomes worse. A woman who judges him, catastrophic.\r\n\r\nThen the dream sequence. Or, really, Cathy's dream inside Nelly's narration inside Lockwood's frame, because this novel does not believe in giving you one layer of mediation when three will do. The important line, obviously, was that heaven did not seem to be her home, and she broke her heart weeping to come back to earth. That sentence felt even stronger once class placed it next to Heathcliff's earlier vision of Thrushcross Grange as heaven. Heaven there means wealth, cultivation, carpets, chandeliers, the whole soft civilizing apparatus. It also contains the Lintons, who are somehow at once polished and absurd, little children in heaven fighting over a lapdog like it is the last good thing in creation. Cathy and Heathcliff look in and laugh. Their laughter matters. It is one of the few truly healthy sounds in the novel.\r\n\r\nWhat class made clear is that Cathy's later \"elevation\" into that world is really a fall. She gets refined, re-dressed, and raised into ladyhood, which from the outside looks like improvement. Yet the novel keeps treating it as a disaster in progress. By the time she says she wishes she were \"a girl again, half savage and hardy,\" the whole value system has inverted. Heaven is the social role that kills her. Earth, or the moor, or whatever pre-social wildness she had with Heathcliff, becomes the lost thing worth mourning. This was one of the places where the Milton comparison helped. If there is a fall here, it is into heaven. That is such a good reversal that I am a little annoyed Emily Bronte got there before everyone else.\r\n\r\n### Reflections\r\n\r\nWhat I keep coming back to is the idea that this novel hates being looked at from above.\r\n\r\nLockwood keeps trying. The tourist does this. The realist classifier does this. The gentleman from elsewhere does this. He wants Yorkshire to become scenery, local color, social type, rural earnestness, almost-loveable life in the country. He wants women to become beautiful figures whose looks stop at his body rather than returning to him. He wants houses to mean what houses are supposed to mean. The novel keeps frustrating every one of those wishes. It does not simply say that he is wrong. It makes his style of seeing itself look foolish.\r\n\r\nThat feels important because tourism, realism, and domesticity all seem to be under pressure here at once. Tourism wants the region as image. Realism wants the person as type. Domesticity wants heaven to look desirable. The novel keeps taking these forms and bending them until they expose the violence or stupidity inside them. The Grange is heaven if your idea of heaven includes decorative imprisonment. The Heights are savage if your idea of savagery cannot recognize the violence in cultivation, inheritance, and trained dogs. Nelly is a gossip if your idea of narration cannot imagine working-class intelligence without turning it into chatter.\r\n\r\nI also cannot stop thinking about the names. Catherine Earnshaw. Catherine Linton. Catherine Heathcliff. Those names are not only future options. They are pressures. The whole novel seems obsessed with what happens when women move through male names and are expected to become coherent in them. Cathy's writing refuses that coherence for a moment. She proliferates instead. She becomes several. She is not \"free\" exactly, because every available name is still attached to a male line. But she is not docile inside that system either. She scribbles through it. That seems to me more important than the usual clean take that she is just daydreaming about marriage.\r\n\r\nThe heaven and hell language is probably where the novel feels most alive to me right now. Usually those words arrive with moral clarity prepackaged. Here they do not. Heaven starts sounding airless, over-civilized, dead in advance. Hell sounds closer to vitality, desire, weather, mud, trouble, and whatever still throbs underneath social arrangement. I do not mean that the novel simply celebrates suffering or romanticizes the moors like a perfume ad. It is much meaner than that. What it seems to say, at least for now, is that the social forms calling themselves elevation may be perfectly capable of producing spiritual ruin. Cathy is improved into illness. That is a sentence this novel would understand.\r\n\r\nAnd maybe that is why Lockwood irritates me so productively. He is the wrong reader inside the book, which makes him very useful to readers outside it. He keeps trying to put everything back into place. The place keeps moving. He sees a northern farmer's house. He gets Heathcliff. He sees a beautiful young woman. He gets contempt in the eyes. He finds Catherine's little scribbled kingdom of names and gets a ghost. Honestly, at this point the novel is almost bullying him, and I support that.",
  "journal-entry-april-9": "A class about servants, storytelling, and the people literature keeps using without fully seeing. We moved from Harriet Jacobs, where an enslaved woman's speech is stolen and turned against her, into *Wuthering Heights*, where Nelly Dean tells nearly everything and still risks being treated as furniture with opinions.\r### Preparation\r\n\r\nI want to begin with a servant whose story gets used against her.\r\n\r\nBefore class, what was sitting with me most was Harriet Jacobs telling Mrs. Flint about sexual harassment and then watching that story get stolen almost instantly. Mrs. Flint does not receive it. She repurposes it. She turns Linda's words into accusation, jealousy, surveillance, and that bizarre whispering scene where she basically ventriloquizes her husband's abuse back into the ear of the girl he has been abusing. That scene is so ugly it almost feels engineered in a lab for the study of power. Which, I guess, slavery was.\r\n\r\nSo I came into *Wuthering Heights* already thinking about what it means when servants speak inside literary forms built by and for people above them. Dr. Cantrell's point about literature not really being written by working people or for working people stayed with me. That sounds a little too cleanly Marxist when you first hear it, but then you start looking at who gets to be a subject and who gets to be a function, and it gets harder to shrug off. Working people appear in literature all the time. The trouble is that they often appear the way furniture appears. Necessary, positioned, useful, sometimes even memorable, but mostly there to support someone else's drama.\r\n\r\nThat was why the little exercise with the three servants interested me. Nelly, obviously.<annotation data-note=\"The important question is not only whether a servant speaks, but under what conditions. Nelly tells the story because Lockwood wants it, which means narration is still entangled with service even when it becomes more than service.\" data-label=\"servant note\"></annotation> Joseph, because you cannot really forget Joseph once he has begun sounding like a haunted farm implement. Then Zillah, who is easier to forget precisely because the text mostly uses her to do things. She takes Lockwood upstairs. She misjudges the room. She moves the plot into place. If you blank on her name, that is not really your moral failure as a reader. It is part of how servants get written. They serve. Their action gets remembered more easily than their subjectivity.\r\n\r\nSo my question going in was basically this: if Nelly is more visible than that, more articulate than that, more central than that, what kind of space does the novel actually give her? Is she really speaking, or is she just a more advanced tool than Zillah?\r\n\r\nI was also already thinking about dogs, which is a ridiculous sentence until you remember that dogs in this class are never just dogs. The Heights has savage dogs. The Grange also has savage dogs. Which ruins the easy opposition between wild and civilized almost immediately. Good. That opposition was getting too comfortable anyway.\r\n\r\n### In Class\r\n\r\nClass opened with Harriet Jacobs, and I was glad it did, because it gave the servant question real stakes before *Wuthering Heights* could turn it into atmosphere.\r\n\r\nThe key point was that Linda Brent tries to tell the truth about sexual violence, and the conditions of reception are already arranged against her. Mrs. Flint hears the story and promptly makes it about herself, her injury, her humiliation, her husband, her suffering. Some of that suffering is real. Jacobs is not denying that white women are damaged by slavery. But the damage does not produce solidarity. It produces appropriation. The enslaved girl's account becomes one more instrument through which a white woman can rehearse her own pain and reassert power over someone even more vulnerable. That was one of the more brutal class points because it kills the lazy fantasy that common injury automatically makes common cause. Apparently not.\r\n\r\nThe whispering scene felt even worse once class slowed down over it. Mrs. Flint knows the language her husband uses on Linda because Linda has had to tell her. Then she repeats it. Which means Linda's effort to speak becomes fresh material for domination. That seemed to me a genuinely important thing to hold onto before reading Nelly Dean, because it makes you more suspicious of easy ideas like \"telling your story\" or \"finally having a voice.\" Speech is not freedom if the whole situation is built to convert what you say into a weapon.<annotation data-note=\"Jacobs matters here because she shows how structurally subordinate speech can be turned against the speaker. That does not make Nelly and Linda equivalent, but it sharpens the question of what it means for a woman in service to narrate.\" data-label=\"jacobs note\"></annotation>\r\n\r\nThat became the bridge into *Wuthering Heights*. We started with the question of servants in the ten chapters. Nelly, Joseph, Zillah. What do they do. That question sounds simple enough. It also quietly reveals the problem. Zillah does plot work. Joseph does dialect and religious grotesquerie. Nelly does narration, which is obviously more substantial, but also still service. Lockwood calls her in with supper and tells her to sit down and talk. He does not exactly ask in the modern polite sense. He commands with enough softness that a polite reader could miss the command. Class did not miss it. The story is compelled. Nelly is not sitting down because she has suddenly decided that a bored tenant needs the Earnshaw family saga. She sits because serving includes speech when the employer wants entertainment. That mattered.\r\n\r\nI liked the point that Lockwood wants a \"regular gossip,\" because it clarifies the status of the story from the beginning. He does not ask for testimony, historiography, or some morally serious accounting of social relations on the moors. He wants something to animate him. He is bored. That boredom is important. A servant's life can be turned into narrative because someone with leisure wants not to be lonely for an hour. There is a lot packed into that arrangement, and none of it is flattering to Lockwood.\r\n\r\nNelly herself got more complicated the longer class stayed with her. She has been in service all her life. Her mother served the Earnshaws. She has moved between the Heights and the Grange. She has worked indoors and in the fields. She knows the families from within, but from within a position that is never equal to theirs. That means she sees things they do not see, or sees them differently. It also means she cannot tell the story as though she were floating above its consequences. She still has to live in this world. She still has to survive in relation to masters, employers, tenants, people above her who may listen badly or punish indirectly. That seemed to me the most useful correction to any easy celebration of her as a subaltern truth-teller. She is speaking. She is also speaking inside service.\r\n\r\nClass kept pressing her ambivalence toward Cathy, and that felt right too. Nelly does not simply adore Cathy. She does not simply hate her either. The relation is mixed, which is more interesting and more believable. She nursed her. Grew up alongside her. Served her. Judged her. Probably resented her. Probably loved her in some ways. \"Protective\" felt too neat, and I liked that class resisted it. Nelly may protect Cathy at moments, but she also protects herself, her job, her standing, her ability to remain inside the household while narrating it. Those motives do not cancel each other. They complicate each other.\r\n\r\nThe speech question mattered a lot. Joseph's language gets marked as dialect in the full literary way, apostrophes everywhere, orthographic suffering, the whole routine by which the reader is made to labor through his speech and enjoy that labor as proof of rustic excess. Zillah gets much less. Nelly, by contrast, is well spoken. She reads. Lockwood is almost surprised by her articulateness, which says plenty about him. Class made a point I liked here, which is that if Nelly has read widely in the house libraries, then she may not only be telling a story. She may know something about how stories are told. That changes her status. She is not necessarily naive narrative labor. She may be narrating with an awareness of narrative itself. Which means the old critical move of calling her \"the villain\" because she shapes events starts to look a little suspicious. Funny how a servant becomes threatening the moment she starts sounding too literate.\r\n\r\nThen Heathcliff arrived and all the race and class questions that I had been half-expecting came fully to the surface.\r\n\r\nEarnshaw returns from Liverpool with the child, and the child is described first through darkness, dirt, gibberish, black hair, dark skin, devil-adjacent weirdness, all of it. Liverpool matters. The slave trade matters. Irish migration matters. Romani associations matter. The text keeps refusing to let Heathcliff settle into one clean identity. Irish, Black, Romani, racially indeterminate, all of the above in the imagination of those around him, maybe none in any stable modern sense. What matters is that he arrives already racialized and already classed for degradation. He is not merely poor. He is made strange in ways that allow poverty and racialization to feed each other.\r\n\r\nI appreciated that class did not try to \"solve\" Heathcliff's identity too fast. The point did not seem to be that there is one correct answer hidden in Brontë like an Easter egg. The point was that the text insists on his indeterminacy and makes that indeterminacy do social work. He is beaten into labor. Forced into the fields. Spoken of as degrading. Made to occupy a place where race and class become hard to disentangle. Cathy says marrying him would degrade her, and that one sentence carries more than one hierarchy at once. You cannot really pull them apart without losing what the novel is doing.<annotation data-note=\"The novel seems less interested in giving Heathcliff one fixed racial identity than in showing how racial ambiguity, class degradation, and outsider status work together to make him legible as threat, filth, or disorder to the people around him.\" data-label=\"heathcliff note\"></annotation>\r\n\r\nThe dogs helped here too. The Heights dogs are violent, yes. But the Grange dogs bite Cathy too. Which means civilization does not get to outsource savagery to the Heights and keep its own hands clean. I liked the point that domestication itself is violent, that the Grange represents a cultivated world built through enclosure, dispossession, managed grounds, trained animals, the whole apparatus of polite force. The savage dog at the Grange is not an exception. It is evidence.\r\n\r\nAnd then there was the relationship between Cathy and Heathcliff, which class only really began to open, but already it felt interesting because it does not fit the cleaner gender roles that later social life wants to impose. Before gentility, before marriage, before inheritance does its usual sorting, the two of them feel less like boy and girl in a conventional novel and more like allied creatures of the moor. That is probably too romantic a sentence, but there is something in their relation that precedes social typing and then gets broken by it. Cathy moves into ladyhood. Heathcliff gets beaten into labor and later weaponizes gentility. Whatever they had does not survive in an innocent form, if it was ever innocent at all.\r\n\r\n### Reflections\r\n\r\nWhat I keep coming back to is the difference between serving a story and telling one.\r\n\r\nZillah serves the story. Joseph complicates it through speech but is still partly trapped in function. Nelly seems to do both. She keeps the machinery of the novel running, yes, but she also begins to occupy the position of someone who can interpret the world she serves. That is why she matters and why people get nervous about her. A servant who merely carries trays is easy to place. A servant who narrates starts looking structurally dangerous. She knows too much. Worse, she may know how to say it.\r\n\r\nThat does not make her free. I think class was exactly right to resist that temptation. Nelly is still speaking under compulsion, under class pressure, under Lockwood's boredom, under the need to appear loyal enough, reasonable enough, useful enough. She is not Harriet Jacobs. The stakes are not identical, and pretending otherwise would be sloppy. But Jacobs helped clarify the basic problem. Speech does not arrive outside power. It arrives inside it, warped by it, working through it, sometimes against it. Nelly's narration matters because it is neither pure truth nor mere service chatter. It is a compromised form, and that compromise is part of the meaning.\r\n\r\nThe Heathcliff question is still bugging me too, in a useful way. I do not think I want to nail him down as definitely this or that, because the text seems much more interested in what racial indeterminacy permits the social world to do with him. He can absorb multiple forms of suspicion at once. His darkness can mean different things in different mouths, and those meanings all help justify his degradation. That feels disturbingly modern, actually. People do not need precision in order to racialize someone. Vagueness often works better.\r\n\r\nI also think the class question about literature and leisure is going to keep bothering me for a while. Working people appear in literature constantly, but the conditions of writing, preserving, publishing, and canonizing literature have historically belonged to people with more time and more insulation from necessity. That does not mean working class people have no forms. Of course they do. Poetry, song, oral forms, religious speech, vernacular tradition, all of it. But it does mean that when a servant enters the novel as narrator, I should pay attention. Something unusual is happening. Even if the novel still tries to absorb that speech back into service, the fact that it has to do so suggests a pressure point.\r\n\r\nSo I suppose what I am left with after this class is a version of suspicion, but a productive one. When Nelly speaks, I do not want to ask, \"Is she reliable?\" and then check a box like some exhausted AP Lit grader. I want to ask what conditions make this speech possible, what conditions deform it, what she has to sound like in order to be heard, and what the novel can only let her say sideways. Harriet Jacobs makes that question impossible to forget. Once you have seen a woman's story weaponized the instant she tells it, it gets harder to believe that any structurally subordinate speaker in literature is simply \"given a voice\" and then left alone with it.\r\n\r\nAnd then, selfishly, I am excited because Heathcliff has now entered the book in exactly the right way, which is to say in a way that makes everything messier. Reminds me of the good ol' Brown days. Good. Clean novels are usually lying (not that messy ones don't - \"all novels do is lie!\").",
  "journal-entry-april-7": "A class about framing, voice, and who gets to own a story. We began *The Confessions of Nat Turner* as a historical document that behaves like a Gothic text, then kept asking the more uncomfortable question: if every word on the page is written down by Thomas Gray, where, if anywhere, is Nat Turner still speaking?\r### Preparation\r\n\r\nI want to begin with the copyright.<annotation data-note=\"A pamphlet matters as a form because it sits between speech and print. It is public, fast, polemical, meant to circulate quickly, and often tied to urgent political moments rather than stable literary prestige.\" data-label=\"pamphlet note\"></annotation>\r\n\r\nThat sounds dry, which is unfair to it, because it is actually obscene. Before class, what kept bothering me was not only the fact that *The Confessions of Nat Turner* is framed by a white writer, Thomas Gray, but that Gray is not merely introducing the text or certifying it or doing the usual antebellum white-preface routine. He is asserting legal ownership over Nat Turner's words. That matters. It means that before we even get to Turner's \"confession,\" the text has already staged a familiar relation: white possession of black labor, now transferred from the field to language. Nat Turner is dead, and Gray still intends to make him work. That is ugly enough on its own. It also makes the whole pamphlet feel less like a neutral historical record and more like a struggle over who gets to turn revolt into narrative.\r\n\r\nI was also thinking about genre, because the class had apparently already decided that this was the only nonfiction work on the syllabus, and then immediately started making that category unstable. I liked that. The pamphlet is historical. Fine. It is also framed like a Gothic narrative, full of gloomy fanatics, dark bewildered minds, mysterious plots, blood, concealment, public terror, and the effort to restore order by identifying the villain. Thomas Gray wants the event to be legible in exactly that way. He wants Nat Turner to function as a kind of monster whose capture will allow slave society to sleep again. The problem, as I suspected before class and was glad to have confirmed in class, is that the text does not cooperate very well.\r\n\r\nAnd then there is Nat Turner's opening phrase, \"the right insurrection, as you call it.\"<annotation data-note=\"This phrase is tiny but important. Turner does not reject Gray's term directly. He marks it as Gray's term, which lets him signal a rival understanding without pretending he has equal power in the exchange.\" data-label=\"as you call it note\"></annotation> That \"as you call it\" was already doing more work than some whole paragraphs in lesser books. It does not openly refuse Gray's language. Turner cannot afford that. What it does is worse. It marks the term, tilts it, puts scare quotes around it without the quotation marks, and lets Gray know, very politely, that words are under dispute. I came into class thinking that if Turner is anywhere in this text, it will be in places like that: slight pressure, tonal shifts, the point where Gray's frame starts to creak.\r\n\r\nSo my main question was pretty simple. If Turner cannot write freely, cannot speak outside of Gray's transcription, and cannot openly declare the politics Gray most fears, how does he speak anyway?\r\n\r\n### In Class\r\n\r\nClass made the text feel much more alive and much more combative than I had expected.\r\n\r\nWe began with the outer frame: the pamphlet, the title page, the legal apparatus, the address \"to the public.\" One of the first important points was that this \"public\" is not some universal reading community floating above history. It is a white, literate, slaveholding public whose world has just been violently interrupted by rebellion. Gray is writing to reassure that public. Or that is what he says he is doing. He presents himself as offering the explanation they need, the motives, the hidden workings of Nat Turner's mind, the knowledge that will let them put terror back in its box. That is the official story. The unofficial one is that Gray needs money, wants to sell the pamphlet, and knows perfectly well that fear is good for business. A calm and peaceful public does not buy much. A terrified one might.\r\n\r\nThe Gothic language of Gray's preface mattered a lot. \"A gloomy fanatic\" revolving schemes in the recesses of his own dark, bewildered mind is not the language of neutral documentation. It is the language of villain-construction. It turns revolt into pathology. It turns politics into psychic deformity. And it was useful to hear class connect this to the broader entanglement of Gothic fiction with plantation slavery. Harriet Jacobs has to keep insisting that her actual life is not a Gothic novel precisely because the real violence of slavery had already been half-aestheticized by that fictional mode. Here Gray reverses the process. He uses Gothic language to contain a historical insurrection. He wants Nat Turner to be scary in a way that is finally manageable. Catch the monster, close the book, restore the plantation. That seems to be the fantasy.\r\n\r\nThen we got to the beginning of the confession itself, and the whole thing became more interesting immediately. Gray says he did not question Turner at all, and Turner begins, \"Sir, you have asked me to give a history of the motives...\" Which is a beautiful little contradiction. Turner knows exactly what Gray wants. That recognition was one of the sharpest points in class. Of course he knows. He has lived as an enslaved person for thirty-one years. Knowing what white men want from you is not some optional extra. It is part of surviving them. Gray, by contrast, has far less idea what Turner wants. That asymmetry matters. Turner enters the text disadvantaged in every obvious way and still holds, at least at moments, the advantage of deeper social intelligence.\r\n\r\nThe phrase \"as you call it\" landed even harder once class slowed down over it. Turner does not reject Gray's word outright. He lets it stand and marks it as Gray's. That tiny grammatical move creates a second vocabulary inside the first. The same thing happens with \"mind,\" which became almost the central contested word of the class. Gray wants Nat Turner's mind to be bewildered, confounded, corrupted by religion, trapped in things beyond its reach. Turner takes the word and does something else with it. \"To a mind like mine...\"<annotation data-note=\"Gray wants Turner's 'mind' to mean confusion, darkness, fanaticism. Turner takes the word back and uses it to describe observation, intelligence, memory, and historical consciousness.\" data-label=\"mind note\"></annotation> That sentence felt like a seizure of territory. Not a mind like yours thinks. A mind like mine. He is not merely describing his mind. He is reclaiming the category from the man trying to explain him away.\r\n\r\nI was especially struck by how quickly Turner historicizes himself. Gray wants interiority. Turner gives history. He does not begin with some abstract spiritual confusion. He begins with being born \"the property of Benjamin Turner.\" That sentence does a lot. It shifts motive from private derangement to a material social world. It reminds the reader that his mind did not develop in a vacuum, and that slavery is not background scenery but one of the conditions under which this consciousness became possible. It also cuts directly against Gray's thesis. A mind like Turner's is not simply lost in false religion. It is observant of everything passing. It notices the world. That insistence mattered to me because it kept religion from functioning as a stupid reduction. Turner does not deny religion. He denies that religion exhausts him.\r\n\r\nThen the scriptural language arrives, and the text changes register so sharply that it becomes difficult to believe Gray is still fully in control of what he is producing. Turner's speech begins to sound biblical rather than merely descriptive. Lights in the sky. Blood on the corn. Figures in the leaves. The Spirit speaking as it spoke to prophets in former days. I liked the point class made here that this is not just \"religious fanaticism\" in the dismissive sense Gray wants. It is prophetic language, and prophetic language carries political possibilities the white reading public would very much prefer black people not notice. Revelation here is not closed. Scripture is not simply a dead text to be interpreted safely under white supervision. God still speaks. Or at least Turner says so, and says it in a way that is difficult for Gray to flatten.\r\n\r\nThe comparison to Emerson and Joseph Smith was useful too, because it kept Turner from being trapped in a special category of black irrationality. Claims of ongoing revelation were not unique to him. They were available within the religious atmosphere of the period. What makes Turner dangerous is not that he speaks the language of prophecy. It is where that prophecy goes. Gray wants religion to explain away the revolt. Turner uses religion to open revolt further. That felt to me like one of the central contests of the text.\r\n\r\nThe violence section was also more interesting than I expected, because Turner's narration of the killings is strangely antiheroic. He is not written as some perfectly efficient avenging machine. He hacks badly. The hatchet glances. The sword is dull. He gives weapons to stronger men. He places himself in the rear. At first I thought this would weaken him as a revolutionary figure, but class made a better point. It emphasizes that he is not selling us brute prowess. He is presenting himself as organizer, visionary, strategist, the mind of the revolt rather than its most physically imposing hand. That matters, especially against the racist stereotype of black revolt as mindless physical ferocity. The violence remains intimate, brutal, and terrifying. It also refuses the clean fantasy of the superhuman rebel.\r\n\r\nI liked the discussion of tools becoming weapons too. Axes, hatchets, swords, farm implements, all the ordinary objects of plantation labor can be turned. That seemed to be one of the deepest terrors of the revolt. Slave society depends on convincing itself that the people forced to use those objects will continue using them in the service of the master's world. Nat Turner's insurrection reveals that the whole material environment can reverse direction. The things built to sustain the plantation can enter the house as instruments of destruction. That point made the revolt feel less like an isolated outburst and more like a revelation of the permanent fragility of mastery.\r\n\r\nThen the ending. Gray tries very hard to gather himself, restate that Turner is a complete fanatic, and put the whole problem away. But he cannot quite manage it. He keeps describing Turner in contradictory terms. Gothic villain, yes. Also something very close to a romantic hero: manacled hands raised to heaven, spirit soaring above the attributes of man. That is not the language of a tidy monster. Nor is \"or plays his part most admirably.\"<annotation data-note=\"When Gray says Turner is either 'a complete fanatic' or 'plays his part most admirably,' he accidentally opens the possibility that Turner is using the language expected of him strategically rather than being simply trapped inside it.\" data-label=\"fanatic note\"></annotation> That sentence was probably the most interesting one in the whole class. If Turner is \"playing the part\" of fanatic, then Gray has accidentally admitted performance, strategy, mask, perhaps even authorship. Turner may be using the language expected of him while aiming it somewhere else. Gray cannot decide whether Turner is lost in delusion or terrifyingly in command of his effects. That uncertainty is where the text becomes worth reading.\r\n\r\n### Reflections\r\n\r\nWhat keeps staying with me is that Turner seems to understand framing better than Gray does.\r\n\r\nGray wants the pamphlet to function as containment. He captures Turner, captures his words, copyrights them, publishes them, explains them, sells them, and ideally returns the world to order. That is the project. The trouble is that Turner appears to know he is inside a frame and knows how to work against it. He does not blow it up dramatically. He leans on certain words, reclaims others, shifts registers, speaks in a mode Gray cannot fully master, and keeps historicizing the very mind Gray wants to isolate. The result is not freedom, obviously. He is still imprisoned, still condemned, still writing or speaking under absolute coercion. Yet something in the language exceeds the use Gray wants to make of it. That excess is probably the most interesting thing in the text.\r\n\r\nI also keep thinking about the word \"fanatic.\" Gray needs that word very badly. Slave society needs that word. A fanatic is singular, irrational, detached from material history, the kind of figure you can execute and then stop thinking about. A political actor is much more annoying. A political actor might be intelligible. Other people might think the same thoughts. Other revolts might follow. The revolt might have causes deeper than one deranged religious imagination. Turner seems aware of this. His answer about North Carolina, the one where he suggests that the same ideas and strange appearances might prompt others, is almost rude in its refusal to comfort the reader. Good. It should be.\r\n\r\nThe scriptural language matters to me for that reason too. Gray wants prophecy to read as confusion. Turner uses prophecy to widen the event. Once he aligns himself with prophets, with Christ, with an open field of revelation, he is doing more than justifying himself religiously. He is trying to create a different audience, maybe a black audience, maybe a future one, maybe anyone capable of hearing that execution by the state does not close a revolt if the language of the revolt survives. That seems to be what Gray accidentally helps him do. He prints the thing that should have been too dangerous to print.\r\n\r\nI was also struck by the strange dignity of Turner's self-presentation. He insists on his intelligence, his curiosity, his experiments, his ability to appear as he must appear, his public sense of greatness. There is something almost theatrical in it, though not fake. More like he understands that if you are going to be seen, you might as well decide something about how. That self-consciousness feels important. It pushes against the easy white fantasy that the enslaved are transparent, readable, exactly what they seem. Turner more or less says: I know how appearance works. That is a dangerous thing for a slave society to hear.\r\n\r\nSo I think what I am left with is less a neat \"interpretation\" than a problem of reading. We do not have Turner outside Gray's text. There is no clean access, no rescued authentic voice waiting behind the white transcription like some reward for patient readers. That would be too easy and too false. What we have instead is pressure. Accent. Contradiction. A language that turns slightly against itself. Gray trying to say fanatic and producing, against his own will, something closer to a political and prophetic intelligence. That seems to me the proper difficulty of the text. It does not let us know Turner comfortably. It also refuses to let Gray know him comfortably either.\r\n\r\nAnd maybe that is why the pamphlet was not especially reassuring, though reassurance is what it was supposedly for. Gray wants to close the revolt into one executed man and one confused mind. Turner keeps making it larger. More historical. More collective. More open. He is dead by the time the pamphlet appears, but the text still carries his desire to keep the thing unfinished. That is a nasty gift to leave behind. It is also, from Turner's perspective, probably the point.",
  "journal-entry-march-26": "A class about boxes and the things that slip them. We moved from Poe's theory of analysis in *Murders in the Rue Morgue* to the locked room, the broken nail, the clue as thread, and finally the orangutan, which turns the detective story into a much stranger question about what counts as human and why unreadable difference so quickly becomes criminal.\r### Preparation\r\n\r\nI want to begin with the box.\r\n\r\nThat is basically what this story keeps handing us. A box called \"analysis.\" A box called \"the human.\" A box called \"the room.\" A box called \"language.\" At first Poe seems almost laughably pleased with himself about it. We get pages on analysis before anyone is even murdered, and part of me wanted to say, yes, Edgar, very good, your detective is brilliant, now please proceed to the dead bodies. But the longer I sat with the opening, the less ornamental it seemed. Poe is trying to tell us that the murder cannot be solved until several boxes have been broken open, and also that the desire to keep those boxes intact is itself part of the problem.\r\n\r\nI was especially stuck on the distinction between calculation and analysis.<annotation data-note=\"Poe's distinction matters because calculation stays inside the visible field and the known rules, while analysis asks what the frame excludes. That is why Dupin can solve what the police cannot.\" data-label=\"analysis note\"></annotation> Calculation seems easy enough to understand. Rules, pieces, moves, the visible field, the next step. Analysis, at least as Poe and Dupin are trying to define it, has something more invasive about it. It does not merely observe the board. It goes after the player. It throws itself into the spirit of the opponent. That phrasing is so melodramatic that it becomes useful again. The point is that analysis is not a cool, detached activity here. It is excitatory. Bodily, even. Poe's opening compares the analyst to the strong man delighting in his muscles, which is one of those analogies that is silly until it starts doing real work. The mind in this story is not some clean little lantern floating above the body. It exults. It strains. It wants. It gets off on disentangling. That is a weird way to describe intellect. Also, unfortunately, a persuasive one.\r\n\r\nI also kept thinking about the locked room as a form. A locked room mystery always looks impossible first and mechanical second. You start with wonder, then you move to hinges. That shift interested me because the room only stays impossible as long as you accept the assumptions built into it. The door is locked, therefore no one escaped. The windows are nailed shut, therefore no one escaped. The voices heard were human, therefore the murderer was human. The witnesses disagree about the \"foreign\" voice, therefore the truth must lie somewhere among those languages. Every one of those conclusions feels sensible. Every one turns out to be a trap. So before class I was mostly wondering what kind of story solves a mystery by making your assumptions look provincial.\r\n\r\nAnd then there was the word *clue*, which in Poe is never just a clue because Poe will never let a word do one thing if it can do three and make you slightly miserable in the process. I knew there would be something there. I did not yet know it would turn into Ariadne's thread, the labyrinth, and a room becoming a maze. But once you see that possibility, it is hard to unsee. A locked room is only a locked room if you are still thinking like the room wants you to think.<annotation data-note=\"The older spelling means a ball of thread. In class this opened the story from a locked room into a labyrinth, with the clue functioning like Ariadne's thread, the thing that leads thought out of confusion.\" data-label=\"clue note\"></annotation>\r\n\r\n### In Class\r\n\r\nClass made the story feel both smarter and weirder, which is the best thing a class can do to Poe.\r\n\r\nWe started with the opening account of analysis, and the first useful point was that Poe cannot really describe \"mental features\" directly. He can only describe their effects. Analysis appears as symptom, style, posture, pleasure, excitement. It manifests itself. This mattered because it kept the mind from floating off into abstraction. The analyst is not a neutral machine of logic. He is a body having a certain kind of experience. He takes pleasure in disentangling the way the strong man takes pleasure in exertion. Dr. Cantrell's whole riff on the \"gym guy\" made this much funnier than it had any right to be, but the point held. Poe is joining mental and physical power rather than separating them. Thinking here is strenuous. It has a pulse. It even has, God help us, swagger.\r\n\r\nThat helped with the distinction between calculation and analysis. Chess, as the class framed it, remains largely inside the rules and inside the board. You observe the visible field, anticipate according to defined possibilities, and proceed from there. Whist matters to Poe because it requires more than that. You attend to what lies outside the formal arrangement. Gesture, hesitation, pressure, the opponent's habits, the field beyond the field. It is a game that teaches you how to read the frame instead of merely obeying it. This became one of the central ideas of the hour. The analyst is valuable because he asks how the box was built and what the box excludes. That is true for games. It is true for disciplines. It is true for stories. It turns out to be very true for murders.\r\n\r\nThe section on Dupin and the narrator's life together in Paris was also more revealing than I had expected. They meet in a library, naturally, because everyone in Poe either meets in a library or should have. They move into a grotesque old house, shut out daylight, read strange books, then go wandering arm in arm through the gaslit city at night in search of mental excitement. That sentence, once class slowed down over it, became less quaint and more unsettling. They are not simply strolling. They are hunting contact with difficult minds. The city at night offers them an antagonistic intimacy with the dark, the criminal, the unreadable, and Dupin apparently finds this delightful. There is something a little indecent about how much pleasure he takes in the prospect of someone else's horror. I do not think Poe wants us to miss that.\r\n\r\nThen we got to the case itself. The newspaper provides the crime, which matters because the newspaper already belongs to the city's way of organizing anonymity. It distributes information, arranges events into a common field, makes urban chaos feel readable. The murder in the Rue Morgue is what exceeds that readability. The police are stuck because the room is locked, there is no obvious clue, and the witnesses agree only enough to deepen the confusion. Everyone hears a shrill voice. No one agrees on what language it is. This part of the discussion was especially sharp. Each witness identifies the language as something foreign, which sounds informative until you realize it is not information at all. It is a confession of the hearer's own limit, but phrased as knowledge about the voice. I do not know this language becomes this was Italian, Spanish, German, whatever. Ignorance gets projected outward and suddenly hardens into classification. Poe seems to enjoy watching that happen.<annotation data-note=\"The witnesses do not actually identify a language they know. They identify the voice as other. The story uses that failure to show how quickly ignorance hardens into classification.\" data-label=\"voice note\"></annotation>\r\n\r\nThe locked room itself became much more interesting once class turned from the room to the clue. If the murderer escaped materially, then the answer has to be material too. So Dupin compares the two windows, finds the difference, and arrives at the broken nail. Or, rather, the decapitated nail, which is exactly the sort of grotesque little joke Poe likes hiding in plain sight. The important thing was not simply that the nail reveals the means of escape. It is that the nail becomes a *clew*, the older spelling that means a ball of thread. Suddenly the story opens sideways into Theseus and the Minotaur. A locked room becomes a labyrinth. The clue is what lets you find your way out. I loved that turn because it made the detective story feel older and stranger than realism usually allows. The problem is not merely who did it. The problem is how to think without getting lost inside the shape of the problem itself.\r\n\r\nThe leap to the orangutan was the point where the story either snaps into place or offends you enough to become newly interesting. The police remain trapped because they assume the murderer must be human. Once Dupin allows the possibility of a nonhuman perpetrator, the room starts opening. The hair is wrong for a human. The strength is wrong for a human. The voices are wrong because the shrill voice is not really a language anyone there knows at all. It only sounded \"foreign\" because it was being forced into the binary of my language and the other language. That was one of the strongest ideas from class. The witnesses are not hearing a foreign language. They are hearing something outside the category they already know how to process, and instead of admitting that, they convert the unknown into the foreign. It is a very human move. Also a very stupid one.\r\n\r\nWhat class kept pressing, though, was that the orangutan does more than solve the crime. It breaks the human box. Or at least cracks it. The animal in the story imitates shaving, gets overstimulated, acts violently, panics, flees. This is not \"reason\" in the polished bourgeois sense, certainly. But it is not blank irrationality either. More importantly, Dupin can think his way into that action because, as class argued, he can make contact with the animal point within the human. That sounds melodramatic until you realize the alternative is worse: a human definition so fragile it can only sustain itself by pretending its own animality is somewhere else. Poe seems unwilling to grant that comfort. The human and the animal do not stand cleanly apart here. The detective solves the crime because he is less committed than the police are to the fantasy that they do.\r\n\r\nThe brief turn at the end to Ariadne in the maze was useful too. It could have felt random, but it didn't. Once the room had become a labyrinth through the clue, the myth was already there. Ariadne's thread provides egress from disorientation. The room works similarly. The problem is not the physical impossibility of leaving. It is the mind's inability to see the path because its assumptions keep circling back on themselves. A labyrinth traps by confusing self-direction. That feels exactly right for this story. Dupin's triumph is not magical perception. It is a willingness to stop honoring the wrong constraints.\r\n\r\n### Reflections\r\n\r\nWhat stayed with me most is how much of this story depends on the criminalization of what cannot be placed.\r\n\r\nThe witnesses hear a sound they cannot identify and call it foreign. The police find evidence that does not fit the human frame and ignore or misread it. The room appears impossible because everyone keeps insisting on a human scale, a human strength, a human voice, a human motive. In each case, the mind protects itself by forcing anomaly back into an existing category. The story's difficulty lies in the fact that the categories are bad. Or not bad exactly. Too small. The locked room only holds because thought is locked first.\r\n\r\nThis makes Dupin less comforting to me than he is sometimes supposed to be. He is brilliant, yes. He is also creepy. He enjoys this too much. He wants the excitation of entering another mind, even an antagonistic one. The opening told us that already, though I did not entirely believe it until class. Analysis here is not pure reason serenely illuminating truth. It is a craving. A strength. A performance of mastery. The detective and the murderer are not identical, obviously. Still, the story keeps them close enough that I do not entirely trust the pleasure of the solution. Dupin wins by being willing to inhabit a logic more bestial than the police will allow themselves to imagine. That is impressive. It is also not a wholly clean victory.\r\n\r\nI also keep thinking about the old problem of identity and action. Class kept returning to it through the orangutan and through the nineteenth century's growing habit of classifying criminal minds as atavistic or bestial. Poe seems to be writing right on the edge of that shift. The story wants to ask what sort of creature commits the crime. Then it gives an answer that makes the question worse. Once the murderer is an orangutan, the issue is no longer just who did it. The issue becomes what kind of difference we think separates human from animal, criminal from noncriminal, intelligible from unintelligible. The orangutan is not a moral subject in the same way a murderer in a courtroom would be, but the story still uses it to expose how fragile our species vanity is. One shaved razor and suddenly civilization looks less secure than advertised.\r\n\r\nThe clue-thread-labyrinth complex is probably what I like most, though. It takes the detective story, which can sometimes pretend to be all neatness and puts it back in contact with older mythic structures of getting lost. You do not solve the maze by being very sure of yourself. You solve it by following the right thread and by recognizing that the problem you are inside has shape. That seems true well beyond Poe. It is true of research too, unfortunately. Half the time you are not lacking data. You are still trapped inside the wrong room.\r\n\r\nSo I think the real lesson of this class, or the one I want to keep, is that analysis depends on a certain willingness to insult your own assumptions. The police cannot solve the case because they keep honoring the human frame, the ordinary clue, the ordinary voice, the ordinary route of exit. Dupin solves it because he lets the room become a maze, the nail become a clue, the witness become evidence of ignorance, and the murderer become something outside the box the police had already built. That is irritatingly elegant. It is also, I suspect, why detective fiction was never really as tidy as it later pretended to be.",
  "journal-entry-march-24": "### Preparation\r\n\r\nI want to begin with the man who cannot be read.\r\n\r\nThat phrase was bothering me before class, partly because Poe is clearly baiting us with it. \"The Man of the Crowd\" is the title, and before anything really happens we are told about a text that \"does not permit itself to be read.\" Fine. Good. Very normal way to begin a story. The immediate effect, at least on me, is irritation, which I think is part of the design. Poe does this a lot. He opens with something that sounds gnomic, or fake-philosophical, or annoyingly abstract, and you think, oh great, here we go again, and then twenty minutes later the whole story is leaning on that first sentence like it knew what it was doing the entire time. Which, infuriatingly, it did.\r\n\r\nWhat interested me going in was the relation between unreadability and criminality. Why should failing to fit a system of classification feel threatening enough to become almost criminal by itself? Or maybe the better question is why the narrator seems so desperate to know people by sight in the first place. He sits in the coffeehouse, looks through the window, sorts the passersby into types, classes, ranks, professions, little urban species. That impulse feels familiar in a way I do not entirely like. You see someone, you want to know what they are. You want the face to tell you what the body means, where it belongs, whether it is safe. This is one of those habits that starts to sound practical until you realize how much violence is hiding in the wish to make everyone legible.\r\n\r\nI was also thinking about the structure of the story. Inside, then outside. Coffeehouse, then street. Spectator, then pursuer. The narrator begins with the luxury of framed looking. He has the window, the newspaper, the distance, the café's little arrangement of safety. Then he sees the old man and loses the frame. Or maybe the old man breaks it. Either way, once he goes out into the crowd he stops being merely a reader of the city and becomes part of the thing he wants to decode. I liked that in theory before class. I suspected it would get uglier in discussion. It did.\r\n\r\nAnd then there was the leftover Ligeia material still hanging around from last class, which mattered more than I first thought it would. The bridal chamber in *Ligeia* had already seemed bizarre to me, but once class started moving toward Orientalism,<annotation data-note=\"Here I mean the European habit of constructing 'the East' as fantasy, erotic spectacle, or civilizational opposite rather than as a set of real, internally diverse places and peoples. In Ligeia, that fantasy helps make her beauty seem racially and erotically exceptional.\" data-label=\"orientalism note\"></annotation> whiteness, \"white slavery,\" and the possibility that the whole room is effectively an apparatus for turning Rowena into Ligeia, it became harder to read that story as merely lush and weird. It is lush and weird, yes. It is also coercive. So I came into class wondering whether Poe's interiors and exteriors are actually doing related things. In one story a room tries to transform a woman. In the other a window tries to classify a city. Neither attempt goes well.\r\n\r\n### In Class\r\n\r\nClass began by returning to *Ligeia*, which turned out to be useful because it made the move into *The Man of the Crowd* feel less abrupt than it first seemed.\r\n\r\nThe starting point was that Ligeia's beauty had already been described through a whole apparatus of Orientalist fantasy: Persian eyes, Turkish houris, idolatrous Egypt, all the usual signs that a European narrator has stopped describing a woman and started importing a geography. Dr. Cantrell kept pressing the point that this is not random ornament. Ligeia is being racialized through desire. Her dark beauty becomes readable only through a set of imperial fantasies about \"the East,\" and that fantasy is what makes her seem more passionate, more excessive, more devoted than the women of \"our race.\" The language of love in the story is already racialized before the plot has even fully admitted it.\r\n\r\nThat mattered when we turned to Rowena and the bridal chamber. The room itself is one long imperial shopping list: Venice, India, Luxor, eastern candelabra, sarcophagi, curtains, ebony, all hauled into one interior and arranged around the blonde, blue-eyed Lady Rowena Trevanion. The point class kept making, and I think rightly, is that this room is not simply eccentric décor. It is an Orientalist chamber of transformation. He is trying to place Rowena inside the fantasy-world through which he understood Ligeia, as though the right objects, the right atmosphere, the right weird little death-scented room might somehow convert one woman into another. If you meet someone and they have a photo of their ex by the bed, that is already a problem. If they have rebuilt an entire transcontinental necro-fantasy in order to remake you in the image of their ex, that seems, technically speaking, worse.\r\n\r\nThe discussion of \"white slavery\" sharpened that. The narrator's remark about Rowena's family giving her up \"through thirst of gold\" begins to sound scandalous precisely because the scandal is not that women are bought and sold, which was perfectly true in the nineteenth century, but that a woman coded as white might be. The class made the ugly point very clearly: the supposed horror is selective. That selectivity matters because it reveals how whiteness and innocence are being protected through the story's outrage. It also made the chamber feel even worse from Rowena's point of view, a point of view the text barely allows to exist. She has been placed inside someone else's fantasy and then gets sick inside it. There are cleaner ways to say that. None of them are better.\r\n\r\nThe question of whether the narrator is actually poisoning her came up too, through the ruby drops in the wine, and that seemed to me one of Poe's especially nasty pleasures. A supernatural reading remains available if you want it. The story keeps it on the table. But the likelier possibility, or at least the one I find harder to shake, is that the narrator wants transformation badly enough to administer it himself while narrating the event in a way that distances him from his own act. I saw, or may have dreamed I saw. Poe's syntax is very good at making agency flicker just when it becomes uncomfortable.\r\n\r\nThen we turned to *The Man of the Crowd*, and suddenly everything became windows, newspapers, cafés, and types.\r\n\r\nThe first useful distinction was structural. The story divides between inside and outside, coffeehouse and street, fixed observation and restless pursuit. The narrator starts indoors, convalescent, reading the newspaper and watching the crowd through glass. That setup matters because the window does two things at once. It opens onto the world and frames it. He sees the city, but he sees it as spectacle. The people outside do not touch him, smell of anything, speak back, or disrupt his body. They are available to be sorted. That framed relation to the world is part of what he loses once he goes out after the old man.\r\n\r\nThe newspaper mattered too, more than I had expected. Dr. Cantrell pushed on it as an information technology that belongs to the rise of the city, the public sphere, and a new kind of collectivity. The newspaper lets people imagine themselves as inhabiting the same now. That seems obvious because it is so normal to us, but it also means that the narrator begins the story inside a form that already modularizes the world, arranges events spatially, distributes significance, and gives readers the feeling that the world is knowable because it has been laid out in columns. This was a useful lead-in to the story's obsession with classification. The narrator does with faces what the newspaper does with events. He arranges, sorts, identifies, puts the city into categories it might or might not deserve.\r\n\r\nThat classificatory impulse becomes clearest in the long sequence of urban types. He reads clothes, faces, gestures, class markers, and then as he descends the scale his language changes. The upper classes get attire and manner. Lower down, the body starts taking the burden of meaning: complexion, lips, eyes, filmy dimness, swarthiness, all of it. The story begins looking uncomfortably like physiognomy,<annotation data-note=\"A nineteenth-century 'science' that claimed faces and bodies could reveal moral and social truth. The narrator of The Man of the Crowd behaves like a physiognomist until he meets the old man who breaks the system.\" data-label=\"physiognomy note\"></annotation> and class named that directly. Physiognomy, phrenology, all those nineteenth-century \"sciences\" of reading persons by visible traits, are hovering behind the narrator's confidence that a face can disclose a being. He thinks he can read the crowd because the city has made faces into a legible text. Then Poe gives him the one face that breaks the system.\r\n\r\nThe old man matters because he does not fit the types. That is what produces the narrator's \"craving desire\" to keep him in view. Class was very good on the grammar here. \"Then came a craving desire\" displaces the self. The narrator does not simply decide to follow. Desire arrives, and it arrives as something that overcomes him before he can name it. That made the pursuit feel less like curiosity and more like compulsion. He has encountered an anomaly, and the anomaly threatens the whole classificatory order by which the city had been made manageable. If the old man cannot be placed, then the system is weaker than the narrator thought, and perhaps the narrator is weaker too.\r\n\r\nFrom there class moved into the criminal. That was where the story got much stranger. The old man is unreadable, and the narrator's response is effectively to criminalize opacity. He becomes \"the type and genius of deep crime\" not because the narrator sees him committing anything, but because he refuses placement. He does not go home. He does not settle into a recognizable type. He keeps moving. That movement led to the discussion of vagrancy laws,<annotation data-note=\"Important because it helps explain how unreadability can become criminality. Vagrancy laws often punished being 'out of place' without clearly defining what that meant, leaving enormous discretion to police and magistrates.\" data-label=\"vagrancy note\"></annotation> and how \"vagrancy\" can function as a crime of being out of place rather than of doing any one particular act. I found that especially striking because it made the old man's crime look like pure failure of legibility. He is criminal because the city's reader cannot read him. That is one of those moments where literature stops feeling old very quickly.\r\n\r\nThe final turn I liked most was the idea that by the end the narrator has become a man of the crowd too. He follows the old man all night hoping the old man will finally enter some place that makes him interpretable, but the old man keeps moving, and the narrator keeps moving after him, and the line between object and pursuer starts to get muddy. Meanwhile we as readers are following the narrator the same way, trying to get the secret from him that he cannot get from the old man. So the story ends by implicating everyone in the desire to know what perhaps cannot be known, or ought not be. That seems like the sort of joke Poe enjoys making at our expense.\r\n\r\n### Reflections\r\n\r\nWhat I keep coming back to is the violence of legibility.\r\n\r\nThat sounds overblown until you look at what these stories are actually doing. In *Ligeia*, the narrator tries to make a woman legible to his own desire by translating her into Orientalist fantasy, then tries to make another woman legible to that fantasy by placing her inside a room that should, apparently, do the work of conversion for him. In *The Man of the Crowd*, the narrator tries to make the city legible by sorting faces into types, then tries to make the unreadable old man legible by following him until he yields a category. In both cases, interpretation is not innocent. It wants possession. It wants authority. It wants the relief of having the thing stay still long enough to mean one thing.\r\n\r\nThat is probably why the old man bothered me so much. He does not simply remain mysterious in some romantic, moonlit way. He remains socially unplaceable. And that unplaceability becomes intolerable enough that the narrator makes him criminal. There is something deeply ugly in that move and something very familiar. If you cannot classify a person, if you cannot decide what they are, whom they belong to, what their function is, what danger or utility they represent, then your ignorance starts looking like their offense. That is one of the story's nastiest insights. The unreadable person becomes the dangerous person because your system has no category for him and cannot bear the admission that the failure might belong to the system.\r\n\r\nI also keep thinking about the crowd as relief. That was one of the class ideas that felt true before I could fully explain it. The crowd is frightening in this story, yes, but it is also shelter. In the crowd you do not have to account for yourself in the same way. You can move, be moved, avoid full disclosure. The old man seems to need the crowd almost as a condition of survival, and maybe the narrator does too by the end. There was something in Dr. Cantrell's aside about moving from North Carolina into cities like Boston, New York, San Francisco, and finding relief from a certain pressure to confess oneself. That landed. The crowd can be a place of surveillance. It can also be a place where privacy survives by becoming impersonal. Which is maybe why the narrator's pursuit feels so invasive. He is trying to strip that impersonal cover from someone who may need it.\r\n\r\nThe other thing bothering me is that Poe seems increasingly interested in the point where perception becomes sensation. The narrator starts out perceiving. He sees the city from behind glass, comfortably, taxonomically. Then desire arrives, and the whole thing becomes bodily. He is jostled in the streets, drawn onward, awake all night, running on compulsion instead of detached interpretation. That shift feels important beyond this one story. It lines up with everything class was saying about the nineteenth century's crisis of the unified perceiving subject, the old confidence that the world stands over there and the mind calmly synthesizes it. Poe's world keeps undoing that calm. The seer gets dragged into what he sees.\r\n\r\nAnd maybe that is what links this story back to *Ligeia* after all. Both narrators want the world to present itself in a way that secures them. One wants the woman to stay inside the fantasy he has built around her. The other wants the city to stay readable. Neither gets what he wants. Rowena remains materially Rowena, with all the inconvenient horror that entails. The old man keeps walking. The unreadable thing refuses its category. Good for it.\r\n\r\nSo I suppose the question I am left with is not simply what the old man means. Poe is not going to give me that, and pretending otherwise would be embarrassing. The better question is why the narrator needs him to mean something so badly, and what kind of social world produces that need. A city of strangers. A culture of types. A science of faces. A law of vagrancy. A reader with too much confidence in his own gaze. That seems like enough to be getting on with.",
  "journal-entry-march-19": "### Preparation\r\n\r\nI want to begin with Poe's first phrase, because it is the sort of phrase that sounds simple until it starts breeding problems.\r\n\r\n\"A wild yet most homely narrative.\"<annotation data-note=\"This opening matters because it announces the Gothic problem immediately: violence enters through the household. The home becomes the place where the familiar turns feral, or where domestication itself starts to look violent.\" data-label=\"opening note\"></annotation>\r\n\r\nThat had been sitting in my head before class because the two words seem to pull against each other and also, annoyingly, to need each other. *Wild* gives you sensation, extremity, violation, the promise that something in the story will slip the leash. *Homely* gives you the house, the wife, the pet, the domestic scene, the furniture among which one is apparently supposed to feel safe. Put them together and you get the basic Gothic proposition: the thing that will undo you is already indoors. This is bad news for everyone in the house, especially the cat.\r\n\r\nI was also interested in the fact that *The Black Cat* begins like a confession but a very slippery one. The narrator tells us he is not mad, which is never reassuring. He tells us he will state the facts plainly, succinctly, without comment, which is already a lie by the time he finishes saying it. He says he only wants to unburden his soul, which may be true, though it is hard to tell whether he wants relief, absolution, admiration for his honesty, or company in his badness. Confession is supposed to clear things up. Poe's version seems designed to make everything murkier.\r\n\r\nThen there was the second paragraph, which kept bothering me more than the eye-gouging part, honestly. The narrator tells us he has always been known for his docility and humanity, and his evidence is that he loved animals. Fine. But once he starts describing what he loves about them, the whole thing curdles. He loves their \"unselfish and self-sacrificing\" affection.<annotation data-note=\"The phrase sounds sweet for about three seconds. Then it reveals the narrator's ideal relation to others: they should love him without asserting much selfhood of their own. The cat bite matters because it breaks that fantasy.\" data-label=\"love note\"></annotation> That is a very ugly sentence if you look at it too long. Or not too long, really. It means he loves animals because they do not get in the way of his own selfhood. They depend on him. They adore him. They apparently do not insist on being selves in the room with him. That is one of those preferences that should probably disqualify a person from intimate life, though Poe's narrator does not seem to know that.\r\n\r\nAnd then *Ligeia*, because class was moving there too. What I had from that story, going in, was mostly eyes. Her eyes, specifically, and the narrator's extravagant inability to describe them without dragging half the Eastern Mediterranean into the room. Persian eyes, Turkish women, idolatrous Egypt, all of it. I could already tell that Poe was not simply saying \"she has dark eyes.\" He was constructing her as exotic, and then getting weirdly religious about how much he liked it. Which is a very old male hobby, and not an innocent one.\r\n\r\nSo before class I had three questions. First, what kind of confession is *The Black Cat* actually giving us? Second, what sort of love needs its object to be self-sacrificing? Third, why does *Ligeia* sound so much like a love story and so much like a colonial fantasy at the same time?\r\n\r\n### In Class\r\n\r\nClass made Poe look more deliberate and more deranged, which feels appropriate.\r\n\r\nWe started with the opening of *The Black Cat*, and Dr. Cantrell kept pushing on that first phrase, \"wild yet most homely.\" The point was not just that Poe is setting up a spooky domestic tale. It was that the sentence already announces a relation between the household and the violent, between ordinary life and something psychologically uncontained. The home is not a refuge here. It is the setting in which the wild gets either domesticated or, more likely, fails to stay domesticated and starts biting things. That seems obvious now, but I had not realized how much the first line was doing.\r\n\r\nThe bigger question was tone. What does the narrator want from us? That ended up being harder than I expected. He claims he will simply put down the facts. He claims he will not explain them. He claims he is sane. None of this lasts more than a paragraph. So what are we supposed to do with a narrator who seems both eager to confess and eager to manipulate the terms of confession before it has even begun? Dr. Cantrell brought in the legal question here, which I liked a lot: what makes a confession admissible? What counts as voluntary? Once you start thinking through confession in relation to coercion, free will, Miranda rights, the Fifth Amendment, and the law's fantasy of \"an essentially free and unconstrained choice,\" the whole story starts to look stranger. This man is certainly speaking under constraint. He is about to die. He is writing from within punishment. His \"plain\" confession is already crowded with desire, self-defense, distortion, and whatever else a person feels the night before execution. So even before the cat shows up, the story is making trouble for the very category of confession.\r\n\r\nThen we turned to the narrator's evidence for his own humanity, and this was where the story got meaner. He says he loved animals. He says he derived happiness and pleasure from feeding and caressing them. Fine. But when he explains why he values them, he reveals much more than he means to. He loves their \"unselfish and self-sacrificing love,\" which is to say he loves beings that love him without insisting on their own independent wants. That phrase became even uglier once class put it next to his marriage. He moves from pets to wife with a weird smoothness, as if domestic relations all run on the same logic. His wife has \"a disposition not uncongenial with my own,\" which is maybe the coldest possible way to discover matrimonial compatibility. The cats get the language of feeling. The wife gets a polite double negative. That felt revealing in a way Poe would probably enjoy.\r\n\r\nThe cat bite mattered because it exposed the limit of the narrator's love. The cat bites him out of fright, out of self-preservation. That small act of selfhood becomes intolerable. Dr. Cantrell's reading here was that what the narrator cannot stand is precisely the emergence of a self where he had wanted pure dependence. The cat ceases to function as the fantasy object of unselfish devotion and instead becomes a living thing that wants not to be seized. That should not be controversial. For the narrator, it becomes the occasion for mutilation. Which tells us, fairly clearly, that his \"love\" was always hostile to the beloved's independence.\r\n\r\nThen came perverseness. I had remembered the word from reading the story, but class made it much more interesting. The narrator elevates perverseness into a whole anthropology. It is one of the primitive impulses of the human heart, he says, this desire to violate that which is law merely because it is law. That is a grand claim, and a conveniently flattering one if you are trying to turn your private brutality into a universal condition of humankind. Still, the idea is not stupid. It opens onto a theory of law, and class went there. Does law restrain a naturally violent human creature, in the Hobbesian sense? Does law itself generate transgression by existing as prohibition? Or is this just a drunken man dressing up cruelty in philosophical costume? Probably yes to at least one of those.\r\n\r\nThe part that hit hardest, though, was the turn to mastery and slavery. Dr. Cantrell put Poe's story next to George Fitzhugh and pro-slavery sociology, and the parallels were unpleasantly sharp. Fitzhugh's argument that reciprocal affection exists only in dependence, that men love wives, children, and slaves precisely because they are weak and dependent, suddenly made *The Black Cat* look much less like a random horror story and much more like a psychological anatomy of mastery. If your identity depends on other beings remaining dependent upon you, then any sign of selfhood in them becomes a threat. The cat bites. The wife intervenes. Violence follows. That reading made the story feel much larger and much nastier. The Black Cat is not \"about\" a cat in any simple way. The cat becomes a figure for any domesticated being whose dependence props up someone else's sense of self.\r\n\r\nThen class pivoted to *Ligeia*, which somehow took all the weirdness of Poe's gender politics and added Orientalism. We talked first about the narrator's failure to remember Ligeia's family name, which is suspicious in itself. He remembers the eyes, the hair, the emaciated body, the spiritualized beauty, the way she worshipped him; the name somehow vanishes. That selective memory felt less like romantic grief and more like suppression. Once Dr. Cantrell started unpacking the references to Persia, Turkey, Egypt, and the houris of Islamic fantasy as filtered through European Orientalism, the whole description of Ligeia's beauty became easier to read and much uglier.<annotation data-note=\"The references to Persia, Turkey, Egypt, and houris are not decorative exotica. They racialize and eroticize Ligeia by making her legible through European fantasies of the East. Her beauty is being constructed, not merely admired.\" data-label=\"ligeia note\"></annotation> She is being constructed as an Eastern woman, or at least as a woman whose desirability lies in being imagined through the East. Her darkness is eroticized because it is made foreign. Her eyes are not simply beautiful. They are imported beauty, fantasized beauty, book-learned beauty.\r\n\r\nThat mattered especially when the story turned to love. The narrator tells us Ligeia loved him with a devotion \"amounting to idolatry,\" which is one of those sentences that arrives pretending to flatter her and ends up saying much more about him. If her love is idolatrous, then he is the idol. Or something adjacent to a god. Class kept pressing that point, and rightly. The relation he wants is not companionship so much as worship. Then he says her love involved \"more than womanly abandonment,\" which is an extraordinary phrase. More than womanly according to whom? Compared to which women? The implied answer seems to be: compared to the women of \"our race,\" the ordinary women of England who cannot match this exoticized, spiritualized, eroticized devotion. So Ligeia becomes racially marked precisely in order to become the fantasy of a woman who loves beyond ordinary womanhood. That is a sentence so bad it almost becomes impressive.\r\n\r\nWe also talked about emaciation, consumption, and the nineteenth century's grotesque aestheticization of dying women. That helped because Poe keeps trying to spiritualize female wasting. The woman fades. The flesh recedes. The ideal gleams through. Everyone is supposed to find this beautiful instead of horrifying. Which, to be fair, the nineteenth century often did. But class made clear how violent that idealization is. The more the woman loses material life, the more perfect she becomes as image. That is not love. That is a very elaborate form of disappearance.\r\n\r\n### Reflections\r\n\r\nWhat ties these two stories together for me, more than cats, dead women, or Poe's usual excess, is possession.\r\n\r\nIn *The Black Cat*, the narrator wants beings who love him by not having too much self. The pet is ideal as long as it is dependent, affectionate, self-sacrificing. The wife is acceptable as long as her disposition remains \"not uncongenial\" and, more importantly, not obstructive. The instant another being acts like a being and not a reflection, violence enters. That seems to me the story's ugliest and clearest point. His love is premised on the other's managed dependence. Selfhood shows up as threat.\r\n\r\nIn *Ligeia*, the structure is stranger but not, I think, fundamentally different. Here the beloved is not reduced through domestic possession so much as elevated into aesthetic and racial fantasy. She becomes foreign, mysterious, dark, spiritually intense, more than womanly, idolatrous in devotion. Which sounds extravagant and romantic until you realize that each of those terms removes her from ordinary reciprocity. She does not have to be a person in the full, inconvenient sense. She gets to be the impossible woman who worships. That worship makes him larger. When she dies, he loses not only her but the version of himself that her devotion sustained. No wonder he cannot stop talking about her. He has lost an audience for his own divinity.\r\n\r\nSo I keep thinking that both stories are less about love than about control under the sign of love. Poe's narrators speak the language of affection all the time. They practically drown in it. Yet in both cases the affection turns out to require a distorted relation to the other. The cat must not bite. The wife must not intervene. Ligeia must adore. She must adore in a way ordinary women cannot. She must also, conveniently, become less bodily as she does so. This is the sort of male fantasy that looks ornate on the page and rotten once you translate it into plain English.\r\n\r\nThe legal frame around *The Black Cat* has also stuck with me. Confession usually promises truth. This confession promises access to a man's mind and instead gives us a sequence of explanations, evasions, and universal theories deployed exactly when he needs them most. Alcohol. Perverseness. Fate. Household events. One starts to see confession not as the stripping away of rhetoric but as the place where rhetoric becomes most desperate. The narrator wants us to believe he is telling all. He is telling us plenty. The trouble is that what he tells reveals him sideways.\r\n\r\nI also cannot shake the racial part of *Ligeia*. The story's whole economy of beauty depends on making her different from \"our race,\" then eroticizing that difference while pretending it is simply aesthetic appreciation. The references to Persia, Turkey, Egypt, all of that, are doing way too much work to be decorative. They turn her into a fantasy assembled out of imperial reading habits. Even the inability to remember her surname starts to look less romantic and more suspicious. He remembers exactly the parts of her that sustain the fantasy. The rest fades.\r\n\r\nAnd this leaves me with an annoying thought, which is usually how class is going when it is going well. Poe's narrators are often read as psychological wrecks, and they are. They are also social wrecks in very specific ways. Their madness is structured. Their desires are structured. Their fantasies of pets, wives, and exotic women do not come from nowhere. They come from worlds that train men to treat dependence as love, adoration as proof of worth, and difference as material for fantasy. Poe may have supported slave society in life. These stories, to my mind, keep staging the psychological rot required to inhabit that world and still call it affection.",
  "journal-entry-march-17": "### Preparation\r\n\r\nI want to begin with the ending, because endings are rarely content to stay at the end.\r\n\r\nWhat stayed with me before class was not Victor's death exactly, but the fact that after Victor dies, Walton steps in and immediately starts sounding like Victor. The creature appears, speaks again, and Walton's response is basically the same old routine: I will not hear you, you are hideous, you are evil, you are beneath address. Different man, same script. That bothered me, partly because it suggests the problem is larger than Victor's personal failure. Victor is not just a bad father, bad scientist, bad narrator, though he is impressively gifted in all three categories. He is also the local representative of a larger social reflex: see the creature, name him monster, absolve yourself.\r\n\r\nThat word *species* had also been sticking with me.<annotation data-note=\"Victor's language of species is a way of turning a created relation into a natural difference, which lets him dodge creatorly obligation.\" data-label=\"species note\"></annotation> Victor keeps insisting that the creature belongs to another species, which feels like one of those scientific descriptions that is not really descriptive at all. It is a moral maneuver dressed as classification. Once the creature becomes another species, Victor owes him nothing. No duty, no kinship, no reciprocity, no embarrassment, not even the basic decency of consistency. He can call him devil, demon, fiend, wretch, and those names do the work of canceling obligation. The whole thing has the feel of a very old trick. Rename someone until responsibility no longer adheres.\r\n\r\nBut what interested me most was the creature's position at the end. He is still speaking. More than that, he is speaking outside Victor's frame. During the central part of the novel, the creature's story reaches us through Victor's narration as recorded by Walton. At the end, after Victor dies, the creature addresses Walton directly and reminds him that Frankenstein's story could not possibly include the hours and months of misery he endured. That line matters. He is not simply defending himself. He is contesting the structure of narration itself. You know one story, he says. Not mine. That is already more than self-justification. It is an attack on the authority of the whole book.\r\n\r\nSo before class I was mostly thinking about two questions. First, what does it mean that Walton turns out to be so easy to recruit into Victor's vocabulary? Second, what does it mean that the creature escapes, not only physically into the polar outside, but narratively, out of Victor's account and even, in some sense, out of the book's ability to contain him?\r\n\r\n### In Class\r\n\r\nClass made the ending stranger, which I appreciate in endings.\r\n\r\nWe started with Walton's response to the creature after Victor's death, and the key point was how little Walton actually learns. Victor dies, the creature appears, begins to speak in grief and anguish, and Walton more or less picks up Victor's script without revision. He calls him ugly, horrible, monstrous, and resists hearing him. The creature, meanwhile, does what he has been doing all novel long: reasons. Even now, even after murder, revenge, desolation, and the complete collapse of any hope for happiness, he is still trying to explain. Walton is not interested. Or not interested enough. Which is worse, probably. He wants the moral comfort of Victor's story intact.\r\n\r\nThat point mattered because it made Victor's failure look systemic rather than idiosyncratic. If Walton, supposedly a different kind of man, immediately reproduces Victor's way of seeing, then the issue is not just Victor's individual cruelty. It is a whole structure of interpretation. The creature appears and human beings begin naming rather than listening. They classify. They condemn. They restore their own innocence by relocating evil into the body in front of them. Victor does it. Walton does it. Society does it. At some point the pattern stops being accidental and starts becoming the novel's subject.\r\n\r\nDr. Cantrell kept returning to the creature's final speech to Walton, especially the line where the creature says that in Victor's tale of \"my crimes and his misfortunes,\" Victor could not sum up the months of misery he endured. That line almost feels like the creature stepping outside the novel and objecting to literary form itself. Victor's story is not false exactly. It is worse than false. It is insufficient. It presents Victor's suffering as suffering and the creature's suffering as background radiation, something continuous and therefore easy to ignore. The creature's complaint is not only moral but narratological. He is protesting the terms on which he has been represented.\r\n\r\nThat led to one of the most interesting ideas from class, which was that Shelley gives the creature the last real word. Victor gets to narrate for most of the novel, but he does not get final mastery. The creature returns after Victor's death and speaks again, not to be pardoned, not even really to be understood in any full sense, but to rupture Victor's exoneration of himself. Victor wants his story to end with his own suffering. Shelley refuses him that convenience. The creature speaks once more and reminds everyone, including us, that Victor's innocence has always depended on refusing to narrate responsibility as responsibility.\r\n\r\nThen the discussion moved into the creature's escape, which I had not been thinking about strongly enough. He does not die onstage. He promises some kind of disappearance, maybe death, maybe self-immolation, maybe simply departure, and then he goes out into the polar night. The point class kept pressing was that this matters because he escapes the frame. He escapes Victor's narrative. He escapes Walton's attempt to pin him down. He escapes the book's own interior system of explanation. That outside is unnerving because it leaves open the possibility that the creature exceeds every story told about him. He cannot be fully stabilized as villain, victim, devil, revolutionary, child, slave, or double. He takes pieces from all of those and then walks off.\r\n\r\nDick Gregory came in here, and I was glad he did. His reading of Frankenstein as a parable of life in the ghetto, a monster created by white society and then feared when it turns back upon its creator, made clear how portable the novel becomes once the creature is understood as historically made rather than metaphysically evil. That seems to me one of the reasons the text survives adaptation, distortion, and simplification so stubbornly. It is a novel about created misery. Once you understand that enslaved people, ghettos, racial categories, legal classes, all of these are social creations rather than natural facts, the creature becomes available as a figure through which later histories can think themselves. He is not found in nature. He is made. That distinction keeps echoing.\r\n\r\nThen we watched the 1910 film, which was fascinating mostly because of how hard it works to get rid of the creature's claims. The film does not want his story. It wants him as figure, as bad conscience, as visible evil, as the ugly externalization of something in Victor that must then be purified. The creature is reduced to a product of an evil mind. That already feels like a betrayal of the novel, but the betrayal is instructive. The film cannot afford the creature's speech. Once the creature starts reasoning, the moral arrangement becomes unstable. So the film strips him down. He becomes spectacle. He gets no real interiority. He gets no long education through language and books and social desire. He becomes something closer to a symptom.\r\n\r\nThe class discussion of the mirror scene was probably my favorite part. The creature sees himself in the mirror and is horrified. Later he disappears into the mirror, allowing Victor to see himself as himself again and proceed toward marriage, domesticity, heterosexual restoration, whatever clean name one wants to give that ending. The point was not simply that the mirror reflects an evil inner self. That would be too easy. The more interesting argument was that the mirror is social. It reflects not truth but the truth society permits. The creature in the mirror becomes the image of male desire, male relation, or male interiority rendered monstrous through social judgment. Once that image disappears, Victor is free to assume the acceptable self again. The film's ending begins to look less like resolution than repression with better lighting.<annotation data-note=\"In the 1910 film, the mirror seems to reflect a socially acceptable self by casting the creature as the monstrous form that must disappear before Victor can be restored to normality.\" data-label=\"mirror note\"></annotation>\r\n\r\nThat discussion moved, inevitably, toward the relation between Victor and the creature in the film, which is weird enough that trying to make it not weird only makes it weirder. The creature reaches toward Victor. Appears in his room. Hides behind curtains. Comes back on the wedding night. The captions insist on Elizabeth, jealousy, true love, all of that, but visually the film keeps returning to scenes between men that it does not quite know how to metabolize. One student said the captions felt like the film applying heteronormativity after the fact, which seemed exactly right. The image says one thing, or at least opens one possibility. The captions rush in to tell us what we are really seeing, please do not panic, a woman will arrive shortly.\r\n\r\nI also liked the point that the early film is still close to theater. The gestures are broad. Everything is dramatic. Even the creature's evil is a little low-budget, which I mean affectionately (well as affectionate as you can be to a monster straight out of a 1900s horror film). He is a figure of horror with surprisingly unserious shoes. But that theatricality helps because it makes the repression visible. The film is not subtle. It is almost endearingly blunt about wanting natural love to drive out monstrous love, or social love, or misdirected love, or whatever it fears this relation between creator and creature might become if one looked too long. Which is why, of course, class kept looking.\r\n\r\n### Reflections\r\n\r\nWhat I keep coming back to is the creature's refusal to remain where the novel puts him.\r\n\r\nThat sounds obvious. He moves around a lot. He kills people. He flees into the ice. Fine. But I mean something narrower. He refuses the meanings assigned to him, even when those meanings have immense institutional force behind them. Victor calls him species, demon, devil, fiend, and all the rest. Walton tries to do the same. The film reduces him to an evil projection. Later adaptations, class suggested, keep trying either to engage or flee his claims. Yet the creature keeps returning as something more troublesome than a villain. He wants a hearing. He wants an account of justice. He wants to narrate his own suffering. He wants, at the end, even his revenge to be understood as emerging from misery rather than from pure metaphysical wickedness. He is, in other words, infuriatingly legible.\r\n\r\nAnd that is why the ending matters so much. If the creature simply died nobly or terribly in front of Walton, then Walton could seal the story back up. Victor tragic. Creature awful. Everyone frozen. Instead the creature speaks, Walton fails him, and then the creature exits into an outside the text cannot master. That outside matters because it breaks the fantasy that narrative can settle the moral account. It cannot. Victor's version is not enough. Walton's version is not enough. The film's version is not enough. Something remains uncontained. Good. It should.\r\n\r\nThe mirror scene in the film kept bothering me after class for a related reason. A mirror is supposed to show. That is its whole job. Yet the more we talked, the less it seemed to be showing truth and the more it seemed to be enforcing social legibility. The creature in the mirror is what must be repudiated in order for Victor to become marriageable, readable, normal. That seems to me the film's real work. Not simply to tell a story about evil, but to reassure its audience that evil can be separated out, made visible, cast off, and replaced by the correct social self. The novel is much meaner than that. The novel suggests that what is disavowed does not vanish. It talks back. It kills. It returns at the bedside and at the end of the book and says, more or less, you still have not understood what you made.\r\n\r\nI am also struck by how often the creature's relation to others is treated as the problem rather than the condition produced by others. Victor abandons him and then blames him for solitude. Society beats him back from every attempt at fellowship and then reads his rage as evidence of essence. Walton hears enough to know better and still chooses the easier vocabulary. This is why the word species bothered me before class and bothers me more now. Species is how Victor launders responsibility. It is the taxonomic form of bad conscience. If the creature is another species, then history disappears. Manufacture disappears. Obligation disappears. We are back in the comforting world where monsters simply are.\r\n\r\nDick Gregory's reading helps because it restores history to the monster. The ghetto is made. The racial order is made. Slavery is made. Monsters are made. None of that absolves violence. The creature murders a child. The ghetto burns. History is not tidy, and the wronged do not become innocent because they were wronged. But Gregory's point, as I understand it, is that one cannot look at the revenge of the made and pretend one is looking at nature. One is looking at return. That seems right to me, and it may be the most frightening thing in the novel. The creature is not some alien eruption. He is the creator's work come back with claims.\r\n\r\nSo I do not think the most interesting question at the end of Frankenstein is whether the creature is good or evil. That question starts to feel like bait. The better question is what kinds of narrative, legal, social, and visual systems are required to make him appear as pure evil in the first place. Victor does it with names. Walton does it with recoil. The 1910 film does it with captions, mirrors, and a determinedly heterosexual ending. Shelley does something else. She lets him speak. Worse for everyone involved, she lets him be compelling when he does.<annotation data-note=\"The creature's demand for a hearing never really goes away. Even in the final scene with Walton, he is still insisting that Victor's account cannot contain the misery that produced his crimes.\" data-label=\"ending note\"></annotation>",
  "journal-entry-march-12": "### Preparation\r\n\r\nI want to begin with a command.\r\n\r\n*Listen to me.*<annotation data-note=\"This is the creature's first real ethical demand. Before he asks for a companion, he asks for a hearing. The point is procedural justice: hear the case before pronouncing the sentence.\" data-label=\"listen note\"></annotation>\r\n\r\nThat is what the creature keeps asking for, and what Victor keeps refusing him. Not explanation. Not mercy, at first. Not even the female companion yet. First he wants a hearing. Which sounds modest enough until you realize how much is packed into it. To be heard is already to be admitted into some kind of moral world. Devils are not heard. Devils are denounced, exorcised, killed, or, if you are at a crossroads somewhere in the Mississippi Delta, possibly bargained with for guitar skills, which complicates the theology a bit. But generally speaking, once Victor says devil, demon, fiend, monster, the conversation is supposed to be over. That is what those words are for. They do not describe. They terminate.\r\n\r\nSo what interested me before class was not simply that the creature wants something from Victor, but that what he wants first is procedural. Hear me. Listen before you judge. Even the guilty, he says, are allowed by human laws to speak in their own defense. That line had been sitting in my head because it makes the creature sound, weirdly enough, more committed to justice than anyone else in the novel. Victor creates him and then refuses to hear him. The court condemns Justine. The priest bullies her into confession. Human law is bloody, yes, but at least it preserves, in theory, the possibility of a hearing. Victor cannot manage even that.\r\n\r\nI was also thinking about the creature's strange and almost embarrassing earnestness. He is so much less demonic than Victor wants him to be. He has clearly been preparing for this conversation. Victor arrives hurling the usual vocabulary of horror, and the creature, with an almost painful dignity, responds as though language still might work. That seemed important to me. Victor speaks in names. The creature speaks in arguments. Victor says devil. The creature says creator. Victor threatens. The creature reasons. The asymmetry is almost funny for a second, and then not funny at all.\r\n\r\nAnd then there is the word *equity*.<annotation data-note=\"The creature is asking for a remedy ordinary law cannot provide. He has already seen what 'human laws' do in Justine's case. His appeal is to a higher obligation owed by a creator to a creature, a justice beyond routine legal compensation.\" data-label=\"equity note\"></annotation> Not equality. Not revenge, exactly. Not compensation in any simple sense. The creature asks for a justice beyond ordinary law, because ordinary law cannot fix what has happened to him. The system that might try him is not built to remedy creatorly neglect, radical abandonment, or being stitched together, brought to sensation, and then told to go die in a ditch somewhere. This is not a normal grievance. Which is to say, unfortunately for Victor, this is not a case you can solve by pretending it is someone else's problem.\r\n\r\nSo before class I was mostly wondering what sort of claim the creature is actually making. Is he asking for love? For justice? For recognition? For happiness? For a wife? For all of them? And why is Victor so terrified of the claim the moment it begins to sound reasonable?\r\n\r\n### In Class\r\n\r\nClass made the creature seem at once more sympathetic and more dangerous, which is probably the point.\r\n\r\nWe began with Victor's first words to his creation, which are, unsurprisingly, terrible. Nothing paternal, nothing recognitional, certainly nothing like \"my son\" or even \"good heavens, what have I done.\" Just devil, monster, be gone, I'll crush you, all the greatest hits. It is almost comical how little imagination Victor has at the precise moment where imagination would matter most. He has managed to make a human being out of corpses and stolen anatomy, and now that the being is standing there talking back, his vocabulary contracts to the moral intelligence of an angry villager with a torch.\r\n\r\nThe creature, meanwhile, has been thinking. He says he expected this reception, which immediately makes Victor look even worse because it means the creature knows his creator better than the creator knows himself. What follows is not incoherent rage but argument. \"All men hate the wretched,\" he says. \"How then must I be hated, who am miserable beyond all living things?\" That line did a lot of work in class because it returned us to the misery and happiness binary that keeps organizing the novel. The creature is not merely saying that he feels bad. He is making a claim about social exclusion as the condition under which vice is produced. Make me happy, he says later, and I shall be virtuous. This is Enlightenment talk with teeth.\r\n\r\nThe important point, though, was that before he asks for a companion, he asks to be heard. \"Listen to me.\" Hear my tale. Judge after hearing. Do me at least the justice that human law extends to the guilty. That last part struck me because he is explicitly comparing Victor unfavorably to courts, and courts in this novel are not exactly shining beacons of justice. Justine has already shown us that. Still, the creature knows that even a bad system has procedures, however compromised, whereas Victor wants only repudiation. It turns out the creator is less just than the law.\r\n\r\nDr. Cantrell's distinction between justice and equity helped a lot here. I had been using those words a bit lazily, which is apparently a hobby of mine with important words. But the point was that equity refers to a form of remedy the ordinary law cannot supply. If a grievance can be compensated within the system, fine. Equity begins where the system itself has no adequate mechanism of repair. The creature knows perfectly well that no social institution can simply absorb him and redress his condition. He has watched Justine die. He has watched what human society does with innocence when class, fear, and law begin collaborating. So his appeal is not to society. It is to his creator, the one being supposedly above the ordinary terms of law because he is the origin of the injury in the first place. He asks, in effect, for creatorly equity. Which is a phrase I would never have invented on my own, but there it is.\r\n\r\nFrom there the argument turned toward *Paradise Lost*. The creature says he ought to have been Adam but is instead the fallen angel,<annotation data-note=\"The creature's point is not just that he feels like Satan. It is that he never had the chance to be Adam. He was excluded from joy before any fall, which makes Victor's abandonment harsher than a simple story of rebellion and punishment.\" data-label=\"adam note\"></annotation> and the class kept worrying that distinction in useful ways. Adam is created in likeness, placed in a world, given relation, given speech, given a garden, given at least the possibility of joy before loss. Satan is cast out. The creature's point is that he never even got Eden. He was excluded from joy before he could misdeed his way out of it. That seems essential. He is not saying, \"I was once happy and then I fell.\" He is saying, \"Paradise was never on the table.\" Which is much meaner, and maybe the novel's harshest point about Victor.\r\n\r\nThe chapter of the creature's \"education\" became much more interesting once class framed it not simply as a monster learning things, but as an origin story for society itself. Fire, food, weather, pain, shelter, language, sympathy, exclusion. He begins almost in pure sensation, which makes Victor's earlier description of the grinning, demonic infant look increasingly suspicious. The creature remembers a multiplicity of sensations. Victor remembers a ghastly grin. These are not the same event. Or rather they are, but they do not occupy the same moral universe. One thing I liked from class was the insistence that Shelley means for us to compare these accounts. The book does not merely move forward. It asks you to go back and realize that Victor has been narrating under the pressure of aversion all along.\r\n\r\nThe cottagers matter because they teach the creature two things at once: society and the lack of society. He learns what affection looks like by watching other people have it. He learns language by hearing people speak beautifully to one another. He learns what it means to desire companionship by discovering that companionship exists and that he is shut out from it. That felt especially cruel. It is one thing never to know a thing exists. It is another to watch it through a hole in the wall.\r\n\r\nAnd then the books. *Paradise Lost*, Plutarch, Volney. The reading list has always felt to me slightly absurd in the best gothic way. Of course the eight-foot abandoned creature in the woods gets a better humanities education than half the population. But class made that less silly and more politically charged. His reading is not just cultivation. It is alienation. The more he reads, the more he acquires frameworks for understanding descent, property, hierarchy, slavery, exclusion, and the less possible contentment becomes. He learns that human society values names, family, wealth, inheritance. He has none. He learns to ask \"Who was I? What was I? Whence did I come?\" and the answers, when they come, are awful.\r\n\r\nThe comparison to slave narrative was one of the most interesting parts of class. Not because the creature is \"really\" a racial allegory in any simple way, but because the language of creation, mastership, exclusion, agility, coarser diet, and legal unfreedom begins to resonate with abolitionist discourse in ways that are hard to ignore. The creature comes to consciousness through reading. So does Douglass. Knowledge becomes pain because it reveals a condition for which no immediate remedy exists. \"I had no money, no friends, no property,\" the creature says, and suddenly the novel is not only about monstrosity but about social death.\r\n\r\nThe De Lacey scene was, to me, still the cruelest part. The creature quite sensibly goes to the blind old man because blindness might suspend visual prejudice long enough for a hearing to occur. And for a moment it works. The old man listens. Which is all the creature wanted in the first place. Then Felix barges in, sees deformity, and the whole thing collapses back into violence. That sequence made Victor's later behavior even less defensible, because it shows that just hearing is possible. The problem is not that the creature cannot speak or cannot reason or cannot move sympathy. The problem is that sight keeps outrunning judgment.\r\n\r\nThen we got to the demand for a companion, and I liked that class did not treat it as self-evident. Why a female creature? Why does he imagine happiness heterosexually? The obvious answer is Adam and Eve, plus the cottagers, plus the social forms he has actually seen. Still, it was useful to ask the question and not let convention answer too quickly. The important thing, in any case, is that the creature defines happiness not as domination or revenge but as exchanged sympathies. He wants someone of the same species, the same deformity, the same condition, someone who can be miserable with him and therefore maybe less miserable. There is something almost embarrassingly tender in that. Victor, naturally, is horrified.\r\n\r\nOne of the best moments from class was the sentence on page 149 about Victor's change of feeling. Hearing the creature, he feels compassion and even a wish to console him. Seeing him, he recoils again. The sentence literally shifts registers. Voice produces sympathy. Sight produces disgust. It is such a naked admission that Victor's ethical failures are inseparable from the way he sees. Or fails to see. Once the creature becomes visible again, he ceases, in Victor's mind, to be a person with claims and becomes \"the filthy mass that moved and talked.\" That line made me angry in class and still does. \"Mass\" is what you call something when you are trying very hard not to call it someone.\r\n\r\n### Reflections\r\n\r\nWhat bothers me most now is how modest the creature's first demand really is.\r\n\r\nHe does not begin by asking Victor to love him. He does not even begin by asking for the companion. He begins by asking to be heard, which is such a low bar that Victor's refusal starts to look less like fear than like a commitment to injustice. The creature's first political claim is auditory. Listen. Hear the case. Suspend, for a second, the vocabularies that already have me dead on arrival. That seems to me one of the novel's hardest ethical questions: what does it mean to hear justly when every visible sign is trying to recruit you into disgust before judgment even begins?\r\n\r\nThis is where the De Lacey scene matters so much. Blindness is not ideal, obviously. I am not arguing for a legal system in which everyone is blindfolded and vibes their way through testimony. Still, the scene makes a devastating point. The old man can receive the creature as a voice before he receives him as a form, and that brief interval is enough to make justice imaginable. The problem is not that the creature is unintelligible. The problem is that social life trains people to see deformity as moral evidence. Once Felix sees him, the hearing ends. Maybe that is the whole problem in miniature.\r\n\r\nI also keep thinking about how much the creature's education resembles a curse. That sounds dramatic, but he practically says so. He learns language, history, property, social attachment, books, religion, all the symbolic machinery by which human beings make a world, and the result is not flourishing but a more articulate misery. He does not merely suffer. He learns what he lacks. That distinction matters. An animal may feel pain. The creature acquires grievance. He becomes able to narrate exclusion as exclusion. That is a political education whether Victor likes it or not.\r\n\r\nThe comparison to slave narrative keeps lingering too, partly because it helps explain why the creature's knowledge turns so quickly from sorrow toward vengeance. This is not because knowledge is bad. That would be a very boring moral, and Shelley is not boring in that way. It is because knowledge without remedy curdles. \"Make me happy, and I shall be virtuous\" sounds almost naive on first reading, but I think it is a serious claim. Misery is not just a private feeling in this novel. It is a condition socially produced and then moralized. Society makes monsters and then congratulates itself for identifying them.\r\n\r\nThat may be why Victor's eventual partial concession feels so weak. He admits there is justice in the creature's argument. He feels compassion. He even wishes to console him. And yet all of that remains catastrophically unstable because it depends on not looking too hard. The moment sight returns, so does revulsion. In other words, Victor's ethics are aesthetic. If the creature looked different, the whole novel would be different. That is a nasty thought, but the text keeps earning it.\r\n\r\nWhat I cannot quite shake, though, is the creature's insistence on relation. He is so much less satanic than Victor's vocabulary would permit. Even when he invokes Satan, he does so because Satan at least has a story for exclusion. He wants to be Adam, or at least something adjacent to Adam, something created into relation rather than expelled into solitude. He wants hearing, sympathy, companionship, and finally some place in the world where his existence is not automatically an injury to others. These are not demonic desires. They are, annoyingly for Victor, human ones.\r\n\r\nSo perhaps the most uncomfortable thing about this section is that the creature's demand is not extravagant. It is reasonable. That is what makes it frightening. If he were only a fiend, Victor could keep shouting and we could all go home morally satisfied. But he is intelligible. He has arguments. He has read Milton. He has watched human beings love one another and wants in. Which leaves the novel asking not whether monsters can speak, but what happens when they speak better than the people who made them.",
  "journal-entry-march-10": "### Preparation\r\n\r\nI want to begin with a sentence that is doing more work than Victor seems to know.\r\n\r\nHe says he pursued nature to her hiding places.<annotation data-note=\"This line matters because it makes scientific inquiry sound gendered, secretive, and violent all at once. The phrasing is not innocent. Nature is feminized, hidden, and imagined as something a male investigator forces into disclosure.\" data-label=\"nature note\"></annotation>\r\n\r\nThat line had been bothering me before class, partly because it sounds so natural in the nineteenth century that it is easy not to stop for it at all. Of course nature is \"her.\" Of course scientific discovery can be described as pursuit. Of course truth is something hidden, veiled, withdrawn, waiting for the properly determined man to force it into visibility. None of this is neutral. The sentence is already crowded with assumptions about gender, knowledge, secrecy, and power. Victor wants to know where life comes from, yes, but he does not imagine that question as patient study within a shared world. He imagines it as penetration, seizure, access to what has been hidden from others. The grammar is practically panting. Maybe leering.\r\n\r\nI was also thinking about time again, because the last class on the mills made it hard not to notice how Victor's labor in the laboratory resembles industrial time. Two years pass. Seasons pass. His family passes, in a sense, out of the frame. He tells us there is summer outside, then harvest, then whatever comes next, and none of it matters because he is in the workshop. So the question I came in with was not just what Victor discovers, but what kind of space his discovery requires. What has to be excluded in order for this form of scientific work to become possible? The obvious answers are family, domestic affection, ordinary obligations, sleep, the body's own reluctance. But there is also something else being excluded, something like reverence. Not superstition, necessarily. Something harder to name, and probably more important.\r\n\r\nI was struck, too, by the sheer weirdness of his method. If his question is whence life proceeds, then his answer is to go to death. He studies corpses, graves, charnel houses, slaughterhouses. Only by recourse to death can he discover life. The reasoning is not exactly wrong. If mortality is the problem, then perhaps the border where life becomes death is where the answer must lie. Still, there is something awful in the calmness with which he enters the churchyard and insists that darkness had no effect on his fancy, that the graveyard is merely a repository of matter. Merely. As if bodies were ever only matter. As if the dead were not also the dead of someone. That \"merely\" does a lot of ugly work.\r\n\r\nSo before class I had a cluster of linked questions. What does Victor's science require him to kill off in himself before he animates anything else? Why is his research narrated through the suppression of feeling, relation, and memory? And why does the text keep making creation feel less like a triumph than like a long preparation for abandonment?\r\n\r\n### In Class\r\n\r\nClass sharpened all of that and made Victor look even worse, which I appreciated.\r\n\r\nWe began, unexpectedly but usefully, with research questions in general. Dr. Cantrell kept insisting that when we frame a question historically, we should know what we mean by history and not just toss around periods as if they were self-evident containers. The nineteenth century, for instance, is not a fact the way a desk is a fact. It is a construction, and the way you construct it changes the work you think you are doing. That sounds abstract, but it mattered. He kept pushing us to treat language critically, not as transparent delivery but as the thing that shapes thought in the first place. When you say \"magic girls,\" for instance, what history of girls and what history of magic are already colliding in that phrase? That point was broader than *Frankenstein*, but it ended up mattering a great deal for *Frankenstein*, because Victor's whole enterprise depends on words he does not interrogate: life, nature, creation, discovery. Big words, and suspicious ones.\r\n\r\nThen we turned to chapter four and to Victor's two years at the university, which now look less like diligent study and more like a program of self-mutilation. The lab is not just where he works. It is a space organized to cut him off from whatever might interrupt that work. We had just talked, in the previous class, about factory time severing labor from the rhythms of sun, moon, season, family, all the older temporalities that once constrained it, and Dr. Cantrell brought that back here. Victor's workshop functions similarly. Summer outside the window, harvest, the passage of seasons, letters from home, all of it becomes irrelevant to the scientific task. External nature does not enter. Internal nature does not enter either. He does not write home. He neglects those affections he elsewhere describes as the very conditions of his happy formation. He learns, in other words, how to amputate relation. That feels dramatic, but the chapter earns the drama.\r\n\r\nThat seemed to me the key move of the chapter. Not simply that he studies hard, or even obsessively, but that his science requires a systematic exclusion of domesticity, affection, reverence, grief, everything that might make the world feel inhabited rather than usable. The text makes this clearer than Victor does. He tells us his attention was fixed upon objects most insupportable to the delicacy of human feelings, and the sentence already stages the split. Human feeling becomes the impediment. The \"I\" that does science is produced through turning against that which would recoil. Dr. Cantrell pressed this point by asking us to look carefully at the syntax: \"my human nature\" recoils, while \"I\" keep working. The scientific self emerges through the suppression of human nature.<annotation data-note=\"Victor's narration splits the self in two: 'my human nature' recoils, while 'I' continue the work. The chapter suggests that his scientific identity is formed through suppressing those human capacities that would otherwise restrain him.\" data-label=\"scientific i note\"></annotation> That is a brutal sentence once you really sit with it. It is also, unfortunately, a very efficient one.\r\n\r\nThe discussion of corpses and churchyards developed that further. Victor prides himself on not being superstitious, not trembling in graveyards, not fearing spirits. But that is not really the issue. The problem is that he lacks reverence for the dead. A cemetery is not just material storage. It is memory. It is relation. It is where families place those they have loved, however imperfectly. Victor treats it as supply. One person in class pointed out that even modern medical schools often try, however sincerely or half sincerely, to rehumanize cadaver work through ceremonies of remembrance. That mattered because it clarified what Victor will not do. He wants knowledge without acknowledgment. He wants the body as material but not as someone's body. He wants life while bypassing every ordinary form of relation to the lives already lived.\r\n\r\nThat brought us back to the gender of \"nature.\" Dr. Cantrell asked us to imagine how strange the sentence would sound if Victor pursued nature to his hiding places. You would stop cold. Nobody writes that. Which is exactly the point. The feminization of nature passes as obvious, and so too does the violent structure of scientific desire that accompanies it. Waldman had already described scientific exploration in heroic terms earlier, but here that rhetoric gets much uglier. Secret toil. Hidden places. Penetration. Discovery as violation, or at least perilously close to it. Victor's scientific ambition begins to look less like neutral curiosity than like a masculinist fantasy of solitary access. That phrase sounds respectable until you look directly at it for five seconds.\r\n\r\nMary Shelley's own circumstances kept returning here, and I think rightly. The text is too preoccupied with creation, mothers, domesticity, birth, and abandonment for those questions to be merely accidental in a novel written by a young woman who had already known pregnancy, childbirth, grief, and the loss of her own mother. One does not need to reduce the novel to autobiography to see that Victor's attempt to create life while excluding women is not just scientifically audacious but conceptually grotesque. It is reproduction imagined as male sovereignty, a fantasy both absurd and durable.\r\n\r\nThen came the creature's animation, and Victor's reaction to it, which is somehow always more damning the more he narrates it. He assembles beautiful parts, he says. But the whole horrifies him. The eyes, especially. Or rather the fact that the eyes look back. He keeps trying to objectify them, to treat them as hideous surfaces, but the real issue seems to be reciprocity. The creature sees him. The creature addresses him. The creature reaches out. Victor cannot bear being called into relation by what he has made. He wants authorship without obligation, invention without response, creation without care. The creature's first crime is that it survives animation long enough to demand a creator.\r\n\r\nThe dream after that made the whole chapter darker. Victor kisses Elizabeth, she becomes his dead mother, the grave worms appear, the folds of the shroud return. That dream did not feel ornamental at all. It felt like the re-entry of everything he had tried to seal out of the laboratory: women, death, maternal loss, disgust, the body, grief, all of it rushing back once the fantasy of autonomous creation collapses. One student pointed out that the dream seems to connect his creation of life with the death of the women he loves, and that felt exactly right. Shelley may not be condemning \"playing God\" in the simple Sunday school sense. She may be condemning a form of creation that disavows dependence and leaves ruin where relation should have been. That is a much harsher accusation, and a better one.\r\n\r\nAnd then, because the novel never lets up, we moved to Justine. The evidence against her is almost insultingly thin: the locket, her being outside at night, bad luck, class position, the usual ingredients. What condemns her finally is not proof but confession, and even that confession is false. The priest besieges her into it. If she does not confess, he threatens excommunication and hell. So the confessor, ostensibly there to care for her soul, becomes an arm of the legal order. That part of class bothered me a lot. Justine is told so persistently that she is monstrous that she almost begins to believe it. The law, religion, and social hierarchy converge to make a victim narrate herself as guilty. Ugly work, and very efficient work.<annotation data-note=\"Important because it is not evidence of guilt but evidence of coercion. Religion here does not console the innocent. It helps produce a legal fiction in which the innocent person comes to name herself as guilty.\" data-label=\"justine note\"></annotation>\r\n\r\n### Reflections\r\n\r\nWhat I keep returning to is the relation between knowledge and desecration.\r\n\r\nThat may sound melodramatic. I do not mean that all knowledge is desecration, or that science is wicked, or some equally lazy conclusion. The text itself is more interesting than that. Victor's question is real. Mortality is a real problem. The desire to understand life, disease, generation, death, all of that, is not absurd. It is among the most human things imaginable. What the novel seems to ask, however, is what kind of self one becomes in pursuing such knowledge under the sign of mastery, privacy, and domination. What happens when knowing requires one to deaden exactly those capacities that would make the knowledge answerable to the world? That seems to be the issue. Not knowledge itself, but the sort of person this version of knowledge needs.\r\n\r\nVictor thinks his freedom from superstition is a mark of intellectual maturity. Maybe it is, partly. But the novel keeps suggesting that what he calls enlightenment is also a failure of reverence. He can walk through the graveyard without fear because he has converted the dead into matter. He can animate a body because he has already trained himself not to feel too much about bodies. He can create life because he has practiced disregarding lives. That seems to me the real horror of chapter four. His success is prepared by a long education in indifference. It is a phrase I wish were less reusable than it is.\r\n\r\nAnd that is why I do not think the novel's central problem is pride in the abstract, though Victor is certainly proud enough to be annoying. Pride is too clean a moral label. The deeper problem is abandonment built into the very fantasy of creation. Victor wants the generative power without the relational consequences. He wants what mothers do not get to want: the child without care, birth without dependency, authorship without obligation. The moment the creature looks at him, the fantasy collapses, because to create a being is to enter a relation one does not fully control. Victor recoils not because the creature is objectively monstrous, whatever that would mean, but because the creature exposes the lie that creation could ever have been solitary. He made a being, not a project. Beings answer back.\r\n\r\nThe Justine section made that more painful by widening the frame. Victor's science is one form of dehumanization. The court and the priest produce another. Justine is innocent, beautiful, beloved, and still perfectly disposable once the machinery of guilt begins to move. Her confession is extracted not through evidence but through terror and abandonment. No one supports her strongly enough to counter the structure arrayed against her. So the novel begins to look less like a story about one mad scientist and more like a story about institutions that turn living beings into things: corpses into materials, creatures into monsters, servants into criminals, women into functions, all by way of naming, or refusing to name rightly.\r\n\r\nI also cannot stop thinking about the line that a human being in perfection ought to preserve a calm and peaceful mind. Victor's father means it as wisdom, and perhaps it is wisdom of a sort. But the novel seems to know that tranquility, in practice, is often purchased by pushing disturbance onto someone else. Victor wants knowledge without disturbance. The court wants order without justice. The priest wants salvation without truth. Everyone wants cleanliness. Someone else gets buried in it. That sentence came to me a little too cleanly, which probably means it is true enough to keep and suspicious enough to watch.\r\n\r\nSo I do not think this class left me with a neat thesis, which is probably for the best. It left me with a harder question. What does it mean to pursue knowledge in a way that does not require the symbolic killing of relation first? Shelley does not reject inquiry. She rejects, I think, a form of inquiry that mistakes detachment for objectivity and domination for understanding. Victor learns how to overcome disgust, grief, memory, affection, even his own \"human nature.\" He calls that progress. The novel does not. Or if it does, it says the word with a grimace.",
  "journal-entry-march-5": "## March *5* | What Cannot Be Said, What Cannot Be Named\r\n\r\n### Preparation\r\n\r\nI want to begin with a word that sounds melodramatic enough to be useless.\r\n\r\n*Unspeakable.*<annotation data-note=\"Here I mean more than 'difficult to say.' The word matters because the class discussion kept pushing toward desires and identifications that the text cannot state openly, and so converts into silence, oath, panic, and indirection.\" data-label=\"unspeakable note\"></annotation>\r\n\r\nStill, that was the word I kept coming back to before class, partly because *The Vampyre* keeps circling a silence that feels larger than the literal oath Aubrey swears to Ruthven. Yes, he has promised not to speak. Fine. But promises do not usually work so well unless they fasten themselves to something already lodged in the person who makes them. That is what interested me. Why can Aubrey not speak? Not merely why does he not, but why does the story make his silence feel less like external compulsion than like the formal expression of some desire or identification he cannot bear to name.\r\n\r\nAt first the obvious answer seems to be his sister. Ruthven goes after Aubrey's sister. Aubrey cannot warn her. One could say the silence is tragic because it prevents him from protecting innocent femininity, which is certainly how the story wants to dress itself up. But I do not quite buy that, or at least I do not buy that as the deepest level of the problem. The women in the story are too obviously arranged as objects within a traffic among men. That sounds colder than I mean it, but the story is colder than it first appears. What interests it is not women in themselves, but the way men circulate value through women, attach themselves to one another through rivalry, imitation, violation, admiration, disgust, all of it. The question, then, is whether Aubrey desires Ruthven, or desires what Ruthven desires, or whether that distinction collapses the moment you try to make it too clean.<annotation data-note=\"A compact way of getting at mediated male desire. The issue is less 'who likes whom' than how desire circulates between men through a woman whose value is publicly constructed by masculine attention.\" data-label=\"desire note\"></annotation>\r\n\r\nAnd then, because class was already moving toward *Frankenstein*, I kept thinking about another word: *nameless.* Or maybe namelessness. That word does different work from unspeakable, but the two seem related. In Polidori, desire cannot say itself directly and so gets displaced into silence, oath, and female mediation. In Shelley, life itself seems to arrive through mediation, frames within frames, voices inside other voices, a creature whose speech we only receive through another's transcription, a being made by a man and then abandoned, a being with no name. The more I thought about it, the less that seemed accidental. What cannot be admitted is not merely hidden. It gets formalized. It enters the structure of the text.\r\n\r\nSo I came into class with two linked questions. First, what exactly is unspeakable in *The Vampyre*? Second, what does it mean that *Frankenstein* is a novel so preoccupied with creation and yet so haunted by mediation, absence, and namelessness? I had the sense that both texts were not simply \"about\" gothic excess, desire, monsters, whatever useful AP-Lit-ish noun we want to drag over them, but about the problem of relation itself: how desire attaches, how language fails, how life is made answerable or not made answerable at all.\r\n\r\n### In Class\r\n\r\nThe discussion of Aubrey and Ruthven made the word *unspeakable* feel less decorative and more exact.\r\n\r\nOne student asked, reasonably enough, why Aubrey does not simply break his promise. Ruthven is a vampire. The ordinary ethics of gentlemanly obligation would seem, at that point, somewhat outmatched. I appreciated the bluntness of the question. It clears away a lot of Victorian fog. And Dr. Cantrell's answer, or really the line of thinking he pushed us toward, was that the oath itself may not be the deepest barrier. There is no mechanical reason Aubrey cannot speak unless something in his will, or in his relation to Ruthven, interferes with that will's enactment. That shifts the issue immediately. The question stops being legal or supernatural and becomes psychological, maybe erotic, maybe social, probably all three at once.\r\n\r\nFrom there the whole thing turned on desire. Not in the easy sense of \"Aubrey likes Ruthven\" or \"Aubrey loves his sister\" or any single statement that would let the story settle. Rather, desire as triangular, displaced, shared. Dr. Cantrell returned to the fact that, within aristocratic masculine culture, women are valued not simply for themselves but through the way men value them. Their desirability is publicly constituted. A woman is desirable because men desire her. Which means that when two men \"desire\" the same woman, the woman may be mediating a desire between the men that can only appear safely in that form. I am aware this risks sounding too schematic. The story is messier than the theory. Still, the theory fits messily enough to matter. Miss Aubrey begins to look less like a center and more like a screen.\r\n\r\nThat raised the sharper question. Does Aubrey desire Ruthven, or does he desire what Ruthven desires? Again, maybe these are not different questions in the end. The point was not to force the story into some flattened identity category but to notice that Aubrey's inability to speak seems bound up with an inability to admit the nature of his relation to another man. Dr. Cantrell was careful here in a way I appreciated. To call this \"homosexual panic\" is only useful if one is very clear that such panic is not descriptive of queer people living their lives, but of straight masculinity's terror that its own identity may be less stable than it pretends.<annotation data-note=\"Used here in the narrow critical sense discussed in class: not fear felt by queer people, but anxiety within straight masculinity about its own instability, especially when male attachment threatens to exceed socially acceptable forms.\" data-label=\"homosexual panic note\"></annotation> That distinction matters. Otherwise the phrase becomes one more stupid academic shortcut.\r\n\r\nThen we lurched, productively, into *Frankenstein*. I say lurched because the transition felt abrupt at first, though by the end it did not. What linked the two discussions, at least for me, was mediation. In *Frankenstein*, as Dr. Cantrell pointed out, the speech we most want, the creature's own account of himself, comes to us through layers. Walton records Victor. Victor records the creature. The most urgent voice in the novel is not immediate. It is framed, transmitted, filtered. That seemed to me less like narrative convenience than like a theory of access. We do not get the creature whole. We get him by way of the structures that would contain or explain him.\r\n\r\nDr. Cantrell said he wanted us to think of the novel as advancing both a theory of science and a theory of education, which is not how *Frankenstein* is usually first handed to students, but it makes immediate sense once you hear it. The science part came through the historical controversies around life itself. Priestley, Lavoisier, the question of respiration, the extent to which life might be explained in material rather than divine terms, the debate between Abernethy and Lawrence over whether \"organization and function\" are enough or whether some vital principle beyond matter is required.<annotation data-note=\"The scientific dispute beneath Frankenstein: does life require some immaterial life force, or can it be explained through material organization and function alone? The novel emerges right in the middle of that argument.\" data-label=\"vitalism note\"></annotation> I liked that section because it made Victor's question, \"whence comes the principle of life,\" feel less like gothic thunder and more like an actual intellectual crisis in the early nineteenth century.\r\n\r\nGalvani showed up too, naturally, twitching frog legs and all. Volta as well. The point was not simply \"look, electricity, how spooky, now you understand the book.\" The point was that modern science emerges in the text not as pure secular clarity but as a field still shot through with theological residue, anxiety, and language it cannot quite purge. That seems right to me, and not only for the nineteenth century. Scientific writing is very often less scientific than it imagines itself to be, especially when it starts talking about bodies, women, reproduction, or whatever category it most wants to master. Science, like everyone else, has metaphors it pretends are not metaphors.\r\n\r\nBut the part that stayed with me most was Mary Shelley herself. Here \"biography\" stopped feeling like cheap literary gossip and started feeling structurally unavoidable. Shelley writing this novel as a teenage mother, after the death of her first baby, amid pregnancies, loss, and the public danger of appearing as an author at all. The first child nameless. The book first published anonymously. The creature nameless in the novel and even listed as \"------\" in the early theatrical adaptation. That is too much namelessness in too close a space to mean nothing. Nor did I find the point about Shelley's own name easy to shake: Mary Wollstonecraft Godwin Shelley, a self assembled out of maternal, paternal, and marital naming. A stitched name in a novel about assemblage. One need not become a crude biographical determinist to notice the pressure there.\r\n\r\nThis also sharpened the question of Victor's crime. Dr. Cantrell pushed against the lazy version, the one that says the novel condemns him mainly for \"playing God.\" Maybe. But maybe that is the more pious and therefore less interesting reading, especially in a text where God is not exactly available as an active explanatory presence. The stronger argument, I think, is that Victor's failure is abandonment. He creates, then recoils. He wants the triumph of making life without the obligation of relation. He wants production without care. That seems to me a much harsher and better indictment.\r\n\r\n### Reflections\r\n\r\nThe more I think about class, the more it seems to have been organized by forms of refusal.\r\n\r\nAubrey cannot speak. The creature cannot initially speak for himself without mediation. Shelley cannot safely publish under her own name. Victor creates and then refuses the responsibilities of creation. Even the scientific debates circling the novel are, at some level, refusals. A refusal to grant matter too much power. A refusal to concede that life may be material through and through. A refusal, maybe, to let women remain central to reproduction in a novel where a man tries to bypass them altogether. These are different refusals, obviously. Still, they seem to cluster.\r\n\r\nWhat I find most compelling in *The Vampyre* is that the story's real content may lie less in what it says than in what it arranges itself not to say. I do not mean that as a cheap \"read between the lines\" formula. I mean that the unspeakable enters the story as structure. Aubrey's silence is not an obstacle to meaning. It is meaning. The oath matters because it formalizes a prior incapacity. He cannot speak because the world of the story has made certain desires available only in displaced forms: rivalry, imitation, moral panic, the exchange of women, the whole tedious machinery of aristocratic manhood. Ruthven, in that sense, is not simply a villain with fangs. He is a figure for the social and erotic logic the story cannot admit in daylight.\r\n\r\nAnd then *Frankenstein* arrives and shifts the pressure from desire to care, or maybe to responsibility. I am tempted to say the novel asks what happens when life is produced outside ordinary structures of relation. That is true, but a little too easy. Better to say that the novel asks what kind of subject would desire creation without dependency, genesis without mothers, invention without obligation. Victor's fantasy is often described as intellectual ambition, and it is that. It is also, more disturbingly, a fantasy of pure authorship. To make a being and owe nothing. To generate life and then disown it once it looks back.\r\n\r\nMary Shelley's situation makes that fantasy impossible to read innocently. Again, I do not mean \"the novel means what happened to her.\" That is school essay nonsense. I mean that a woman who had undergone pregnancy, childbirth, loss, and the public risks of authorship was in a position to recognize, with unusual clarity, what kind of masculine dream Victor's project represents. It is not merely a dream of science. It is a dream of escaping the embodied, dependent, relational facts of human making. Which is to say, escaping women while retaining creation. No wonder the result is horror.\r\n\r\nI also cannot stop thinking about the namelessness. The creature has no name. Shelley's first child had no name. The novel first had no author's name. There is a kind of violence in namelessness, though not always the same kind. Sometimes it erases. Sometimes it protects. Sometimes it marks a subject the culture cannot yet receive except as dash, blank, circumlocution. A line. A gap. In that sense namelessness and unspeakability are cousins. Both mark the point at which relation breaks down, or is prohibited, or becomes too charged to enter ordinary language intact.\r\n\r\nWhat I want to hold onto from this class, then, is not a neat comparison between Polidori and Shelley, because that would flatten both. It is something narrower and stranger. Both texts seem to understand that what a culture cannot say directly it will force into form. Into oath. Into frame narrative. Into anonymous publication. Into a monster with no name. Into a gentleman who cannot speak because to speak would be to know what he wants. Into a scientist who calls his creation filthy the instant it demands recognition. The repressed, as always, is not silent. It is structural.\r\n\r\nThat seems worth remaining with. Uncomfortably.",
  "journal-entry-march-3": "### Preparation\r\n\r\nI want to begin with the light. Yes, I know. Painting of night, very perceptive. Still, that was what kept catching me before class, and I think for good reason. The painting seems organized by two kinds of illumination that are sharing a canvas and not much else. There is the moon above, dimmer but wider, touching the clouds, the hills, the path, the water, all the damp outer surfaces of the world. Then there is the light from the mill windows in the distance, smaller and more concentrated, but somehow ruder for being man-made. The moonlight diffuses. The mill light insists.<annotation data-note=\"The central visual contrast is between moonlight and mill light: one diffused across the landscape, the other concentrated within the factory windows.\" data-label=\"note 1\"></annotation>\r\n\r\nWhat bothered me, in the productive sense, was that the two lights do not simply differ in brightness. They imply different understandings of what night is *for*. Under the moon, night still feels like part of the world's own time. Under the mills, night begins to look like waste. Unused capacity. A thing to be entered, organized, maybe conquered. I did not have that language before class, but I had the feeling of it.<annotation data-note=\"A major question in class was what night becomes under industrial capitalism: no longer rest or limit, but unused capacity, time available for labor.\" data-label=\"note 2\"></annotation>\r\n\r\nAnd then the figure in the foreground. The bent man, the horse, the cart, that little bridge. My first impulse was to read him too cleanly, which is usually a sign that I am about to say something stupid. Nature, I thought. Or the preindustrial world. But that does not quite work. He is not \"nature.\" He is already inside labor, already inside roads, burdens, domesticated animals, the whole human rearrangement of the landscape. The question is not whether he belongs to culture. Obviously he does. The question is what kind of culture he belongs to, and what kind is arriving behind him in the form of those glowing mills.\r\n\r\nThe river also looked odd to me. Running low, or at least looking strained. I could not tell whether that was seasonal, compositional, or economic. Probably all three, which is annoying in the way good paintings are annoying. Nothing in the scene felt accidental. Not the distance of the factories, not the persistence of the moon, not the fact that the worker is outside the mill rather than neatly swallowed by it. The whole thing felt transitional, but not in the optimistic museum-plaque sense. More like one way of life lingering just long enough to watch another one declare itself inevitable.\r\n\r\nSo that was where I came into class: suspicious of the word progress, interested in the two lights, and not convinced that the figure in the foreground was there merely to provide picturesque melancholy for the mills to dominate.\r\n\r\n### In Class\r\n\r\nThe first thing that usefully complicated my reading was Dr. Cantrell's point about interpretation. Or really about intention. Trying to recover \"the\" intention of the painting, he suggested, can become a ghostly way of ending interpretation rather than beginning it. Better to work with hypotheses and test them against the details. Even the preposition matters. Does the factory emerge *from* the landscape? Stand *against* it? Advance *into* it? A whole argument can hide in that little word. Which is irritating, because it means grammar has opinions.<annotation data-note=\"Dr. Cantrell framed interpretation as hypothesis-testing rather than intention-recovery. Even prepositions matter because they quietly determine the relation between factory and landscape.\" data-label=\"note 3\"></annotation>\r\n\r\nOne student pointed out that both the moon and the buildings emit light, but only the moon actually seems to illuminate the surrounding scene. The clouds catch it. The hills catch it. The atmosphere itself catches it. The factory light does not really do that. It remains mostly within the windows, within the enclosure, as if it were less a light *of* the world than a light *for* a task. That distinction opened up the painting immediately. The moonlight belongs to a world. The mill light organizes a site.\r\n\r\nAnd then the line that stayed with me all class: there is a difference between moonlight and gaslight, and it may be a difference we have largely lost. That sounds a little dramatic until you realize it is also completely true. There is, apparently, a moon over Durham too. News to most of us. We have switches. We have screens. Night has been electrified so thoroughly that darkness no longer announces itself except as inconvenience. The old relation to evening, to dimness, to whatever other creatures are adjusting their eyes at twilight, has been flattened by indoor brightness. Again, I am very fond of not wandering through the dark by candlelight. Still. Something has been altered.<annotation data-note=\"Cantrell's point was that electrified modern life has altered our relation to evening itself. We no longer really inhabit darkness; we override it.\" data-label=\"note 4\"></annotation>\r\n\r\nThe discussion of the figure in the foreground got more interesting once the easy nature/culture binary was pushed aside. Dr. Cantrell said the person is not a figure of nature but of an earlier economic mode of production, which feels exactly right. He is closer to the natural world than the factory worker will be, but that is not the same as being outside history or labor. Someone else noted that the path seems almost to move away from the mill, when you would expect a composition like this to draw the eye and the figure toward the illuminated future. That observation mattered because it made the scene less triumphalist. The mills are there, yes. They are also at a distance. Their future has not yet fully absorbed the foreground. Not yet.\r\n\r\nThen the question turned, as it kept doing, toward sacrifice. What has to be sacrificed for this kind of progress? What does \"moving ahead\" even mean here? And from there we got enclosure, the destruction of common forms of life, the long historical process by which peasants and agricultural workers were pushed off the land and into wage labor.<annotation data-note=\"Enclosure refers to the long process by which common land was privatized, helping push peasants and agricultural workers away from subsistence and toward wage labor.\" data-label=\"note 5\"></annotation> Not through some cartoon villain conference where five men sit in a room and twirl their mustaches and decide to manufacture factory workers, but through the privatization of land, the disappearance of commons, the loss of local sustenance, the gradual making of a class with nothing to sell but labor. The man in the foreground began to look less like an individual and more like a threshold.\r\n\r\nMarx showed up at this point, which was inevitable. Factories tend to summon him.<annotation data-note=\"Marx matters here less as a slogan than as a thinker of labor time. The factory reorganizes work by detaching it from seasonal and lunar rhythms and subordinating it to the clock.\" data-label=\"note 6\"></annotation> The point that mattered most was that what is new here is not simply machinery. Water power is not the revelation. The revelation is a new relation between labor and time. Agricultural time is cyclical. It answers to season, weather, growth, harvest, periods of intense work followed by periods of relative slack. Capitalism, in Marx's account, has trouble taking full hold in that sort of temporal world because the earth refuses regularity. The factory solves that problem by creating an enclosed space in which labor can be detached from those rhythms. Inside the factory, the relation is no longer to moon or season but to the clock.\r\n\r\nThat made the painting much sharper for me. The mills are not merely objects in a landscape. They are engines for producing a new kind of time. Twelve-hour shifts. Child labor. Work severed from family, community, play, weather, night, all the older interruptions that once constrained it. Dr. Cantrell's examples from North Carolina textile mills made that history feel unpleasantly local. Workers once tended one machine. Then scientific management arrives, the \"stretch\" arrives, and workers are retrained to keep multiple machines going with abbreviated, efficient motions, as if the body were a badly designed attachment that needed optimization.<annotation data-note=\"Scientific management and 'the stretch' refer to the rationalization of labor: more machines per worker, more efficient motions, less slack, more output.\" data-label=\"note 7\"></annotation> Human beings are awkward, he said. We were not made to be machines. Capitalism took that less as an observation than as a design challenge.\r\n\r\n> \"Sleep is the last resistance to capitalism's fantasy of total productivity.\"<annotation data-note=\"This was one of the sharpest claims from class. Sleep appears as one of the last bodily interruptions to the fantasy of continuous productivity.\" data-label=\"note 8\"></annotation>\r\n\r\nAnd then, right near the end, the line I underlined twice: sleep as the last resistance to capitalism's fantasy of total productivity. That sounds a little grandiose until you look back at the painting and realize the night itself is already being drafted into service. The moon remains above the mills, but the factory no longer cares that night has come. Darkness no longer stops work. It has become another surface to be entered by light.\r\n\r\n### Reflections\r\n\r\nI keep returning to the word *progress*, mostly because the more class used it, the worse it sounded.\r\n\r\nThat is not because the old world was good. I do not want to turn the man in the foreground into some saint of agrarian authenticity, trudging nobly through the moonlight with his horse while evil industry glowers in the distance. That would be embarrassing. Rural labor is labor. It is exhausting, precarious, bodily punishing labor. But the painting does not ask for nostalgia. It asks, I think, for precision. And precision here means saying that industrial capitalism is not simply conquering nature. It is reorganizing temporality. That seems to me the deeper violence.\r\n\r\nThe moon remains. The hills remain. The river remains, though low and already being used. Nature is not gone. It has been subordinated. Its rhythms no longer determine the terms of labor. Seasonal time can continue existing beautifully in the background while losing all authority over the working day. That seems worse, in a way, than straightforward destruction. Destruction at least admits conflict. Subordination lets the old world remain visible as scenery while stripping it of jurisdiction.\r\n\r\nThat is why the factory light bothers me more than the factory itself. The buildings, taken alone, could be explained away as neutral structures, maybe even impressive ones. The light gives away the ambition. It says the night will no longer interrupt production. It says darkness has been made administratively irrelevant. I found myself thinking of the mill windows less as illumination than as a kind of argument. A proposal for how life should now be lived: regularized, continuous, detached from season, detached from the body's own sense of enough.\r\n\r\nAnd the figure in the foreground, bent over and outside, does not cancel that argument. He sharpens it. He is still in relation to the land in a way the factory worker will not be, but that relation already looks endangered, maybe already doomed. He is close enough to the mill for history to have reached him. That is what gives the painting its melancholy. The future is not abstract. It is right there, lit up with a confidence that feels, frankly, a little rude.\r\n\r\nI also cannot stop thinking about the category of laziness. Or inefficiency. Or desultory habits, to use the nicer industrial phrase. Those words always pretend to describe a deficiency in workers. What they often describe instead is refusal, bodily limit, interruption, the stubborn fact that human beings are not well designed for twelve hours of repetitive motion in service to somebody else's clock. The moral language attached to labor has always seemed suspicious to me, and class made it seem more so. Once \"progress\" becomes the reorganization of time for maximum extraction, then every remnant of older life gets redescribed as backwardness.\r\n\r\nSleep, then. It is hard not to end there, though I do not mean \"end\" in the neat sense. More like get cornered there. If sleep is the last resistance, as class suggested, that is both comforting and bleak. Comforting because the body still interrupts the machine. Bleak because even that interruption is now under pressure, folded into optimization discourse, sleep tracking, productivity advice, the whole cheerful campaign to make unconsciousness useful. We sleep, yes. But more and more we are asked to sleep efficiently, recover strategically, wake ready.\r\n\r\nSo maybe the question the painting leaves me with is not whether the moon survives the mill. It obviously does. The question is whether our relation to what the moon once organized survives it. Whether night can still mean anything other than deferred labor. Whether rest can still mean anything other than maintenance. The mills in the distance are beautiful enough to be dangerous. They glow. The sky still answers to another light. I do not think the painting lets us assume that the second one wins.\r\n\r\n*March 3. The moon remains. Jurisdiction does not.*"
};
